[edit] Centereach Boys Track

Centereach boys track is best known for there 158 dual meet winning streak beginning in 1972, under the leadership of Coach Burkley and Schneider. The team went 27 seasons undefeated. This streak ended in 1998, in a dual meet against Bay Shore High School. Due to many coach changes and declining numbers, the team since Coach Burkley's resignation had not been fairing well. But in the 2006 track season under the leadership of Coach Jason Strom, William Gilmartin, and Vincent Rucci the track team had made noticable improvment. Athlete numbers increased, and so did the skill of the athletes. Unfortunately it had also been decide that season the Centereach Track team would be combined with Newfield track team to form a new Middle Country track Team. Many in the board of education believed it would save money, and put money in other parts of the schools budget. But under futher analysis by the Centereach Track coaches it was discovered the combination of the teams would save very little money. Also combining the track teams would also severly cut the amount of students willing to compete on the Middle country track team. In an effort to save the Centereach Track team from the combination, the coaches and athletes created shirts spreading the word of their soon to be fate. And also attended a Board of Education meeting to speak out about the situation. The decision to combine the teams or not is still pending, but it is very likely that the teams will be combined.

DP Tha Mad Hatter (born Daniel Paul on October 17th, 1985) is an up & coming hip hop producer/artist from Mississauga, Ontario, Canada. He has written, produced, edited, mixed and performed a number of songs on the underground circuit in and around Toronto.

[edit] Lar Daly

Lawrence Joseph Sarsfield Daly (1912-1979), known as Lar Daly, fringe American politician who ran unsuccessfully for a variety of political offices (including President of the United States), often campaigning wearing an Uncle Sam suit.

Best known today for using the Federal Communications Commission's "Fairness Doctrine" to force radio and television news broadcasts to give him equal coverage with Chicago Mayor Richard J. Daley.

[edit] Sherwood Act

The Sherwood Act of May 11, 1912 was the first important pension law in the 20th century. It awarded pensions to all veterans. Veterans of the Mexican War and Union veterans of the Civil War could receive pensions automatically at age 62, regardless of disability.

[edit] Sources

http://www1.va.gov/opa/feature/history/docs/history1.pdf

[edit] Gealic College Pipe Band

The GCPB has been around forever in many different forms and whatnot. They are based out of St. Ann's, Cape Breton, Nova Scotia, Canada. They won the World Pipe Band Championship in Grade 3 in 1994. Under the direction of Pipe Major Bruce MacPhee. They are currently raising funds to head to the World Championships in Scotland this summer. They're selling tickets on a 2006 Harley Davidson Fat Boy Screamin' Eagle.

[edit] Islam is peace

It was stated by Voltaire, one of France’s greatest writers and philosophers, that “If God did not exist, it would be necessary to invent Him”(The Quotations). Religions played essential roles in any assemblage of people from the very beginning of life on this earth. For many people, religion is something that represents an individual’s faith and beliefs. However, in the ancient Islamic regulations, it is said that Islam is a way of living, with many teachings in all aspects of life. Islam originally is the religion that was sent to Prophet Mohammed (peace be upon him and his family) about 600 hundred years after Prophet Jesus (peace be upon him and his chaste mother). Islam regulations are based on Prophet Abraham’s (peace be upon him and his family) conventions. Muslims use the former peace expressions to show respect and gratitude to God’s prophets and messengers. Muslims believe that there is no God but Allah, and Mohammed is the last prophet which constructs the first pillar of Islam.

The Islam word in Arabic (إسلام) is derived from the word ‘salaam’, which means peace. It is required by all Muslims to greet each other by saying ‘Assalaam Alaikum’, which simply means: peace be with you. Islam’s perception of peace is unique. It is so, because Muslims pursue the peace and tranquility of worshiping Allah through the five daily prayers (towards Mecca) they practice; the peace that comes when somebody truly realizes the higher essence of these prayers. Therefore, having peace with oneself is easily attainable. And as a result of having peace with God and oneself, peace is spread between individuals in society and between nations.

Islam is a holy religion that was sent to people in the Middle East more than fourteen centuries ago to guide them from adoring idols to worshipping Allah, the Gracious the Merciful. Coming to systemize people’s lives, Islam’s guidelines clearly state Muslims’ duties and responsibilities toward God, themselves, and others. Thus, nothing was left undeclared for people to decide on by themselves. In fact, even bad-mouthing is forbidden, and is considered as a very big sin just like killing or torturing. Hence, Islam is not what is mistakenly known to some people in the Western world these days as the violence and terrorism foundation, especially after the September eleventh attacks on the World Trade Center. Conversely, Islam is the religion of peace and forgiveness that strictly prohibits any kind of violation to others’ privacies rather than killing innocent people or ruining others’ lives. Even animals’ slaughtering in Islam has a unique purpose not merely for the sake of torturing or killing. However, people must not pass judgments on entire races, nations, or religions based on irresponsible individual acts. That is primarily because individuals’ acts never reflect societies’ beliefs. Hence, neither Americans can judge Muslims based on the individual acts on September 11th attacks, nor Muslims can judge Americans by some careless group of soldiers regarding the Iraqi prisoners’ abuse problems for example. Recently, some of the issues misjudged and raised erroneously -for the lack of knowledge- against Islam are: the animal slaughtering, and the September 11th attacks.

Although Islam is the religion of mercy and compassion, and as most things in life, there must be some opponents, like Franklin Graham, who think that Islam is a religion that encourages violence. One sign of violence (the first issue) opponents find is that Muslims slaughter animals for food, which, they think, is a sign of killing passion in Islam. Those people think that slaughtering is a ruthless manner of torturing animals. They think that Muslims merely do it for the sake of torturing and killing. Therefore, these opponents think that the love of assassination is a genuine part of the Islamic culture.

However, a look into the guidelines of Islam is helpful at this stage to clarify the mystery people may have for the animal slaughtering rules in Islam. Muslims believe that Islam considers things as ‘Haram’, a way of forbidding something or making it illegal, because they harm us in a way or another. For example, drinking alcohol (an intoxicant) is Haram for many reasons. First, alcohol is proven scientifically to harm the stomach and make it gradually malfunction. Secondly, alcohol leads to the loss of brain cells and reduces the ability to think and speak, which is strongly unacceptable in Islam. It is unacceptable because when somebody loses his mind, it would let him commit sins and may lead him, while being drunk, to the thought of ‘Shirk’, the most severe and unforgivable sin which means associating partners with God, and that would obviously contradict the first pillar of Islam. On the other hand, Islam considers things as ‘Halal’, a way of permitting something or making it legal, if they were on contrary to Haram things; that is they do not do any damage to people. Therefore, legislating animals’ slaughtering is Halal because it has no side effects whether on people or animals, yet it is proven scientifically to be healthier than other ways. Besides, Islam is not the only religion that permits the use of animals for food as other religions do. (another article about animal slaughtering will be up soon)

The September 11th attacks (the second issue) made a very big impact against Islam in a dramatic way, in which it is the strongest criticism against Islam so far. In the United States, some people protested against Islam, relating it with terrorism and violence as a reaction of condemning the attacks. Such an impact was very clear in a survey sponsored by the Ethics & Public Policy Center that was published in Fall, 2002. That survey “was based on a national sample of leaders of Evangelical organizations” (Survey). The survey results were released to the public on April 7, 2003.

In the survey 72% of people thought that Islam opposes democracy. Plus, 70% thought that Islam is a religion of violence. 66% believed that Islam is dedicated to world domination. Sadly, 45% of people consider the war against terrorism is basically a war between the west and Islam. Unfortunately, only 10% thought that Islam is a religion of peace. Finally, 77% of people were unfavorable as their overall view of Islam. Furthermore, in a speech shortly after the September 11th attacks, Franklin Graham claimed that “Islam has attacked us… The God of Islam is not the same God… Islam is a very evil and wicked religion” (qtd. in Muscati 249).

However, Wahab Gharfarzoy states in his article “Islamic faith preaches peace, not violence” that “As a Muslim child growing up in a strictly Muslim country… I was taught that Allah…[is] God of the Universe, not only of the Muslims” which all Muslims agree on. Graham’s statement is strange because it is emotional and based on a personal judgment rather than an analytical thinking and true studying of Islam. It is weird how people judge entire nations or religions based on sole racism. Isn't it weird that when a Christian or a Jew kills someone, religion is not mentioned, but when a Muslim does so, it is Islam that goes to trial! Isn't it weird that when someone sacrifices himself for others, he is noble and well respected, but when a Palestinian does so to save his children from being killed, his wife form being raped, or his house from being destroyed, he is considered as a terrorist solely because he is Muslim! These are just few questions that Mr. Graham or any doubtful person may want to look at when accusing Islam even before spending sometime studying the traditions and regulations of Islam.

On the other hand, Muslims all over the world tend to understand this kind of disagreement because they know and feel the pain that Americans went through on September 2001. However, Americans must understand a few things before condemning Islam. Islam has nothing to do with individuals who claim they are Muslims because these individuals do un-Islamic deeds by killing innocent people. Bin Laden for example, the one who planed the attacks, is proven to be non-Muslim because throughout the years, he practiced many non-Islamic habits. First, in Afghanistan, where he and his gangs live, there were farms that were used for planting cannabis and drugs which is strictly forbidden in Islam for the same reasons alcohol is forbidden. Secondly, Bin Laden and his gangs in the al-Qaeda organization have been involved in many terror attacks in many Islamic countries such as Saudi Arabia and Yemen. Thirdly, killing innocent people on purpose is Haram to the extent that it is equal in Islam to ‘Shirk’. Hence, killing innocent people is a proof that Bin Laden is ‘Mushrik’, the person who does Shirk, and therefore he is not Muslim. Plus, how can somebody pretend that he is Muslim, and kill Muslims in Saudi Arabia and Yemen? And above all, why is Islam being blamed for non-Muslims’ deeds?

The day of the attacks on the World Trade Center, Muslims were shocked by the irresponsible acts by insane individuals. Those individuals who oppose the United States clearly created a misconception of the religion throughout the world. However, killing innocent people is totally rejected and Muslims feel sorry for those who lost their lives in that tragedy. Truly, Islam believes that people have the right to choose what believe and which faiths they practice and nobody can force them to choose his own believe and faith. In fact, even during Prophet Mohammad’s life and the ancient Islamic times, when Muslims were dominating and ruling almost all of the middle earth, Muslims were living with Christians, Jews, the ones who continued to worship idols, and all others in harmony, without any problems. It is important to consider that other religions’ origins are from the same God with basically the same principles, but different Prophets, languages, and set of rules suitable for that era. Therefore, Bin Laden can not force people to share his (non-Islamic) believes and faiths.


Nevertheless, resisting bad deeds is a natural trait that everybody should practice. Likewise, the attacks that happened on September 11, 2001, the current issues that have been raised in Iraq are unacceptable for all societies. Despite the fact of the Iraqi prisoners’ stories people have heard and the photos that were released to the public, the United States still has the gratitude on Iraqis by freeing them from the former criminal regime. The condemnations that were in the mass media by the American government are just a proof that these incidents were not meant or supposed to happen. Yet, the individuals who did these acts do not represent the U.S. values and reputation as a peaceful and manner-loving country. Consequently, Arabs must not oppose the U.S. as a nation but those individuals who did these faulty acts, which is an Islamic manner; that is a group should not be judged by the mistakes of individuals and the many should not be affected by the few.

Accordingly, Islam is the religion of forgiveness and mercy as Allah presents this in Quran: “God does not forbid you from showing kindness and dealing justly with those who have not fought you about religion and have not driven you out of your homes. God loves just dealers” (Quran, 60:8). Prophet Mohammed also has many sayings that enforce peace and oppose violence, such as, “…Do not betray, and do not be excessive…” Moreover, the Prophet said: “Whoever kills a person having a treaty with the Muslims shall not smell the fragrance of Paradise, though its fragrance is found for a span of forty years” (Islam Guide). Part of the Islamic culture is realizing that diversity is an advantage -because it promotes humans lives- and then, living with others in a simple and a wise way. Hence, misjudging and opposing others is not a healthy way of life especially when it gets to the extent of assassination, which is extremely disagreeable. Based upon the former arguments Islam is proven to be a peace-loving religion and in many ways similar to other religions’ guidelines. Islam has nothing to do with savagery but with peace and mercy.

[edit] Hall of Famer

Hall of Famer is a term used to describe one who has achieved the honor of being inducted into the Hall of Fame in a sport or other established field for unprecedented or outstanding achievement. Such athletes as Lou Gehrig, Larry Bird, and Joe Montana are all Hall of Famers and musicians such as Elvis is in the Rock n' Roll Hall of Fame. To a lesser extent, the term Hall of Famer is also used in an ironic sense to describe one who boasts feats worthy of the Hall of Fame, though their boasts are merely fabrications. For example, one who proclaims to have been an All-Star hockey player but fabricates pictures of the games may be called a Hall of Famer.

[edit] Sources

Thompson, Erich. Great Achievements. New York: Bantam, 1998.

24.174.91.13 21:34, 14 May 2006 (UTC)Peter Flemming

[edit] I-MO Christian Service Camp

I-MO Christian Service Camp is located southeast of Bloomfield Iowa, on Quinine Road. Each summer it offers week long camps (Sunday-Friday) for 5-12 graders, 3 day long camp for 3rd and 4th graders, a day long camp for 1st and 2nd graders, and 3-day (Friday-Sunday) camp for families. You can come to camp from when you are entering first grade through the summer after you graduate.

The camp offers 3 dorms, (boys, girls and faculty), a mess hall (cafeteria), chapel, swimming pool, 3 open-air shelters, 2 basketball courts (one half, one full), 2 tetherball courts, volleyball court, playground including monkey bars, loft, bars, 2 see-saws, and balance beam, sandbox, tire swing, 2 water fountains, softball field, campfire area, and rope swing.

Set in a rural area it has a lot of trees and is off a gravel road, very peaceful. Nearby towns are Stiles (mapdot), Pulaski, and Bloomfield.

Camp currently running: Last camp to run was Family Camp July 14-16. All weeks of camp are now over.

Don't forget to come next year and bring a friend. To all campers who attended there last week of camp this year, 2006; God be with you as you go through your life.

Come join the fun this summer!

Make sure to check back for 2007's summer schedule!

[edit] Target aquisition

The process of finding targets for artillery and aircraft bombardment. This includes the use of special forces with laser target designators and counterfire radar (that tracks the path of enemy shells back to the guns).

In summer 2006 Jan Nederveen Pieterse will teach the Global Studies Programme on "Theories of Globalization" at Freiburg University. Jan Nederveen Pieterse is Professor of sociology at University of Illinois Urbana-Champaign specializing in transnational sociology. His research interests include globalization, development studies and cultural studies. He taught at Institute of Social Studies in The Hague, in Ghana and United States, was visiting professor in Japan and Indonesia and is faculty member of the Graduate School of National College of Arts, Lahore. his book Globalization Empire looks at Globalization from historical sociological and anthropological perspectives.He believes in a multi-disciplinary approach to globalization and asserts it is an ongoing historical process that has accelarated in the contemporary period.

[edit] Alan Cork

Alan Cork was a striker who signed for Wimbledon FC in 1978, a fresh-faced 18 year old, coming from Derby County FC, were he had not impressed. "Corky", as he became affectionately known, was a huge fan's favourite at Plough Lane, and became the club's leading goalscorer in the league, scoring 149 goals in 413 appearances. His prowess in the air was legendary, there are few players in the history of the game better with their heads. He had a song named after him, as all West Bankers will know, which related to his balding pate. Corky played an hour of the FA Cup Final win in 1988, and no one in the team deserved a medal that day more than him. He had been through all four divisions and helped the Dons into the top-flight of English football.

He left he club in 1992 to rejoin former Manager Dave "Harry" Bassett at Sheffield United, and famously didn't shave until his team's FA Cup run had ended in 1993, at the semi-final at Wembley, at the hands of bitter rivals Wednesday.

It has been said that Alan Cork was a great player, but what was great about him, was that he never cost a penny. Indeed, during Alan's 15+ years as a professional, no transfer fee was ever paid for him.

To think there was no page devoted to him, is a travesty, now hopefully put right. If any other former West Bankers wish to add to it, they are most welcome.

[edit] Sources

"Wimbledon" from Southern League To Premiership, Clive Leatherdale, Desert Island Books. ISBN 1-874287-09-0

[edit] Harcum College

History of Harcum College

Edith Hatcher, daughter of prominent Virginia clergyman and educator Dr. William E. Hatcher, was a talented concert pianist. In 1913, Edith Hatcher married Octavius Marvin Harcum. After the birth of their first child, Edith wrote "the concert career did not offer a chance for family stability" so they chose a venture that would combine "my talents as an educator and artist and his business vision and ability." They opened the Harcum Post Graduate School on October 1, 1915, in Melville Hall, with three students and five pianos. Edith's goal was to "start a school where the individual talent of each girl would be treated as an integral part of her education." Though her expertise was in the fine arts, Edith was also committed to providing a strong academic program.



In its early years, Harcum was a preparatory school, giving students the skills needed for college study. It quickly grew, soon adding junior college-level courses. Soon, the "lower school" program was eliminated, and the junior college program was in place. Mr. Harcum, or "Uncle Marvin" as the students called him, was the first President. When he tragically died in a car accident in 1920, Edith assumed the Presidency. She remained in that post for more than 30 years with the exception of one academic year, 1946-1947, when Dr. John Barber served as President.

In addition to Edith, one of the most important women in Harcum's history is Maud L. Marren. Marren was appointed Dean of the College in 1920 and was a central figure on campus until she retired 43 years later.



The College grew steadily through the 1930s and 1940s with a student enrollment of 185 in 1948. However, Harcum was a proprietary institution and faced financial difficulties. In 1952, it could no longer run as a profitable enterprise; Edith declared bankruptcy.

The Junto Adult School was a non-profit educational corporation founded by Benjamin Franklin. It purchased the assets of Harcum for possible use as a residential college for adults but soon decided to continue Harcum's mission as a two-year college for women. Leadership was assumed by Mr. Philip Klein. In 1956, Pennsylvania granted Harcum permission to be the first junior college in the Commonwealth's history to confer the Associate of Arts and the Associate of Science degrees.

Tremendous building and expansion occurred in the 1960s under the direction of President Michael Duzy, with the addition of the Academic Center, Pennswood Hall, and Klein Hall. Five presidents have succeeded Dr. Duzy, yet the College's mission and purpose are essentially the same. In Mrs. Harcum's words, Harcum educates students in the arts and occupational skills, respecting each student as an "individual with personal needs, interests, aptitudes, and aspirations.


[edit] Sources

http://www.harcum.edu/about_harcum/history.html

Who is Felix Klaemont?
A self-taught guitar player / one man show from NW Washington (Bellingham). He started writing music the day after he got his first guitar, although it took some time for him to be able to sing the lyrics and play the guitar simultaneously. Currnetly, he is working on a Ph.d. with too little time to do enough with his music.

What has he done?
- 15 albums (working on No. 16)
- A few hundred songs recorded at home
- Lots of sore throats, broken strings, selfpity and small house concerts

Where has he lived?
1980-1998 - Bellingham, Washington
1998-1999 - Provo, Utah
1999-2001 - Romania and the Republic of Moldova
2001-2003 - Provo, Utah
Summer 2002 - Orange County, California
Summer 2003 - Tempe, Arizona
Winter/Spring/Summer 2004 - Tempe/Scottsdale, Arizona
2004-present - Lincoln, Nebraska

When did he do it?
4 albums worth of songs were written between 1996-1999 and recorded in the summer of 1999. From 1999-2001 he didn't touch a guitar (long story). Then, starting in the Fall of 2001, he started writing and recorded a new album every few months. Starting in 2004, the # of songs being written and recorded decreased dramatically. Currently, many ideas are being schemed and thought about, but little is being done. Life just gets too busy.

Why has he done it?
- Boredom
- A way to dramatize insignificant occurences in his life
- A only slightly successful attempt to get chicks

[edit] Alex Brown (musician)

Alex Brown is a guitarist, and general musician, from Louth, Lincolnshire.

While specialising in guitar, he also plays vox, bass, keyboard, harmonica, kazzoo, and drums.

He is a member of Edwards Theatre Company and has appeared in various productions with them. In 2005, he wrote the song for their production of Alan Bennett's Habeas Corpus, which was sung in front of thousands on the Royal Mile at the Edinburgh Fringe.

Recently, Alex has been studying English with Creative Writing at Nottingham Trent University.

[edit] Roberto Rexach Benítez

The tenth President of the Senate of Puerto Rico (1993-1996), has served as a member of Puerto Rico's House of Representatives under the Popular Democratic Party (PDP) and as a member of the Senate under the pro-statehood New Progressive Party (NPP). He has distinguished himself as a reformer of legislative processes and the author of many laws pertaining to education.

Prior to his legislative career, he was the first director of the University of Puerto Rico's Arecibo Regional College. He currently serves as an educational consultant and writes a weekly column for El Vocero, Puerto Rico's second most widely read daily newspaper. He lives in Hatillo, Puerto Rico with his wife, attorney Ada Urdaz.

[edit] airiel

Formed in '97 by Jeremy Wrenn, it was initially a solo project supported by various drum machines. However, he had dreams of entertaining the masses located outside of the confines of his bedroom, so he drafted local music scene veterans Cory Osborne and John Rungger on bass and drums. But the heady mélange was not completed until guitarist Chris De Brizzio entered the fray.

Many bands today are an exercise in minimalism, stripping everything down to the bone and sinew. Airiel takes a different approach. Injecting their well-crafted songs with enough effects to level a small village, they stretch and expand the sonic boundaries of the genre until the listener is completely deluged by an aural wave of reverb, distortion and sweat. They are advancing the art of sheer sonic energy while utilizing the power of a good melody to provide a basis for the effects, never forgetting the innate human desire to shake one's ass. In short, it's loud, it's beautiful, and you can dance to it.

Through Clairecords (Sacramento), Airiel released a series of 4-song EP's titled Winks & Kisses. The EP's were also sold as a limited edition box set, capturing the evolution of Airiel in its current form. Their cds are consistently some of the top sellers of the label, and they have already sold out of the Frosted EP. In June of 2005 Airiel released their newest EP. This self-titled EP further illustrates Airiel's ever-evolving sound and provides a glimpse at their promise with blistering waves of gorgeous guitars, kinetic drum beats and soaring vocal harmonies. The group has also been asked to contribute to several compilation cds, including the "Never Lose That Feeling" compilation by Club AC30(UK).

In addition to their recordings, Airiel has also gained a reputation for being a stellar live band. Utilizing video projection (courtesy of Arturo Valle of Panic Films) and amps that go up to eleven, they are able to win hearts and minds even in the most hostile of hipster-pomo environments. In addition to playing such local Chicago landmarks as the Double Door, Subterranean, and the Bottom Lounge, recently they have begun plying their trade farther afield, in such locales as Minneapolis, Milwaukee , Pittsburgh and Indianapolis . This summer, they embarked on their first tour of the East Coast, hitting New York City, Washington D.C., Philadelphia, and points in between. Airiel has also opened for some high-profile acts, including The Dears and The Brian Jonestown Massacre.

2006 should prove to be a banner year for the band. Plans include the recording of a full-length album, and continued touring to destinations both near and far.

www.airiel.com www.clairecords.com www.myspace.com/airiel

[edit] Area Code 860

Area code 860 is the area code in use in most of the state of Connecticuit. The entire state used to be area code 203, and in the 1990s, it was split, with 203 remaining for the southwestern corner of the state, as far east as New Haven, and the rest of the sate was given the area code 860.

Chairman Sibley earned his bachelor's degrees in Accounting and Secondary Education. from York College of Pennsylvania and is currently persuing a Master's of Business Administration from the same institution.

He currently resides on Fox Ridge Road in Dover, Pennsylvania (a town damned to hell) and is formerly of Cottage Place in York City. His father, a retired baptist minister, is currently employed as a greeter at Wal Mart. His sister lives with her parents.

[edit] Wissinoming, Philadelphia, Pennsylvania

Wissinoming is a small neighborhood located in the Near Northeast section of Philadelphia, Pennsylvania. Its zip code is 19135. It is bounded by Tacony on the north, Bridesburg on the south, I-95 and the Delaware River on the east, and Frankford on the west. It has a wide variety of nationalities, including Irish, Polish, and African-American.

[edit] Shaun Gladwell

Shaun Gladwell, born in Sydney, Australia, 1972, is an accomplished artist who is not limited to one media. He is a sculptor, painter, and video artist. He is best known for his video works which often feature him skateboarding, as well as a range of street subculture such as break dancing. Shaun Gladwell grew up in Sydney’s western suburbs and started to experiment with video after his dreams to become a professional skateboarder were ruined by injury. Gladwell went to Sydney College of the Arts and then completed postgraduate research at the College of Fine Arts and is now one of Australia’s rising young artists. Gladwell said that his concept is based on “the isolated figure moving and struggling through the panoramas of nature, urban and real, in a possible engagement with the sublime.”

[edit] Vierordt's law

Vierordt (1868) was the first to record a law of time perception which relates perceived duration to actual duration over different interval magnitudes, and according to task complexity.

Vierordt's law is "a robust phenomenon in time estimation research that has been observed with different time estimation methods" Fortin. C and Rousseau. R. (1998). It states that, retrospectively, "short" intervals of time tend to be overestimated, and "long" intervals of time tend to be underestimated. The other major paradigm of time estimation methodology measures time prospectively.

The cut-off point between what is considered "short" and "long" - and therefore between overestimation and underestimation - is between 2 and 10 minutes depending on the task e.g. Yarmey.A.D. (2000). The percentage of underestimation grows as task duration increases.

The law is relatively unknown outside psychophysics and is not cited in the Transport Planning literature, which relies heavily on the Valuation of Time Savings http://www.its.leeds.ac.uk/projects/WBToolkit/Note10.htm.

(Note to avoid controversy: Vierordt law is irrelevant to the economic appraisal of transport infrastructure on account of the Constant Unit Value of time (CUV) assumption, which states that the same unit value should be assigned to time changes irrespective of the size or sign of the change [see para 3.27 http://www.dft.gov.uk/stellent/groups/dft_econappr/documents/page/dft_econappr_610340-03.hcsp#TopOfPage ]. However, at least one group of researchers have pointed out the possible importance of asymmetric variation of VTTS distributions:

"For purposes of investment appraisal, it is acceptable to use "average" figures for VTTS, which could mean mode or median figures for the variations in VTTS in the population are asymmetric [...] in terms of individuals' actual willingness to pay and modify their behavior, it may be necessary to recognize that small time savings might not be valued the same as larger blocks of time" Zhang et al (2004).

There is, in other words, evidence (not yet understood or fully accepted) that "the unit value of time is lower for small travel-time savings and falls with the length of the trip" Zhang et al (2004). This is a well-known and sometime widely debated controversy in Transport Planning know as "the small travel time savings controversy". Interestingly 3 minutes used to be considered a "small" time saving. Now it is about 10. )

REFERENCES: Fortin. C and Rousseau. R. (1998) 'Interference from short-term memory processing on encoding and reproducing brief durations' Psychological Research 61 p269-276.

"Towards estimating the social and environmental costs of transportation in Canada" A report for Transport Canada by Zhang. A, Boardman, A.E., Gillen. D and Waters. W.G. 2004 http://www.sauder.ubc.ca/cts/docs/Full-TC-report-Updated-November05.pdf

EXTERNAL LINK: http://psychologicalscience.org/cfs/program/view_submission.cfm?Abstract_ID=3713

[edit] Gene D. Matlock

Gene D. Matlock seems to have discovered many language and culture similarities between many precolumbian civilizations and people from Afghanistan to far east Asia. Also giving arguments that support the idea of extensive comercial relations between precolumbian America with the rest of the world, long before Christ. He might be quite convince that ancient cities from Mexican gulf to Tenochtitlan are related to some Atlántepec, Tolan, A-tolan and other TLan like cities:

Atlán, Autlán, Mazatlán, Cihuatlán, Cacatlán, Tecaltitlán, Tihuatlán, Atitlán, Zapotlán, Minititlán, Ocotlán, Miahuatlán, Tecaltitlán, Tepatitlán, Tihuatlán, Texiutlán, and the like. Notice that the Nahuatl Tlán root of these place names is exactly like the Tlan in "Atlantis."


He says:_"Should we continue our fun guessing games about Atlantis for another few millenniums? Or should we confidently begin our search for the submerged half of Atlantis from Atlántepec's (Mexico's) southeast coast? Will the ruins that we'll surely find be those of the real Atlantis?"

He believes we should be conducting the search for Atlantis in the Yucatan region of Mexico. Matlock cites place names as one of the compelling proofs:

Atlán, Autlán, Mazatlán, Cihuatlán, Cacatlán, Tecaltitlán, Tihuatlán, Atitlán, Zapotlán, Minititlán, Ocotlán, Miahuatlán, Tecaltitlán, Tepatitlán, Tihuatlán, Texiutlán, and the like. Notice that the Nahuatl Tlán root of these place names is exactly like the Tlan in "Atlantis."

He also cites an ancient, spiral-shaped harbor with high banks or dikes lining the channels that once existed near San Lorenzo Tenochtitlán, Mexico. This layout is very much like that described by Plato for Atlantis's great port city.

When Gene D. Matlock was seven years old, he became deathly sick from pneumonia. His mother prayed that if he survived, she would dedicate him to the study of theology. She never suspected Gene's studies would lead him to "no-no" conclusions not welcome in Sunday School, the mosque, and the synagogue.

Matlock says that the linguistic revelations comparing different cultures are astonishing. That we are and always have been a global community from the very beginning of civilization. He says: "When I was a young college student in Mexico, I took a course in linguistics. This course and my experiences in studying Spanish, Portuguese, Malay, and Nahuatl, taught me that a word is much more than a combination of strange sounds. Each one tells the history of the people who use it." According to Matlock, the secret surrounding the location of Atlantis -- and thus, proof that it really existed -- can be traced back to the forbidden letter.

[edit] [ [ Thomas Hellor Cooper ] ]

SS-Unterscharfuhrer Thomas Hellor Cooper (1919+) was the only Englishman to win a German military decoration during World War Two.

Born to an English father (a Boer War veteran) and a German mother in Chiswick, London, on 29 August 1919, his application to join the police, air force and navy were all declined on account of his mother's origins. Cooper joined the Hammersmith branch of the British Union of Fascists during the late 1930s and later went to Germany for work as a teacher. On 1 February 1940 he was admitted into the prestigious "Leibstandarte Adolf Hitler", the Fuhrer's personal boydguard turned Waffen-SS division, in Berlin. In July he was transferred to the Totenkopf Waffen-SS division (mostly comprised of concentration camp guards) where he acheived the rank of NCO at a training camp in Pomerania. In Februay 1943 on the Russian Front he was severely injured and consequently qualified for the German "wound badge" (silver class). He was later placed in command of the British "Freikorps".

After the war Cooper was tried before the Old Bailey for high treason, found guilty and condemned to death but this was commuted to life imprisonment. He was released from jail in 1953, and is thought to have resettled in Japan.



[edit] Sources

Christopher Ailsby, "SS: Roll of Infamy" (London, 1997), Page. 27.

[edit] Fred Myrow

Fred Myrow was born in Brooklyn, New York in 1939, moving to Hollywood at age six where his father, Joseph Myrow ("You Make Me Feel So Young") composed music for musical films. His grandfather, Irving Mills, was a music publisher( Mills Music), producer (Cotton Club Productions) and manager (Duke Ellington).

Studying with Darius Milhaud in Aspen in 1956, Mr. Myrow went on to the University of Southern California. In 1959 he received a commission by the Young Musicians Foundations to write Symphonic Variations, premiered later that year at the Hollywood Bowl, and subsequently by the Los Angeles Philharmonic, B.B.C., and Concerts Colonne in Paris, conducted by Lawrence Foster.

In 1964, Mr. Myrow returned to the United States to be composer, pianist, and conductor with Center for Creative and Performing Arts in Buffalo, appearing regularly with Evenings For New Music at Carnegie Hall under Lukas Foss. His Songs for the Japanese was performed at Tanglewood, Los Angeles and the B.B.C., London with subsequent recording by Nonesuch Records. The Fromm Foundation commissioned Music for Orchestra I, premiered at the Tanglewood Festival by Gunther Schuller. Later performed by several orchestras including Berlin, and Oakland where Music For Orchestra II was premiered.

Mr. Myrow has also been composer-in residence with the New York Philharmonic, and received a Dimitri Mitropolous Commisssion to write an orchestral work for that orchestra.

In 1969 he undertook a period of study of music from other cultures, worked and composed for various media. He worked with Jim Morrison(of the Doors) selecting music for HWY, a film starring Morrison, and collaborating on a theatrical musical aborted by Morrison's death.

Leo the Last ( directed by John Boorman) was Myrow's first feature film score. During the period from 1969 on, he composed the scores to twenty five other films including Soylent Green, Scarecrow and director Don Coscarelli's other features, Jim The World's Greatest, Kenny & Company, Phantasm II and also Survival Quest and Phantasm III with co-composer Christopher L. Stone.

Myrow died of a heart attack on the morning of January 14, 1999 at his Hollywood Hills home in Los Angeles, California. He was 59.

[edit] Asteroid (42531) McKenna

(42531) McKenna = 1995 LJ Martin McKenna (b. 1978) was named 2005 Astronomer of the Year by the Irish Federation of Astronomical Societies. An avid visual comet hunter and all-round observer, he also undertakes a photographic search for novae. The name was suggested by J. C. McConnell.

The asteroid 42531, was discovered by Dr. David J. Asher in 1995 at Siding Springs, Australia.

[edit] Evan Mecham Eco-Terrorist International Conspiracy

The Evan Mecham Eco-Terrorist International Conspiracy (EMETIC) was a group that performed acts of sabatage against ski resorts and nuclear power plants in the Southwestern United States between 1987 and 1988. The group's name is a reference to impeached Arizona governor Evan Mecham.

EMETIC's first act was to damage a chairlift at the Fairfield Snow Bowl near Flagstaff, Arizona. During the incident an acetylene torch was used to cut bolts from several of the lift's support towers. A warning letter claiming responsibility for the damage also contained a threat to "chain the Fairfield CEO to a tree at the 10,000-foot level and feed him shrubs and roots until he understands the suicidal folly of treating the planet primarily as a tool for making money." Upon receipt of the letter the resort shut down the lift in order to repair the over US$ 50,000 in damages caused by the EMETIC.

The EMETIC made two other attacks against targets the group considered to be causing ecological damage before the FBI began arresting group members. In May 1989, Marc Leslie Davis, Margaret Katherine Millet, Marc Andre Baker were arrested on charges related to the sabatage against the Fairfield Sun Bowl and on conspiracy charges to damage facilities related to nuclear power plants in Arizona, California, and Colorado. A fourth EMETIC member, Ilse Washington Asplund, was later arrested on related charges. All four individuals pleaded guilty and were sentenced in September 1991.

  • Kiefer, Michael. "The Big Steep: The only thing slick about Arizona Snowbowl is the snow", Phoenix New Times, 1997-02-20.

[edit] John Creamer and Stephane K

John Creamer and Stephane K are acclaimed New York-based DJ/Producers who work as musical partners and are considered by many to be among the most influential progressive-house music pioneers of the early 2000's. They created a very signature sound - very deep, often dark and always sexy as hell - straight from the grooviest alleys of New York City and into the world's best clubs. Superstar DJs John Digweed, Danny Howells, Danny Tenaglia and Pete Tong were among the first to champion the John Creamer and Stephane K sound and made it an international sensation. What was "the new sound of New York" went well beyond the banks of this metropolis and became a global craze.

There is a certain texture and mood to every track Creamer & K touches. The duo has an affinity for good, quality vocals (but not the over-the-top diva kind), steamy percussion and twisted, tribal efx. This formula has been used time and again in the construction of some of the most popular remixes of the last decade. Their stellar remix portfolio includes reworkings of Kosheen's "Hide U," Satoshi Tomiie's "Love In Traffic" New Order's "Crystal" Nat Monday's "Waiting," Hybrid's "True To Form," Moony's "Doves," Puretone's "Addicted To Bass," The Crystal Method's "You Know It's Hard," Sinead O' Connor's "Troy" and Iio's classic anthem, "Rapture." Although this list features artists representing many different musical styles, they have one thing in common - these tracks have all been made into dance floor hits. Most notable are the remixes of Kosheen's "Hide U" (which won them remix of the year at the 2001 Muzik Awards, entered the UK Top 10 at .. 6 and topped Billboard's Hot Dance Music / Club Play chart), Sinead O' Connor's "Troy" (topped Billboard's Hot Dance Music / Club Play chart) and Iio's "Rapture" (hit ..2 on both the U.K. singles chart and on the Billboard Hot Dance Music/Club Play chart.) Beyond remixing, their acclaimed original productions including "I Love You" and "Wish You Were Here" continue to earn them respect worldwide.

John Creamer grew up in Philadelphia and from an early age was influenced by classic rock; eventually leading to his role as a Trombone player in a garage-ska band. However, like so many others, John's life was changed instantly by his first encounter with the original Sound Factory. Drawn in by the no holds barred approach to music that the Sound Factory DJs instituted, John knew that house music was where he needed to be. Following his instincts, he soon moved to New York and landed a record store gig at the influential Eightball Records. In time, Creamer rose up the ranks to become A&R man for Eightball's growing label (and later A&R for Satellite Records). Constantly surrounded by records, Creamer did quite a bit of DJing around New York City, while also dabbling into the production realm with the release of some well-respected acid jazz under the name Butter Foundation.

Like Creamer, Stephane K also got his start in rock music. The New York resident - by way of Paris and Tokyo - first started out as a bass player in the progressive rock band E Trance and performed with the group at legendary digs like CBGB's and the Knitting Factory. In the early 90's Stephane was also converted by the original Sound Factory and quickly made the shift over to house music production. His first house productions came via a collaborative effort with DJ Katsu under the name Madam. Stephane later went on to record tracks with Satoshi Tomiie under the name Bipath and continues to dabble into the production of his own tracks, most notably "Numb"and "Insane Poem," co-produced with PQM.

Being an A&R man with Eightball, Creamer was quite familiar with Madam's production ability and hired them to remix an Eightball project. A close relationship soon developed between Creamer and K, and they soon began collaborating together with a mutual desire to create vocal-driven tracks. This was quite a bold move when you consider that at the time, long, drawn-out instrumentals were the name of the game in dance music. Well, the rest as they say, is history.

When you are responsible for a number of huge remixes, good things start to happen in all facets of your career. Upon hearing the duo's remix of Trancesetters' "Roaches," Bedrock honcho John Digweed asked them to mix the fourth installment of the label's Compiled And Mixed series. Previously known more for their remixing, this CD provided a forum to showcase their abilities as DJs. The two-disc set was well received around the world and featured Creamer & PQM's naughty "Fucksonnet," described by Muzik magazine as "a fucking brilliant prog-swearathon that would make John Lydon blush."

Drawing from his production and remixing skills, Creamer has launched a budding DJ career. Internationally, he has already played the world's most respected clubs including Cream, Renaissance and Bedrock in the U.K.; Pacha in Portugal, Soda in Athens and Zouk in Singapore. In the U.S., he has played Spundae in San Francisco, Los Angeles and Las Vegas; Axis in Boston and Just about every cool (and not so cool) venue in New York City.

By 2005, the duo Creamer and K had formed their own independent label, NY LOVE, with collaborator Lance Jordan, and had released a string of successful dance singles, most notably the #1 Billboard Dance Anthem Smash "Love Is A Drug" featuring New York singer/songwriter Rosko. In early 2006, they followed up the Rosko track in with another #1 remix, "Glory of Life" by Mink, on the heels of the eagerly anticipated duet between Nadia Ali (iio) and Rosko, "Something To Lose," for Ultra Records. These visionary boys have inspired a tight group of acclaimed underground New York electronic music artists (centered around Creamer, K, Rosko, Jordan and Ali) that is commonly referred to as "The NY LOVE Crew." Together, they continue to throw legendary parties and live performances in New York, Miami, and around the world, in many of the largest and most prestigious nightclubs.

[edit] [ [Mouhammad Faye - aka "Muha"] ]

Member of the Georgia Institute of Technology's (Georgia Tech) 2006-07 Men's Basketball team. Will be a redshirt freshman in the Fall of 2006. Stands 6-feet, 8-1/2-inches, weighs a "razor-thin" 208 pounds, and plays combo-forward positions. Possesses a great feel for the game. Ridiculously long and skilled. Will be an impact guy, who can step-out, has three-point range, can put the ball on the floor and get to the basket, and is also a versatile defender. Reminicient of Mike Dunleavy, formerly of the Dook University and, now, the Golden State Warriors.

A native of the port city of Dakar, Senegal (pop.- 1.5 million) on the west coast of the African continent. Played on that country's national basketball team prior to the 2005 season. Previously ranked as the #3 junior AAU basketball player in all of Africa and ranked as the #7 "NBA potential" list at the "Africa Without Borders" basketball camp. An older brother, named Assane Faye, played varisty basketball at the University of New Hampshire. Another older half-brother, named Mohamed Niang, was a 6'10" center and played varsity basketball at the University of Delaware. At Georgia Tech, started taking classes in the fall of 2005. Majoring in INTA, with a Management minor.

Sat out the 2005-06 basketball season, having not received academic clearance to play from the ruling National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA). Practiced with the team during the 2006 spring semester. Recognized by Head Basketball Coach Paul Hewitt as a named factor in the talents of the new players to be added to the 2006-07 roster, ie. "....plus Mouhammad Faye." Acknowledged by much-heralded McDonalds High School All-American power forward and incoming Georgia Tech Freshman Thaddeus Young, as one who "can play the game. He will shock a lot of people."

Dubbed "GT's Mystery Man!" Nicknamed "Muha" by teammates. Thought to have x-ray vision, as well as the ability to freeze time. More than lovable Aussie Center Luuuke Schenscher, of GT's 2001-05 MBB teams, who had his own "possee," the idolized Faye has a cult, is a message board cult hero or, moreso, "Faye is The Cult." Fans already realize that for the elusive Muha, "none of us are witnesses."

The evolving "Legend of The Fayebulous," who has yet to be witnessed in any photographs or videos, has begun to grow exponentially "On the Flats" of the GT Campus, within the ATL sporting community, and beyond the farthest reaches of the universe....well, make that of the internet, sans Athens, GA.

[edit] Rodgers Forge Elementary

Rodgers Forge Elementary school was founded in 1951 to meet the growing post World War 2 population boom in the north Baltimore, Maryland, suburbs, south of Towson, Maryland, called Rodgers Forge. The brick school was erected on Dumbarton Road, in 1951, and served the communities of Rodgers Forge, Armagh Village, Woodbrook, Haddon, and the Baltimore County portion of Mt. Washington. The school retains its original appearance and serves this population. It has been known as one of the better-performing schools of Baltimore County.

[edit] Ray Velazquez, Jr.

Ray Velazquez, Jr., is a the Former Hudson County Freeholder for the 4th District, State of New Jersey. Velazquez, a graduate of Notre Dame Law School is a partner at the Law Firm of Gold, Albanese, Barletti & Velazquez, in Morristown, New Jersey. Velazquez made national news by attacking Gov. James McGreevey's decision to come out of the closet and declare his homosexuality during a time of political scandal. As a result, Velazquez, Hudson County's first openly gay politician suffered the consequences of his attack and was removed from the democratic party line the following election. He did not run, opting to wait and see what other opportunities arise in the near future.

In November 2005, shortly before leaving office Velazquez disclosed that he was HIV positive. He based his decision to make this announcement on the need to educate the community that everyone is at risk for HIV infection.

Ray Velazquez, Jr., is a prominent trial attorney who has won several significant civil rights cases, including Helmy v. City of Jersey, et als., involving a malicious prosecution case by a Jersey City Police Officer. In addition, Velazquez has a daily political blog read by hundreds of locals who can't get enough of Hudson County Politics. Interested readers should go to: rayvjr.com

Velazquez is a member of the Committee On Model Civil Jury Charges for the State of New Jersey.

[edit] Sigma Phi Omega

Sigma Phi Omega was founded at the University of Southern California in 1949, and is the oldest Asian-American sorority at USC and third oldest in the United States. It was originally established as a social organization for Japanese and Japanese-American women at USC. There was much anti-Asian sentiment left behind by World War II, which had ended in 1945. As one alumni said, " At that time it was understood that Asian women could not become members of a sorority. It has since changed. Thank goodness. "

In its early beginnings, the founding mothers of Sigma Phi Omega were invited by Chi Alpha Delta, an Asian-American sorority from UCLA, to become one of their chapters. (Chi Alpha Delta had been chartered in 1928 at UCLA, but was rendered inactive between 1942 and 1945 because the majority of its members were unable to attend UCLA due to World War II. After the end of the war, the sorority was reorganized in 1946.)

However, our founding mothers decided to start their own organization. The Greek letters were chosen at random and were not used by any other existing fraternities or sororities at that time. Although we did not originate as a sorority, one could speculate that the choosing of Greek letters was a public way of voicing a dissatisfactory opinion about the treatment of Asian American, specifically Japanese Americans, by the campus and Greek organizations.

Membership was primilary those of Japanese descent in the beginning, although it was open in membership. The pledge program was implemented in the mid-1950's.

Since it was founded, Sigma Phi Omega has established six other chapters located in both California and Texas.


Alpha Chapter: University of Southern Caligornia, Los Angeles : 1949 Beta Chapter: California State University, Long Beach : 1970 Gamma Chapter : University of Texas : May 1, 1991 Delta Chapter : San Diego State University : December 18, 1991 Epsilon Chapter : University of Houston : April 21, 1995 Zeta Chapter : University of California at Berkeley : April 5, 1997 Eta Chapter : Baylor University : May 1, 1999


Sigma Phi Omega has helped young women adjust to college life for over fifty years. College is a time for new faces, endeavors, and experiences. Among this whirlwind of unfamiliarity, being in a sorority can help brighten your path and put things into perspective. It provides a base for lasting friendships and special memories. Sigma Phi Omega prides itself for its diversity in membership as we embrace the unique qualities and gifts each brings. Our alumni have gone onto successful careers in business, law, medicine, entertainment, and education.

[edit] Charlene Zettel

Image:Charlenezettel.gif
Charlene Zettel, a moderate Republican, serves as the Director of the Department of Consumer Affairs for the state of California. She was appointed in March 2004 by Governor Arnold Schwarzenegger.

Charlene has served the people of California in many capacities. After many years as a parent volunteer, she was elected to the Poway Unified School District board in 1992 and served in that office for six years. Encouraged by her constituents to seek higher office, Charlene was the first Republican Latina elected to the state legislature, serving two terms in the Assembly as the representative for California's 75th District. Charlene ran against California State Assemblyman Dennis Hollingsworth (R-Temecula) in 2002 for the vacant State Senate seat in the 36th District; Charlene lost the election. Many people viewed the campaign ran by Dennis Hollingsworth to be shady and misleading. After leaving the State Assembly, Charlene remained politically active and when Governor Arnold Schwarzenegger was elected he appointed Charlene to be the Director of California's largest consumer agency, the California Department of Consumer Affairs.

Among her responsibilities in the Assembly, she served as chairwoman of the Republican Caucus, vice chair of the Assembly Committee on Jobs, Economic Development and the Economy, and a member of the Appropriations, Education, Health, Rules, Transportation and Governmental Organization committees.

Some of Charlene's accomplishments in the legislature include the passage of AB 526, which preserved critical testimony of abused elderly victims, AB 2063, which allowed an abuser’s prior acts to be admissible in court, determining violent character and AB 1767, which provided protections against computer terrorists.

She also sought to protect our children with the introduction and passage of “Oliver’s Law,” which provided parents with critical information about licensed day care providers, and AB 1789, which enhanced penalties for child abusers.

Charlene resides in Poway, a city in northern San Diego County. Charlene has been a board member of the San Diego Regional Airport Authority and a public interest director of the Federal Home Loan Bank of San Francisco. She is currently a member of the board of directors of the San Diego and Imperial Counties Chapter of the Red Cross.

Raised in Los Angeles, she received a Bachelor of Science degree in dental hygiene from the University of Southern California School of Dentistry, and practiced in her field for 20 years. She and her husband, David Zettel, a prominent dentist in the north San Diego County area have been married 34 years and have two children.

[edit] "Puppeteer" Class Drone Frigate

Since training piolets for fighters is costly and time-consuming, Fleet Command designed the Puppeteer Drone Frigate. It remote-controles around 25 static drones. Each of these has little power, but combined they unleash a withering firestorm. Predictably, it is most effectave against weakly armored strike craft. [edit] Casa Video

Casa Video

In 1983, two people who loved movies, Raymond and Gala Mellenberndt, and who were raised with movies, decided to create a store with not just mainstream titles, but classics, foreign movies, documentaries, cult movies, and experimental movies.

There were no more mom and pop theatres like the one they grew up in in Rock Rapids, Iowa...there were no more balconies...no more chandeliers. Where once the movie theatre was the center of small town life, the theatres were now abandoned. So were drive-in theatres. In their place moved cineplex octopuses with twenty small box sized rooms.

Casa Video went out of its way to become unique. In the beginning, it was about the same size as the neighborhood candy store. There were no other stores like it in Tucson. The original location on Grant and Campbell was a universe different from any other video store in the west...like an old book- store, it resembled a cave where someone could discover hidden treasures found nowhere else. Then came Blockbuster...then came Hollywood... then came all other McVideos. Most other mom and pop video stores went out of business. Casa Video grew and grew.

Casa Video is now an 8,000 square foot store located at 2905 East Speedway Blvd., Tucson, Arizona 85716. It has two floors, housing more than 40,000 video rentals...DVD's...audio books...and video games.

It has the largest selection of foreign movies, classics, documentaries, independent movies, and hard-to-find movies in the entire state of Arizona.

For questions or comments, call our Customer Service toll free at 1-888-976-1800, or locally at 1-520-326-8098. Or Email us at info@casavideo.com.

website: http://www.casavideo.com/

[edit] [ [Clematis dioica L.] ]

Cientific name: ' ' Clematis dioica L.

Common name: Hair of Angel, Beards of cat, Beards as an older person.

Family: Rununculaceae.

Descripción:Climbing herb of more than 1 meter of height on shrubs and trees. Target-greenish flowers. It requires of semishade although it can support direct sun. Moderate irrigation to frequent, is due to have well-taken care of of the encharcamientos to avoid that the roots rot.

Temperature: Average.

Uses:The starts off aerial is used to adorn domestic altars. In gardening it is used in walls, in flowerpots of terrace (near the walls).

Fertilization: Installment of general nature once to the year.

[edit] Washington State Guard

The Washington State Guard is an all-volunteer unit organized under the Military Department of the State of Washington. Its members are citizens of the State of Washington and often serve without pay or compensation, but commit to a minimum service obligation such as one year and to show up regularly to scheduled meetings, often one weekend day per month. They adhere to uniform standards, such as height and weight, and wear distinctive insignia, such as a unique shoulder patch and a "WASHINGTON" name tape on the front of the utility uniform.

The Washington State Guard serves under state jurisdiction and is employed only within the State of Washington. It is not subject to be called, ordered or assigned as any element of the federal armed forces. However, membership in the Washington State Guard does not exempt an individual from service in the armed forces of the United States.

[edit] Daft Friday

"Daft Friday" is the social event of the year at the GUU (Glasgow University Union). During the festivities of Daft Friday, students are expected to dress formally, girls in dresses or ball-gowns and males in suits or kilts. The union is renovated to a different theme each year which is kept secret until the night of the event. The event is open to all members of the GUU and tickets are purchased from the porters box nearer to the event. Other information regarding the event can be found on the GUU website. The alternative union of Glasgow University is the QMU (Queen Margaret Union) which holds the alternative to Daft Friday, 10 hour Cheesy Pop, which is typically held at the end of each term (as opposed to Daft Friday which occurs once a year). Ask any student on campus about Daft Friday and you can be sure of a wealth of stories and folklore surrounding the event.

[edit] Spherical cow

Spherical cows are a tongue in cheek reference to simplifications that are often made in scientific and engineering calculations.

For instance a physics problem in a textbook might begin with the phrase "Consider a spherical cow of uniform density..." Assuming a uniform, spherical cow greatly simplifies equations dealing with momentum, air resistance, center of mass, surface area, and volume because a spherical cow is mathematically equivalent to the mathematical definition of a spherical solid, e.g. the points in 3-space satisfying x^2 + y^2 + z^2 < r^2. A spherical cow skin is equivalent to the two dimensional surface of a sphere; x^2 + y^2 + z^2 = r^2.

Depictions of spherical cows, along with jokes and other important information, can be found at the sources listed below.

[edit] Uralic Race

In 20th century, when archaeologists and scientists who were exploring the ruins of ancient villages in Ural mountains, they found the remainings of settlers and explored their skeletons and this experiment brought to the results which became an incredible discovery. This discovery was a good opponent to Hitler's and SS racial theories.
As Nazis and Neo-Nazis believed in power of blue-eyed and blond-haired people who's origin they thought can be only North Europe, scientists found out that natives of Ural mountains and ancestors of Finnic-Ugric people were also the origins of blue-eyed and blond haired people, but comparing with Nazi's "master race", these people were not nordics or "Aryans", because their appearances were asian.
Uralic people (blue-eyed and light-haired people with asian apperances) spoke language which is relative to Finnic, Estonian and other Finnic-Ugric languages.

[edit] History

4000-3000 BC all people who were part of Uralic Race joined into one group of settlements and began to create common languages which were the origins of Finnic-Ugric languages. In the first 1000 AD years, most of these nations began to move west and began to live with caucausians and mixed with them. Through generations Uralic people began to look completely European and they lost all appearances which were parts of Uralic Race except blue eyes and blond hairs (means all asian appearances which were parts of Uralic Race have disappeared).
The offsprings of these Uralic People are Finnic-Ugric nations including Estonians, Karels, Finnic people and others.

[edit] How does this information opposes Nazi theories

During the migration of Uralic people in the first 1000 AD years, lots of babies in this area of migration were born who were half Uralic and half Caucausian.
Dark haired and dark-eyed Caucausian man and Uralic woman who married each other can have a blue-eyed and blond-haired with European appearance child, which from point view of Nazis looks like and must be a person of "Aryan" race, but really shouldn't be the ancestor Nordic race. This child got European appearance from his dark haired and eyed father, and got blue eyes and blond hairs from mother who's appearance is asian.

[edit] Samer Kawak

Samer Kawak was born on December 3, 1988, in the Glasgow, Scotland. He was the first child of Abboud and Rola Kawak. At the time, his father was studying at St. Andrew's to receive his Ph.D. After a few years in Scotland, Samer's mother travel back to their home country of Syria to stay with Samer's grandmother for a year while Abboud established himself in the United States. From Syria, Samer made his first trip to the America at the tender age of three. Wisconsin turned out to be the family's initial destination. Again, as a doctor, Samer's father was required to move to complete his fellowship; therefore, the Kawaks moved to Philadelphia, Pennsylvania. Next, Samer, age 9, and his family moved again to Fairfax, Virginia. Finally, Indiana has become Samer's seemingly permanent home as he flourishes today in an excellent three-time blue ribbon high school, Roncalli.

[edit] Asphalt Green

Asphalt Green is a not-for-profit organization dedicated to assisting individuals of all ages and backgrounds achieve health through a lifetime of sports and fitness. They offer sports, fitness and health programs to members, individuals and institutions.

Asphalt Green stretches its 5 1/2 acre sports and training campus across York Avenue between 90th and 92nd Streets in Manhattan.

The facility includes:

  • The George Delacorte Pool: Manhattan's only 50-meter Olympic standard swimming pool
  • Separate Warm Water Teaching / Exercise pool

  • Regulation AstroTurf field for team sports
  • Steam & Sauna

  • Mazur Hall
  • Indoor & Outdoor running track
  • Indoor & Outdoor basketball courts

[edit] Endako B.C.

Endako is a very small town located in the center of British Columbia (Canada), between the towns of Fraser Lake and Burns lake on highway 16. The town has only one or two stores including a fine drinking extablishment "the Endako pub" named after the unincorporated town itself. The pub is central to the town which is evident upon seeing the greeting sign that reads: "Endako and Pub". Endako is a quaint town that has a special place in the hearts of all northerners in the Bulkley-nechako and lakes district regions. But be warned, when looking for the town as you are driving north keep your eyes peeled ;if you blink you will miss it.

[edit] Anthony Cohn

Anthony Cohn


Tony Cohn holds a Personal Chair at the University of Leeds, where he is Professor of Automated Reasoning and served a term as Head of the School of Computing August 1999 – July 2004.

He holds BSc and PhD degrees from the University of Essex where he studied under Pat Hayes. He spent 10 years at the University of Warwick before moving to Leeds in 1990. He now leads a research group working on Knowledge Representation and Reasoning with a particular focus on qualitative spatial/spatio-temporal reasoning. Many of his group’s publications concerning spatial reasoning can be found at http://www.comp.leeds.ac.uk/qsr/publications.html. He has received substantial funding from a variety of sources including EPSRC, the DTI, the European Union and various industrial sources. Work from the Cogvis project won the British Computer Society Machine Intelligence prize in 2004.

He has been Chairman/President of the UK AI Society SSAISB, the European Coordinating Committee on AI (ECCAI), KR inc, the IJCAI Board of Trustees and is Editor-in-Chief of the AAAI Press. He was elected a founding Fellow of ECCAI, and is also a Fellow of AAAI, AISB, the BCS, and the IET (formerly the IEE). He was Programme Chair of the European AI Conference ECAI'94, KR’98 and COSIT-05,Workshop Chair of IJCAI95, Conference Chair of KR2000, IJCAI 2003. He was on the judging panel for the British Computer Society Distinguished Dissertation award, and a co-organiser of a Dagstuhl Seminar No. 05491 on “Spatial Cognition: Specialization and Integration” in 2005. Recent invited talks include the 3rd Summer School on Cognitive Vision, Keynote Addresses at CIT’04, AISB’04 and KBSC-2004, a lecture series at the International Spatial Cognition Summer Institute (ISCSI) in 2003 and at the Australian Logic Summer School, CADE-19, and the AAAI 2003 Spring Symposium on Foundations and Applications of Spatio-Temporal Reasoning (FASTR) . He is Co-Editor-in-Chief of Spatial Cognition and Computation and a member of the IJCAI Board of Trustees. He has been on many programme committees for workshops and conferences, regularly referees for various AI journals, has been on the editorial board of DAKE, AI Communications (AICOM), and Review Co-Editor of the journal Artificial Intelligence; he is currently on the editorial board of the Applied Ontology Journal, the Journal of Applied Logic and on the Policy Committee of Electronic Transactions on AI (ETAI). He is a member of the UK EPSRC Peer Review College and of the UK Computing Research Committee (UKCRC), where he presently sits on the Executive Committee. He was an area co-editor for the UK Government FORESIGHT Cognitive Systems project, and advised the FORESIGHT Intelligent Systems Infrastructure project. He has been a member of two CNRS and two SFI institution review panels, and chair of a programme review panel at NICTA.


[edit] Sources

http://www.comp.leeds.ac.uk/agc/agc.html

[edit] Edith Brown Weiss

Ms. Brown Weiss is an legal scholar who has taught and published widely on issues of international law and global policies, including environmental and compliance issues.

She received a B.A. degree from Stanford University with Great Distinction. She earned an LL.B. (J.D.) from Harvard Law School and a Ph.D. in political science from the University of California at Berkeley and received an honorary Doctor of Laws from Chicago-Kent College of Law. Ms. Brown Weiss is currently Francis Cabell Brown Professor of International law at Georgetown University Law Center where she has been on the faculty since 1978. Prior to that, Ms. Brown Weiss was on the faculty of Princeton University. She has won several prizes for her work, including the Elizabeth Haub prize from the Free University of Brussels and the IUCN for international environmental law. She is the author or co-author of several award winning books, including In Fairness to Future Generations (in English, French, Spanish, Japanese, and Chinese), which won the American Society of International Law's Certificate of Merit for outstanding scholarship, and Engaging Countries: Strengthening National Compliance with International Environmental Accords and Regimes for the Ocean, Outerspace and Atmosphere, both of which won Harold and Margaret Sprout Awards from the International Studies Association.

Ms. Brown Weiss has been very active in the field of international law. She served as President of the American Society of International Law and as Associate General Counsel for the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency, where she established the division of international law. She is a member of many editorial boards, including the American Journal of International Law, Global Governance,

[edit] Orpheus (Band)

Orpheus was a psychedelic rock band founded in 1967. The name Orpheus was inspired by Greek Mythology. Members included guitarists Jack McKennes and Bruce Arnold, bassist Eric "the Snake" Gulliksen, and drummer Harry Sandler. All members also contributed vocals. By its end in 1969, the band recorded three albums and four singles for MGM Records. All of the albums and two of the singles reached the Billboard best-seller charts, including their most famous song, Can't Find the Time. Can't Find the Time is considered to be one of the classic love songs of the late 60's. It has been covered many times by artist such as Rose Colored Glass, the Groovin' Strings, Hootie and the Blowfish, and Johnny Dollar. Comedian Red Peters parodied the song with his own version, Jalalabad.

In addition to recording, the group played many sold-out concerts throughout the United States, sharing the stage with performers like Blood, Sweat and Tears, the Who, Cream, Led Zeppelin, Jeff Beck, the Rascals and Janis Joplin. Their second album, Ascending, reached no. 10 in the 1968 Playboy magazine Jazz and Pop Reader Poll. The group also recorded the theme song for the MGM movie Marlowe starring James Garner, Little Sister.

The group broke up in December of 1969, but reformed in 1971 with Stephen "Steve" Martin as a fifth member. They released a single on Bell Records, Big Green Pearl, but disbanded again in 1972. All of the Orpheus albums were produced by Alan Lorber.

In 2004, Jack, Snake, Harry, and Steve along with other musicians formed the band Orpheus Reborn, with a new style but maintaining the same legacy.

[edit] Ladbroke Hall, Ladbroke, Warwickshire

Ladbroke Hall

Ladbroke, Southam, Warwickshire


Ladbroke Hall viewed across the grounds


SUMMARY

Ladbroke Hall was built at the end of the 16th century and remained in single private ownership until the 1960’s, when it was used briefly as a girls’ boarding school. In the 70’s, the Hall and associated buildings were converted into 21 privately owned residences, providing pleasant accommodation within an exclusive and peaceful location.


Other buildings forming part of the Ladbroke Hall complex

There is full use of all of the Hall’s facilities including a tennis court and swimming pool, within approximately 5.6 acres of landscaped grounds.

The Hall is on the edge of the small Warwickshire village of Ladbroke, less than two miles from the town of Southam and approximately 10 minutes from junction 12 of the M40. Nearby towns include Leamington Spa, Warwick, Stratford upon Avon, and Banbury.


GROUNDS


Views of Ladbroke Hall across the grounds


Ladbroke Hall is set centrally in approximately 5.6 acres of well-maintained shared gardens that are bordered by open farmland. There are extensive lawns and flowerbeds stocked with shrubs and flowering plants and many mature trees.


The open air swimming pool

Toward the eastern edge of the grounds is an orchard and a small coppice with pond. Near to the coppice is the open-air swimming pool and adjacent to this is a landscaped miniature lake with seating area. The grounds also include a tennis court, and a croquet lawn for use during the summer months.

There are small plots for residents who wish to grow their own flowers / vegetables, and there is a laundry room with washing machines and tumble dryers paid for separately, if used, on a quarterly basis. There is an additional parking area which can also be used for caravans and boats set to the south-west of the grounds.

LOCATION

Ladbroke is an attractive South Warwickshire village, the population of which has remained more or less stable at around 250 since the time of the Doomsday Book. There is a pub which also serves food within the village. Ladbroke is 1½ miles from the small town of Southam where there are schools, shops, banks, a Post Office and several pubs. It is close to Leamington Spa, Warwick, Banbury, Stratford upon Avon, the Cotswolds and the M40.

GENERAL INFORMATION


Residents young and old celebrate the 400th

anniversary of the Main Hall

Tenure

Leasehold with approximately 970 years remaining. The freehold is owned by a residents’ management company. Each Ladbroke Hall resident holds an equal share in the company, and there are no other share holders. The Board of the management company is made up of residents who are elected at a General Meeting.

Maintenance Charge

This covers care of the gardens, swiming pool and tennis courts as well as exterior property maintenance e.g. roofing and windows. The maintenance charge is set once a year by a meeting of all residents, and for 2006 it is £140 p.c.m.

Ground Rent: £1 p.a., included in the maintenance charge

Services: Electricity, gas, water/sewerage and telephone services are connected. Broadband Internet is available.


For Further Information:

Email the company secretary (secretary@ladbrokehall.co.uk), or telephone 01926 811236.
