[edit] Melissa Galt

Melissa Galt is an interior designer, national speaker and author known for her no-nonsense philosophy working with clients to design their signature style. Most recently her work is showcased in the 2006 publication, Spectacular Homes of Georgia. Since 1994 when she established her firm Linea Interior Design, Inc., Melissa’s mission has been to create unique and personal environments that reflect her client’s life experiences and passions. “Your lifestyle and home must blend, in order to create the supportive atmosphere necessary for living life to the fullest”.

Often referred to as the Lifestyle Diva, Melissa has been profiled widely in the Atlanta Journal Constitution, Atlanta Business Chronicle, Points North, Atlanta Homes and Lifestyles, Southern Living, Better Homes and Gardens, Atlanta Home to name but a few. She has appeared on national television morning talk shows and talk radio offering tips and helpful advice on “Shortcuts to Better Living,” “Don’t Wait for a Mate, Feather Your Nest Now,” and “Designing Your Signature Life”. In the last decade Melissa has hosted successful lecture series at Evening at Emory, Oglethorpe University and Spruill Arts Center, with popular offerings such as Great Design Sources for Decorating, Gallery Hopping, Decorating Basics, Interior Design as a Second Career, and Change Your Interiors, Change Your Life These topics are the basis for Melissa’s professional and motivational speaking, igniting and energizing others to create change in their own lives. Melissa is also a contributing author in the motivational book Live Every Day Motivated, Successful and Happy. She often keynotes and conducts workshops at conferences, corporate events, fundraisers and consumer audiences nationwide. Design was the natural direction for Melissa career; Melissa Great-Grandfather was Frank Lloyd Wright. His design philosophy blended structure with nature in order to achieve harmonious spaces. Melissa’s philosophy is a natural evolution of those ideals. In the 21st century often our “environment” is a hectic life! Designing your signature life is Melissa’s original concept of using design to bring your life and home into harmony. Her Great-Grandfather would have understood and approved.

While Melissa is in tune with the work and vision of her Great-Grandfather, Melissa’s mother and her god-mother were constants in her life. Growing up with her mother, Academe Award winning actress, Anne Baxter, and blesses with god-mother, eight times Academe Award winning designer, Edith Head, meant exposure to style and design on an international level.



Growing up as the daughter of an actress meant a great deal of traveling. Traveling the world at an early age had a major impact on Melissa’s style and outlook. She has a passion for travel and has visited forty of the fifty U.S. states. Melissa has lived on the West Coast, the East Coast and now in the beautiful South. In addition, Melissa has traveled abroad extensively.

Melissa attended Cornell University’s preeminent School of Hotel Administration. After completing her degree she spent the next several years honing her business skills in hospitality purchasing.

Working with hotels meant moving every eight months. This gave Melissa the opportunity to see even more of his country. Moving to Ryetown, New York; Philadelphia, Pennsylvania; Mackinaw Island, Michigan; Charlotte, North Carolina; Birmingham, Alabama; Nashville, Tennessee; and Melissa final hospitality position at Callaway Gardens in Columbus, Georgia. Melissa enjoyed the newness of each position and locale, but was frustrated by the lack of creativity. Melissa god-mother Edith Head, “Aunt Eddy”, had always encouraged her designing impulses, so Melissa obtained her degree in interior design from Southern Institute in Alabama, Georgia. This was the beginning of designing Melissa’s Signature Life and the start of a very successful designing career.

[edit] Virtual Library Eastern Europe

Virtual Library Eastern Europe (ViFaOst) is an interdisciplinary portal that offers the academic community a wide range of information on the field of East European Studies. Comprehensive search possibilities enable access to specialized academic information on history, language, literature, politics and culture of East, Central East and South East European countries and historical regions. It is one of over 30 Virtual Libraries and information portals in the vascoda network and is sponsored by German Research Foundation (DFG) and the German Federal Ministry of Education and Research (BMBF). ViFaOst is created by the Bavarian State Library, Herder-Insitut (Marburg, Germany), Osteuropa-Institut (Munich, Germany) and the Departement for East and South East European History at the Historical Seminary of Ludwig-Maximilians-University in Munich.

[edit] Lost in Time

A BBC three-disc boxset DVD release of 2004 – a collection of restored Doctor Who episodes and clips from stories that are incomplete or otherwise missing from the Corporation's archives. Note that there are 108 episodes of the programme not known to exist (all from the black-and-white 1960s era) and that though the search goes on, many or all of them may be lost forever, a few clips (mostly herein) notwithstanding, hence this collection's title. Audio recordings of all the episodes' soundtracks – made off-air at the time of transmission by fans – do thankfully exist (though it was not always thought so) and have been archived by the BBC. The visual and audio quality of episodes and clips as originally recovered varies, but the work of the BBC-affiliated Restoration Team (visit: official site) is extraordinary and this boxset of rare archived material presents much never before made available, and all of it restored to a quality beyond what had previously been thought possible. For more information, see Doctor Who missing episodes.

[edit] Content:

  • The Reign of Terror – off-air film recording clips (all excerpts such as these are pretty brief 8mm home-movie material made by fans pointing a cine camera at a TV screen during the original (or a subsequent repeat) transmisison. Even cleaned up, they are not of broadcastable standard, though they have now had their soundtracks expertly added).
  • The Crusade – episodes 1 and 3, plus soundtracks for 2 and 4, and introduction and linking material provided by actor William Russell in character as Ian Chesterton (these are accessible as an 'Easter Egg' when the story is viewed via the 'Play all' option for the story). Ep 3 has a commentary option featuring actor Julian Glover (note: all commentaries are mediated by Gary Russell). This may be considered as a complete story release in the best form available at present.
  • Galaxy Four – a lengthy sequence from episode 1 (see The Missing Years, below) plus off-air film recording clips.
  • The Myth Makers – off-air film recording clips.
  • The Daleks' Master Plan – episodes 2, 5 and 10, plus clips from other episodes. Ep 2 has a commentary option featuring actors Peter Purves and Kevin Stoney, and designer Raymond Cusick.
  • The Celestial Toymaker episode 4.
  • The Savages off-air film recording clips.
  • The Smugglers (brief) clips and amateur footage showing the filming on location.
  • The Tenth Planet clips including off-air film recordings.
  • The Power of the Daleks clips and a (brief) trailer aired on the BBC ahead of the original transmission. (Note that brief further footage has been discovered since Lost in Time was released.)
  • The Highlanders (brief) clips and some on-location footage.
  • The Underwater Menace episode 3 and (brief) clips from other episodes. (Actor Frazer Hines' introduction to this episode from an earlier VHS boxset (The Ice Warriors) is also here as an 'Easter Egg'.)
  • The Moonbase episodes 2 and 4, plus soundtracks for 1 and 3. This may be considered as a complete story release in the best form available at present.
  • The Macra Terror (brief) clips including off-air film recordings.
  • The Faceless Ones episodes 1 and 3 (featuring some clever restoration to fill trimmed film sections).
  • The Evil of the Daleks episode 2, with a commentary option featuring actor Deborah Watling. Also The Last Dalek – footage showing the filming of model and effects sequences at Ealing Studios, and consequently a carefully recreated climactic sequence combining such footage and the original soundtrack.
  • The Abominable Snowmen episode 2 (featuring an extraordinarily recreated snippet of dialogue where the film had been trimmed) and (brief) clips, plus amateur footage showing the filming on location. There is a commentary option on the episode featuring actor Deborah Watling.
  • The Enemy of the World episode 3.
  • The Web of Fear episode 1 plus clips, with a commentary option on the episode featuring actor Deborah Watling and story editor Derrick Sherwin.
  • Fury from the Deep clips, footage from the filming of the final episode in studio, and consequently a carefully recreated climactic sequence combining such footage and the original soundtrack.
  • The Wheel in Space episodes 3 and 6 plus (brief) clips, the latter epsiode offering a commentary option featuring story editor Derrick Sherwin and director Tristan de Vere Cole.
  • The Space Pirates episode 2 plus clips.

In addition, there is the documentary The Missing Years on disc 3, detailing the plight of 1960s Doctor Who episodes and presented by actors Frazer Hines and Deborah Watling. It features the longest extant clip from an otherwise missing Doctor Who episode (in fact the entire four-part story may well be lost forever): more than five minutes of episode one of Galaxy Four. In its original form, this documentary was presented in an earlier VHS boxset (The Ice Warriors) and it is heartening to see that an episode (Day of Armageddon – which is episode 2 of The Daleks' Master Plan) and many of the clips included in this Lost in Time boxset were not known to exist at that time (1999).

[edit] Sources

Content from the item itself – all details from the content listing on the packaging and the booklet and discs within. There are Wikipedia entries for all the individual stories that are referencing this item; this entry is intended to tie things together.

193.202.113.254 15:44, 18 May 2006 (UTC)Stuart Maddison

[edit] Alberto Rapisarda

Alberto Rapisarda was born in Conegliano (Treviso), Italy on July 28, 1964. He is an Italian comics author and a multimedia artist. He starts writing and drawing comics in the mid-eighties for Rome based Frigidaire magazine. From 1983 he also collaborates to the activities of the comics 'factory' and cultural association "Zio Feininger", founded in Bologna by Andrea Pazienza,Lorenzo Mattotti and others, with the goal to promote the Italian cartoonists wave through expositions and live performances.

[edit] Johnnie Wilder Jr.

Johnnie Wilder Jr was one of the founding members and lead singer of the R&B group, Heatwave. Together with his brother, Keith Wilder, they put together a two time Emmy-nominated band. Johnnie Wilder Jr. served in the U.S. Army in Germany, where he met and began forming the group. Their first big hit was, "Boogie Nights" which went to number one on the International Charts in 1976. This was quickly followed by an equally memorable song, Always and Forever. In 1978, Heatwave released the "Central Heating" album which went to number five. In 1979, Johnnie Wilder Jr. was injured in an auto wreck and was paralyzed from the neck down. After spending many years supporting his Christian faith, he passed away at the age of 56 on May 18, 2006.

WHAT IS HENDERSON'S RELISH?

Though similar in appearance to a Worcestershire sauce, Henderson’s Relish is unique in its aroma and flavour. It can be used both as a sauce on meat dishes, pies, fish, chips and as a cooking ingredient in casseroles, pasta dishes, soups and marinades.

Unlike other comparable sauces, the relish is also suitable for vegetarians.

The special mix of spices are blended together with our secret recipe and a special sauce is made. The way in which the sauce is blended is still a closely guarded secret and at least once a year a rumour sweeps Sheffield that the owner is retiring and taking the secret recipe with him. Upon hearing this supermarket shelves are cleared as people stock up on their favourite sauce. Fortunately all these rumours are unfounded and Hendersons is going as strong as ever.


HISTORY

It was Mr Henry Henderson who first began manufacturing his own special type of sauce back in the late part of the 19th century. Originally manufactured at 35 Broad Lane in Sheffield, Henderson’s Relish is still being made no further than half a mile from the site of the first bottle being filled.

During the formative years of the Company there were two different owners but the current Managing Director, Dr Kenneth Freeman is the nephew of the late Charles Hinksman who began work for the company soon after The First World War, and it has been in this family’s hands ever since. He became MD in 1991 and has overseen some important changes in the Company’s profile. Previously unknown outside of Sheffield, Henderson's appeal is now spreading further and further afield with an increasing amount of supermarket listings and a thriving mail order service.

Up until now Henderson’s Relish was the only product that we sold, apart from the War years when we had to turn our hand to wholesaling products due to the lack of ingredients available to make our Relish.

FAMOUS FANS

[edit] Carlos Vergara

Carlos Vergara is a television news anchor born to Hernando and Mariella Vergara. Married to Telefutura (Univision) Network news anchor Beatriz Moncayo. Brother Eduardo Vergara is an electrical engineer residing in New Jersey, and married to Diana Valencia. Carlos speaks, reads, writes, and translates Spanish fluently. Carlos works at WTVJ, an NBC television station in Miami FL, where he reports on daily news events in South Florida. He has worked in other U.S. television markets including Bakersfield CA, Corpus Christi TX, and Albany GA, where he covered the disasterous 500 year floods. But Carlos is not limited to stateside reports. Having worked two US/Mexico border markets in his career, he's gained access to exclusive illegal immigration and illicit drug trade stories. Carlos has interviewed presidents George W. Bush and Jimmy Carter. Carlos has been asked to testify at two seperate murder trials. In both instances,confessions were made to him on camera. Carlos has volunteered his free time to various organizations including reading councils, the American Heart Association, and Instituto de Cultura Hispanica in Corpus Christi, where he is an honorable lifetime member of the board. The board graciously honored him with a special presentation in 2002, when they announced September 26th as Carlos Vergara Day in Corpus Christi. [edit] State College Iced Tea

A State College Iced Tea is an alcoholic mixed drink. It is a variation of the popular Long Island Iced Tea invented by students at the Pennsylvania State University in the Pinchot Inferno. The ingredients in a State College Iced Tea are:

  • 1 oz. Vladimir Vodka
  • 1 oz. Bankers Club Gin
  • 1 oz. Bankers Club or Jacquin's Clear Rum
  • 1 oz. Tortilla Tequila Liquor
  • 1 oz. Triple Sec
  • Lemon-Lime Flavored Gatorade
  • Pepsi

The State College Iced Tea is prepared nearly identically to the Long Island Iced Tea. The liquors are first poured into a large glass full of ice in equal proportions. The Gatorade is then added until the glass is nearly full. Pepsi is finally added to give it the color of a traditional iced tea. The drink may then be mixed in a shaker, making it slightly frothy or stirred.

This drink is popular at Penn State mainly due to the cheap liquors used and the availabilty of the mixers. All of the liquors involved in this drink can be purchased in the handle (1.75L) size for under $20 at Pennsylvania Liquor Stores, making it a bargain for college students. Penn State exclusively sells Pepsi beverages, so the Pepsi and Gatorade are available all over campus.

This drink is particularly potent with nearly five shots in a single drink, and it should be drinken responsibly.

[edit] Teamline

Teamline is a live sports play-by-play service that listeners use to access the play-by-play of sporting events from any telephone or Internet connection in the world! Since 1990 a company in Kent, Ohio called TRZ Communications Inc. has been providing thousands of games to alumni, displaced fans, and parents of athletes for over 500 college and professional teams.

Tom Zawistowski, CEO and Founder of TRZ, came up with the idea while working in athletics at The College of William & Mary. In 1982 his school received a bid to play in the NIT basketball tournament, and Zawistowski was frustrated that alumni from around the country were unable to share in the experience, since the game would not be available on national radio or TV. To solve the problem, he placed speakerphones in his office and played the radio broadcast of the game to alums that had called in and listened over their telephones! The alums loved it, and wanted to call every game.

The TEAMLINE® idea was born but it was not until 1990 that the idea became a reality on a national scale. Today, alumni, fans, and parents of the athletes can hear their games over any telephone by calling TEAMLINE® during any live game at 1-800-846-4700 and entering their team's four digit code. Fans can call from any phone including home, office, cellular, hotel, airplane - even internationally.

Alumni and booster groups benefit from the service as well. Numerous groups around the country have parties on football Saturdays where they rent a restaurant, call TEAMLINE® during the pre-game show and have the game played over the PA system so everyone can hear. “It is a great way to get the spirit going and have some fun. It sounds like you're on the sidelines, and it really conveys the emotion of the game.” claims Zawistowski. A portion of the proceeds from every call to TEAMLINE® are paid to the athletic rights holders to help support their athletics program.

Since 1990 TRZ has provided live coverage of over 800,000 live events ranging from football, basketball, baseball, softball, hockey, lacrosse, volleyball and auto races. Since new teams are always joining the service fans can check the TEAMLINE web site to search for their favorite team's code at www.TEAMLINE.cc.

[edit] Miracle Heart

Miracle Heart is a BL game dating sim adventure released in 2001 in Japan. With a choose your own adventure style gameplay, it relies on text based story, themed music and well-drawn characters with a variety of expressions to move the game along. The characters are gradeschool age and focus on love and romance while censoring the more graphic areas.

[edit] Characters

  • Kakeru Kidajima - main
  • Natsuki Washimiya
  • Natsumi Washimiya
Spoiler warning: Plot and/or ending details about opening gameplay follow.
Set in modern day Japanese all-boys school, the plot revolves around one boy, Kakeru Kidajima. As a boy he met and fell in love with another boy Natsumi Washimiya. They talked of love and marriage, as children do, until the day Kakeru moved away. The fond memories of the past become nothing more than fading dreams until he starts a new year at school and meets up with Natsuki Washimiya. This new boy carries the same face and last name as his once beloved. Kakeru investigates to see if it was a name change or if this new boy knows what happened. Will Kakeru find his childhood love, find a new love in Natsuki, or fall for the boys that help him along the way? Only time will tell.

[edit] Jim Parisi

Jim Parisi is currently a radio talk show host in Arizona. James Parisi was born in Providence, Rhode Island. He began his career in radio news, before becoming a television news anchor and reporter. He appears as himself in the film Everybody Wins, with Nick Nolte and Debra Winger in 1990. During his TV news career Parisi had exclusive, personal interviews with then-President George Bush, and Bill Clinton in 1992. Parisi later managed newsrooms for television stations throughout the United States, lastly leading the CBS station in Albany New York, WRGB-TV 6, in 1996. Jim Parisi is also the current editor of TV Newz, which is an on-line publication for the television news industry, and The Coastal Channel, an internet TV channel for ocean-related news.

[edit] Blues Matters

Blues Matters is both a record label and magazine.


Blues Matters!' Intention

Blues Matters! aims to promote and support the blues in all forms, and provide a service to music fans everywhere, of 'Blues without the Blinkers'. We try to represent every aspect of the blues, will all the seriousness, humour, depth, belief and enthusiasm it deserves, to bring together the music, artists, publications, labels, industry, and fans, to enjoy and sustain the Blues for further generations.

Blues Matters!' Story So Far

Blues Matters! was created out of frustration that British Blues did not get the credit it deserved since the 60’s or now.

In the early 1990's, Blues Matters! started as a fanzine for a British blues band and by 1997 had grown to include exposure for other bands. Demand for Blues Matters! meant that by 2000, the 'fanzine' grew to an impressive 120 page 'magazine' to give more bands and enthusiasts a voice, packed full of interviews, reviews and previews of artists, CD's, DVD's, gigs, festivals, music products, post artists' gigs, and exchange information on blues and music. In 2001, Blues Matters! launched as a limited company that reflected the magazines growth and new opportunities arising …

Blues Matters! reputation for representing British Blues was soon recognized in the industry, and by 2004 boasted 3 Record Labels with 25 recording artists and releases, a music publishing company, a National Blues Gig Guide, merchandise, Blues Music Store, and loads more.

So much can and needs to be done for the blues but it's pretty fragmented. Blues Matters! unbrella was needed to help 'champion the blues', spread the word, and promote the wealth of talented artists and music. Blues Matters! success comes from trying hard to give the artists and industry the recognition and promotion they ought to have ... the title says it all really! ...

Blues Matters! Magazine

From an 80 page A5 (printed in blue) to a whopping 120 page A5 (with colour) the magazine has passed it’s 30th issue and growing ... with a perfect bound spine, more colour, and more content flexibility. The future will include published in other languages!

The A5 size is very convenient, compact, portable, and an ideal bookshelf item that readers collect and use for reference. Packed full of blues, Blues Matters! magazine is the ideal hit for all your musical needs!

Blues Matters! Records

Springing from the success of the magazine can Blues Matters! Record Label, to actively get great acts to people’s attention. The label has released 20 new albums in less than four years, and is being hailed as the UK’s biggest ever independent Blues Record Label. You can read about BM artists and listen to their music here!. The future will see some USA and European acts joining the ‘BM International’ label, to add to the impressive list of very talented British performers.

BM artist talent is illustrated by regular gigs and appearances on shows like Paul Jones’ Blues Show on BBC Radio 2 and various local and international radio, feeding a very thirsty blues public!. You can listen to some tremendous acts on our Radio Shows, sample tracks, and mail order.

The Future

Blues Matters! now has long-awaited recognition; receiving a Welsh Assembly Government Grant in 2004 which enabled new premises and more staff.

The patience, hard work, and enthusiasm of the team at HQ, and with a dedicated team of writers and contributors across the UK and beyond makes it easier to bring you the very latest on the great artists that are out there.

The loyal support of our readers and customers is as always, immeasurable, and allows Blues Matters! to re-invest in the blues and help move forward solidly to bring the blues to you.

How can you get involved in Blues Matters!

So that's the basic story. You can get involved in Blues Matters! and ensure the blues and the music stays near to us all in loads of ways:

• Try out Blues Matters! by subscribing to the magazine; jam-packed full of blues and with loads of benefits like free delivery, free entry into competitions, free blues Gig Guide, discounted music, and loads more ...

• You can buy the latest issue at selected record stores, and catch up to some quality interviews in our back issues section.

• Read about Blues Matters! talented performers, listen to samples from their albums, and check out where the best blues artists are playing next in our Gig Guide.

• Visit our online store for a huge range of BM and other blues artists, records, and merchandise.

Blues Matters! aim to bring you everything - from live events, artists, features, albums, information, gigs, merchandise, news, discussion, publications, and loads more. You can also receive the latest blues news, free, with our monthly Blues Matters! newsletter.

So help represent the many talented acts out there by supporting what matters, the blues, the Blues Matters!!!!!!

[edit] Neo-Eldarin

Neo-Eldarin is a term that may be used to describe the language of texts attempting to actually use the "Elven" tongues invented by British author and philologist J.R.R. Tolkien for his Middle-earth legendarium. (The word Eldarin means "Elvish" in Quenya, one of the languages of Middle-earth.) While Tolkien sketched an Elvish language family with many branches, such efforts primarily focus on the two main Elven-tongues of the legendarium, namely Quenya (High-elven, the ancient ritual language of the Elves) and Sindarin (Grey-elven, the daily speech of the Elves in Middle-earth).

[edit] Neo-Quenya and Neo-Sindarin

Most texts produced to date are in Neo-Quenya, since Quenya is by far the most well-attested language in published Tolkien material. The first substantial post-Tolkien attempt to write an Eldarin text may be Bj&oeuml;rn Fromén's Neo-Quenya poem Valinorenna, appearing in the pioneering Tolkien-linguistic work An Introduction to Elvish (1978, edited by Jim Allan).

The most widely-published examples of Neo-Sindarin are unquestionably the "Elvish" dialogue developed by David Salo for Peter Jackson's movie trilogy based on Tolkien's Lord of the Rings novel. Except for the samples of Sindarin taken directly from the book (such as Gandalf's invocation before the doors of Moria), Salo put together these lines based on his own understanding of Sindarin grammar, extrapolating where Tolkien material available to him was insufficient. This particular dialect of Neo-Sindarin is sometimes called Movie Sindarin.

Asked why they produce Neo-Eldarin texts, writers may cite various motivations. Tolkien himself wrote that The Lord of the Rings was "largely an essay in 'linguistic aesthetic'" (The Letters of J.R.R. Tolkien, p. 219-220), and writers may want to celebrate the peculiar aesthetic of Tolkien's Elvish. To some it will be an attempt to immerse themselves in the world of Middle-earth. Others will be interested primarily in the languages as such, and try to learn them as some kind of intellectual challenge.

As for the movies, Peter Jackson apparently wanted to include Elvish dialogues for effect, and David Salo set out to produce an approximation of Tolkien's Elvish as well as he could reconstruct it.

Especially after the appearance of the Jackson movies, many people wanted brief "Elvish" inscriptions for rings (often wedding-rings), tattoos and the like. These people rarely take the time to study Eldarin in depth for themselves; rather they may request "expert" help on Tolkien-linguistic mailing-lists, or contact individual Tolkien-linguists directly. Typically such inquirers also want the Elvish message to be written in the "original" Tengwar script devised by Tolkien for his languages. They feel attracted to the magical aura and aesthetic qualities of "Elvish", but may not have a deeper scholarly interest in Tolkien's work. Writers intending to compose longer texts must by necessity penetrate far deeper into the linguistic "lore" relating to Tolkien's languages.

[edit] Neo-Eldarin vs. Tolkien's Original Work

The exact relationship between Neo-Eldarin and Tolkien's original Quenya and Sindarin is difficult to define. First of all, it should be understood that none of these languages mentioned exist as monolithic, fixed entities that can readily be compared to one another. Neo-Quenya and Neo-Sindarin texts necessarily reflect the understanding (and to some extent, the preferences) of the individual authors. Various individuals may interpret certain grammatical details in different ways, and the understanding of an individual author may also change over time.

In particular, the occasional publication of hitherto unknown Tolkien material may cause Neo-Eldarin writers to revise the conventions they have been using: Since Eldarin grammar is reconstructed from a very limited corpus, the appearance of even a few new lines of Tolkien-made Eldarin text may sometimes significantly shift the balance of the evidence.

If the linguistic conventions used by Neo-Eldarin writers may change, this is even more true of Tolkien's original work on the languages. He worked on them for half a century, but never achieved definite Eldarin grammars (which is why there is still room for personal interpretation when samples of Elvish are to be analyzed). While most of his linguistic manuscripts remain unpublished, it is already clear from published material that they contain layer upon layer of changing ideas rather than a single, unified vision of what Eldarin was "really" like. The language generally referred to as Sindarin even had its name and internal history revised immediately before the publication of the last volume of the Lord of the Rings trilogy in 1955: When Tolkien actually wrote the trilogy, he thought of this language as "Noldorin" instead, ascribing its origin to the Noldor elves rather than the Sindar.

Since Tolkien himself revised the languages so often, it can be difficult to directly compare "Tolkien's Elvish" to the Neo-Eldarin conventions employed by any post-Tolkien writer. It is out of the question that any substantial Neo-Eldarin text can be written that agrees with all of Tolkien's linguistic writings, since these writings very often contradict themselves.

[edit] Neo-Eldarin Methodology

In principle, Neo-Eldarin texts could be based on any of the numerous conceptual phases observed in Tolkien's writings. In practice, writers almost invariably try to emulate Quenya and Sindarin as these tongues are exemplified in The Lord of the Rings. It is clear that by and large, Tolkien himself felt bound by samples of Elvish that had appeared in print, so this material is as close to "definite" or "canonical" Eldarin as one can get. Typically, Neo-Eldarin writers look to these texts as their primary normative authority.

Obviously the information that can be extracted from these few samples is in no way sufficient to reconstruct a grammar that could support even a semi-functional language. Writers therefore consider other Tolkien material as well. The fact that this material often contradicts itself is problematic from the viewpoint of Neo-Eldarin writers trying to make out definite grammatical rules. The normal approach is to adopt details of grammar that are (or seem) compatible with the samples of Elvish contained in the LotR. Most writers would also want to keep the language largely compatible with other widely-published samples of Tolkien's languages, notably those occurring in the Silmarillion (though this book was edited and published posthumously and may not be considered strictly "canonical" in all respects).

Since the "canonical" samples of Elvish are relatively brief, they do not provide a complete guide to how Tolkien's linguistic material could be edited into a unified grammar. It must be assumed that Tolkien's post-LotR writings on his languages were intended to be compatible with the samples he had already published in the novel, yet these writings still contradict themselves on many details. An editor trying to produce a unified grammar could in theory come up with a string of different "Quenyas" and "Sindarins" that would be equally Tolkienian and equally compatible with the LotR samples. While these languages would probably not be radically different from one another, certain pronominal endings and the like would differ.

An oft-cited editorial strategy would be to approximate Tolkien's final intentions, Quenya and Sindarin as he saw them near the end of his life. Some feel that this would be a quite arbitrary approach, since these late incarnations of Elvish may not be objectively "better" or more consistent than Tolkien's earlier ideas; he was not necessarily in the process of settling on definite versions of Quenya/Sindarin when he died. (Since most of Tolkien's late manuscripts remain unpublished, definite assessments of this material still cannot be made.) Others have suggested that an editor should consider primarily Tolkien's conception of the languages as it was when he actually wrote The Lord of the Rings, though most would also agree that this material should be "calibrated" against Tolkien's post-LotR ideas.

As for current attempts to write in Eldarin (especially Quenya), most writers would probably agree that the results should not be taken overly seriously, and hardly anyone would claim to have reconstructed Tolkien's intentions with absolute certainty or accuracy. (After all, he could not even agree with himself on many details.) Still, many Neo-Quenya writers would argue that the inflection of the noun is fairly well understood: During his lifetime, Tolkien sent an overview of the relevant endings to Richard Plotz, and it mostly agrees well with published samples of Quenya from the 1950s on. Some relatively trivial variations occur, as when the ending for plural ablative occurs as -llon in Plotz, but as -llor in other late texts.

The main outlines of the verb system has been reconstructed to the satisfaction of some, though there is an ongoing debate about a number of features. (For instance, the past tense of car- "do, make" is variously given as carnë and cárë in Tolkien's writings, and it is not obvious which is the best option for a Neo-Quenya writer. An early wordlist actually cites the forms side by side, so maybe both should be considered valid.) There are a few "missing" tenses, such as the pluperfect (currently only attested in a form of Quenya that far predates the LotR, and the form it had in that early incarnation of the language does not seem compatible with Tolkien's later ideas).

Quenya adjectives and adverbs are perceived as relatively unproblematic, though certain commonly held assumptions so far cannot be proved. (For instance, it is often held that adverbs can readily be derived from adjectives by adding the ending -vë; this is based on one single example from the LotR. Lacking any explicit Tolkienian statements either way, we cannot know if the author meant this ending to be as freely applicable as the English adverbial ending -ly.) For certain important conjunctions, writers still have to fall back on Tolkien's earliest writings; many would like to base such vital vocabulary on the later conceptual phases instead.

Parts of the pronoun table are problematic due to frequent revisions and changing concepts, though material published in recent years seemingly allows a fairly plausible reconstruction of a near-complete system. For certain syntactical relationships there are still no good Tolkien examples that could guide writers. The counting system is uncertain from 20 onwards, though extrapolations some would find plausible are not difficult to make. More information about numbers is known to exist, awaiting publication.

Sindarin is altogether more poorly attested and also has its own complexities (phonology and grammar being intertwined in intricate ways). The "quality" of Neo-Sindarin texts is often difficult to assess: Most writers rely on assumptions that are generally compatible with the Tolkenian samples, but these samples would frequently allow other interpretations as well. Hence various writers may base their own Neo-Sindarin texts on differing interpretations. For instance, the word ir occurring in one untranslated Sindarin poem is treated as a variant of the definite article i in David Salo's works. Others see in this ir a possible cognate of Quenya íre;, "when" introducing a temporal clause (The Lost Road p. 72). This would also allow for a sensible (though necessarily unconfirmed) translation of Tolkien's Sindarin poem. Some writers have therefore used ir for "when" in their Neo-Sindarin compositions. Others, following Salo, might use the same word as a definite article.

In the case of Sindarin, matters are further complicated by the fact that material from the pre-LotR period is strictly "Noldorin" instead, and some scholars object to including Noldorin in the Sindarin corpus. Its exclusion would however leave Neo-Sindarin writers with a vocabulary so small that actually composing in the language would be quite impossible. Quenya was at least always called Quenya (though in the pre-LotR period, Tolkien employed the spelling "Qenya"), and even though Tolkien often revised the grammar, the general style of the language remained reasonably stable over the decades. Therefore, many Neo-Quenya writers do not hesitate to use early "Qenya" vocabulary in their compositions, next to words Tolkien devised decades later. Generally, though, Neo-Eldarin writers treat Tolkien's early material as something to "fall back on" when Tolkien's later material does not suffice for their needs.

Obviously many Neo-Eldarin enthusiasts hope and expect that the eventual publication of more of Tolkien's linguistic material will fill many of the current gaps in our knowledge about the languages (and also allow writers to substitute "late" ideas where only "early" solutions are currently available).

[edit] Normalized "Useable" Eldarin?

However, it is not to be expected that even the complete publication of the entire collection (supposedly thousands of pages) will allow anyone to simply lift ready-made "complete" languages directly from Tolkien's linguistic manuscripts. If the manuscripts are eventually made available, they will at best provide an editor with options rather than definite solutions.

To some, the ultimate goal is to develop and lovingly cultivate Quenya and Sindarin to the point where they would become at least semi-useable tongues, capable of sustaining everyday conversation. Some, indeed, use the terms "Neo-Quenya" and "Neo-Sindarin" to refer to such hypothetical future entities, which could be studied and used just like other highly-developed invented languages (like Esperanto, or at least like Klingon). This must be distinguished from the current usage (the term "Neo-Quenya/Sindarin" rather referring to any post-Tolkien attempt to compose in his languages, as opposed to yet-to-be-developed normalized versions of them).

Current projects to develop "normalized Elvish" are tentative and preliminary, due to the incomplete state of the publication project aiming to present all of Tolkien's linguistic manuscripts. Editors trying to establish a normalized grammar should obviously be able to consider the entire collection before suggesting what a representative cross-section of Tolkien's most developed ideas could look like.

The initial stage of the editing process would center on the establishing of a "canon", a selection of Tolkienian ideas that are internally consistent and compatible with the samples of Elvish occurring in the LotR. The editors would not necessarily try to eliminate minor, unimportant variations (as when the Quenya word for "8" variously appears as tolto and toldo). A comprehensive wordlist would be worked out, to determine what concepts Tolkien's vocabulary covers (and what words are "missing"). Tolkien's own decisions and revisions would almost invariably be respected (as when he at one point rejected cainen as the Quenya word for "10", replacing it with quain, though he had been using cainen for decades).

Once a "canon" had been established, material incompatible with it would either be edited to agree with it, or (for this particular purpose) ignored. The editing in question would often only involve straightforward phonological "updating"; this is particularly relevant in the case of "Noldorin" as the earlier version of Sindarin. For instance, many examples from Sindarin and Noldorin show that the former has r- where the latter had rh- (unvoiced R); also, the diphthong oe in Noldorin is seen to correspond to Sindarin ae. Therefore, some editors feel free to transform a Noldorin form like rhoeg ("wrong") into Sindarin *raeg: Wholesale phonological "updating" of Noldorin material already occurs in David Salo's works. (It should be noted that most Noldorin words seem to fit the structure of Sindarin with no changes whatsoever.)

The "core" of normalized Neo-Eldarin would thus consist of a primary selection of Tolkien material that is accorded canonical (or normative) status, supplemented with material that can be made to agree with the "canon" after being subjected to a minimum of editing. Material that would have to be so heavily edited that its Tolkienian status would be compromised, would rather be ignored altogether.

Neo-Eldarin enthusiasts tend to assume that the sum total of Tolkien's linguistic manuscripts would provide options sufficient to compile develop a fairly "complete" grammar. Tolkien noted that he had developed these languages "in some completeness" (The Letters of J.R.R. Tolkien, p. 175), though it remains to be seen what this really meant from his own perspective.

On the other hand, Eldarin vocabulary is likely to remain deficient. While thousands of words are readily available, Christopher Tolkien notes as surprising the fact that his father "was so little concerned to make comprehensive vocabularies of the Elvish tongues" (The Lost Road p. 342). Many animals, tools, substances etc. never received any Tolkien-made Eldarin designations. The author developed these tongues for his own pleasure, not as means of communication, so he did not need a "complete" vocabulary.

Even after establishing a "normative core" of Tolkienian material (edited or not), would-be cultivators of Eldarin would therefore have to supplement it with newly-coined words. As presently envisioned and to some extent already practiced, this does not involve completely random invention with no basis whatsoever in Tolkien's original work. Tolkien's Elvish language family is logically derived from a "Primitive Eldarin" tongue supposed to have been spoken in the pre-historic period of his invented world. He listed a great number of primitive "roots" belonging to this language, used such roots as the basis for "primitive words", and then derived their form in the later Elvish tongues by implementing systematic sound-changes: By simulating the effects of thousands of years of linguistic development in his notes, he could work out the different branches of the Elvish language family.

The Eldarin system of derivation can be reconstructed from thousands of examples, and scholars also believe they have figured out the sets of sound-changes that are used to "produce" Quenya and Sindarin. Some researchers therefore feel able to copy Tolkien's method for deriving new words. The primitive "roots" listed by Tolkien are so numerous and so varied in meaning that it will normally be possible to coin some plausible "primitive" word for a missing concept, and then apply the established sound-laws to derive the forms this word would assume in Quenya and Sindarin. The result is a word that "could have" existed within Tolkien's linguistic framework. If one regards the Elven-tongues only as features of his invented world, such post-Tolkien additions are the equivalent of fan fiction. Many Neo-Eldarin cultivators would rather say they are trying to develop the languages as such, irrespective of the fictional context that only Tolkien could rightly define.

Other methods have also been employed to extend available Eldarin vocabulary without losing touch with Tolkien's original work. Currently, no Quenya verb "to choose" is attested, but cilmë occurs as the noun "choice", and noting that the -më is an ending used to derive abstract nouns, scholars may isolate *cil- as a very likely candidate for the verb "to choose". (Compare such an attested couple as melmë and mel-: "love" as noun and verb, respectively.) Lacking a verb "to think", writers may isolate the probable verbal stem *sana- from Tolkien's noun sanar "thinker" (since -r is an ending used to derive agent nouns).

These would be examples of words that are "deconstructed"; conversely, Tolkien's mechanisms of derivation may also be actively employed to construct new words. There is, for instance, no attested Quenya adjective meaning "visible", but there is the verb cen- "to see" and the derivational ending -ima, usually combined with lengthening of the stem-vowel of the root it is added to. This pattern corresponds to English "-able"; hence some would derive cénima as a possible word for "seeable" = "visible".

Sometimes a certain word is attested in one of Tolkien's two main Elvish languages, but not in the other. Since the Elvish languages are meant to be related, being derived from a single primitive tongue, it is possible to extrapolate the likely cognate in the other language. For instance, in Quenya the verb "to dance" is attested as lilta-, derived from a root LILT (The Lost Road p. 369). No Sindarin verb "to dance" is attested, but the cognate of the Quenya form would be *liltha-.

Such extrapolation is of course not an exact science; not all Quenya and Sindarin words are direct cognates of one another. Prior to 2002, no Sindarin noun "name" was attested; the best guess of Neo-Eldarin writers would have been *ess as the cognate of Quenya essë. As it turns out, Tolkien in one Sindarin text used the word eneth for "name"; this seems to reflect another root altogether.

Despite the uncertainties, Neo-Sindarin writers typically feel that using such extrapolated forms is infinitely better than simply coining "missing" words out of thin air, since there would then be no connection whatsoever to Tolkien's original work.

[edit] Criticism and controversy

A certain amount of controversy attaches to Neo-Eldarin efforts, especially a large-scale project to develop useable, normalized languages. Tolkien-linguists whose angle on the whole study is primarily academic may see such a project as an unwelcome distraction. In their view, "updating" and "editing" the material (like transforming Noldorin rhoeg into extrapolated Sindarin *raeg) would be quite unwarranted tampering with the authentic Tolkienian evidence. Neo-Eldarin supporters may respond that such efforts are in no way intended to supplant or supercede the original sources, least of all for the purpose of academic studies. They merely want to suggest what a possible normalized version of Tolkien's Elvish could look like, if one wants to compose in such a language. Even if they decide to ignore certain manuscripts altogether (because the ideas expressed are incompatible with a normalized grammar), this does not imply any spiteful "rejection" of these ideas as inherently inferior.

Some claim that even for scholarly and academic purposes, normalized versions of Quenya and Sindarin would be useful. New students could then study tidied-up versions of these languages and get an impression of their general structure before they try to tackle the potentially daunting complexities of the primary sources with their many layers of shifting ideas. In a similar vein, ancient languages like Old Norse are often taught in a normalized version that is quite idealized compared to the actual ancient manuscripts and inscriptions. Critics may argue that the never-ending changes in Tolkien's conception of his languages are an integral part of his work on them, so that a normalized version would be a quite artificial construct.

Comparisons have been made with the Silmarillion, a book Christopher Tolkien edited together from manuscripts of varying age, even writing certain paragraphs himself. It was still published and received as his father's work. People supporting a Neo-Eldarin standard may therefore argue that even if editors produce normalized versions of Quenya and Sindarin (even supplementing Tolkien's original work with newly-derived words), the resulting tongues may still be thought of as being essentially the languages Tolkien invented. Critics may reject the analogy, feeling that editing a book is something quite different from normalizing a language. (Also, Christopher Tolkien later expressed doubts about whether producing a unified Silmarillion was the right thing to do; he came to regret some of his editing decisions.)

Tolkien himself wrote that "of interest to some, and agreeable to me" would be "an historical grammar of Quenya and Sindarin and a fairly extensive etymological vocabulary of these languages" (The Letters of J.R.R. Tolkien, p. 381). He never got around to publishing such a work, but if he had, it would presumably have presented "definite" versions of the languages. Supporters of Neo-Eldarin may cite this as evidence that Tolkien was not in principle opposed to such "standard" versions. However, he obviously meant that it was he himself, and not some later editor, that would write the grammar envisioned.

As for post-Tolkien compositions, controversies continue as to whether Tolkien's languages either can or should have any existence beyond the author's own life, and outside the invented world associated with them. Some critics refuse to recognize any post-Tolkien Eldarin composition as "authentic" Quenya or Sindarin, even if all the vocabulary is Tolkien-made and the grammar employed is quite uncontroversial.

For instance, there are probably few Tolkien-linguists (of any camp) who would deny that i Elda lendë i ciryanna is a plausible way of expressing "the Elf went to the ship" in Quenya. Some would still refuse to call this authentic Quenya, since to them "authentic" means "written by Tolkien" and nothing else. Neo-Eldarin authors may claim that to the extent it is possible to reconstruct and understand the structure of Tolkien's languages, it must also be possible to actively use this knowledge to write fresh texts in them. Discussions tend to degenerate into hair-splitting arguments about what is meant by the word "authentic" in such a context.

A few critics regard post-Tolkien attempts to write in his languages as some sort of forgery, and from this perspective it is quite irrelevant how accurately a text may seem to reproduce Tolkien's grammar. Tolkien-linguist Patrick Wynne thus remarks that "skillful counterfeits are, in the end, just as phony as clumsy ones" (from a posting to the Elfscript list, March 28, 2004). If this very negative assessment is seen as representing one extreme in the range of opinions, the other extreme would be the belief that qualified Tolkien-linguists can produce texts that are every bit as authentic and normative as Tolkien's own. The more common attitude among Neo-Eldarin writers would rather be that even though they do their best to reproduce Tolkien's Elvish, they make no grandiose claims of total success. The very fact that writers try to closely emulate the patterns observed in Tolkien's texts has made some claim that Neo-Eldarin is hampered by "the dead hand of classicism", but writers obviously have no other authority they can turn to.

Focusing on the languages as they exist "synchronically" and trying to develop (semi-)useable forms of Quenya and Sindarin is dismissed by some as a project that little resembles Tolkien's own work. Christopher Tolkien notes that "my father was perhaps more interested in the processes of change than he was in displaying the structure and use of the languages at any given time" (The Lost Road, p. 342). If so one could argue that a project which focuses on the "final" version of the languages (rather than their evolution through ages of imaginary time) would differ significantly from Tolkien's own perspective: The focus would shift from diachronic to synchronic linguistics.

Neo-Eldarin practitioners may respond that no one is obliged to consider these languages only from only the angle Tolkien himself possibly preferred. Moreover, the more accomplished among them do study and appreciate "the processes of change" Tolkien envisioned, actively using this knowledge to derive new words from his Primitive Elvish roots. Enthusiasts may indeed be committed to preserving the interrelationship between Quenya and Sindarin that Tolkien intended, developing their Neo-Eldarin incarnations in parallel to make sure they do not become a mismatched couple.

Since grammar must be reconstructed from relatively few Tolkien examples, many conclusions must remain tentative, but for Neo-Eldarin purposes a certain grammatical theory may be treated as "fact" and used as the basis for new texts. At the same time, it must be remembered that it is only a "theory" if one is studying Tolkien's languages from an academic angle. A potential criticism of Neo-Eldarin is therefore that it can lead the unwary to believe that certain theories are actually well-established facts.

[edit] Reyn Ouwehand

Reyn Ouwehand (born 2 August 1973) grew up in a village called Katwijk aan Zee situated at the coast of Holland. Reyn's musical career started off with classical pianolessons at a young age. He went to the 'Havo voor Muziek en Dans' in Rotterdam, Holland which is a school were you get music or ballet besides your normal courses. He studied 2 major courses: piano and 'toegepaste electronica' which is a study for studio-engineering and synthesizer-programming. In the mean time Reyn was busy making music for videogames for the Commodore 64 and Amiga from 1988 till 1991 but stopped when he continued his studies at the conservatory in Rotterdam at the age of 19.

In 1995 Reyn founded his own company called Prevue Productions and built his first studio. From then on his main focus was production work for record-companies. Things went really well and he continues to be much in demand as a producer and as a studio musician, and is building reputation writing film soundtracks.

Now in his third studio Reyn's national production work include famous dutch acts like Kane, Ellen ten Damme, La Kidda, Sita, Birgit, Madigan, Silkstone, Handsome 3some and Wyatt. but he is also gaining territory in France, Belgium and Switserland with acts like Benjamin Biolay, Stephan Eicher, Souad Massi, Indochine, Mayane Delem and Isabelle Boulay.

[edit] Sliver (Magic: The Gathering)

'Sliver' is the name of a creature type in the card game, Magic: The Gathering. Like some other creature types, 'Sliver' identifies that the card will have a certain mechanic - in this case, the "Sliver mechanic."

The "Sliver mechanic" is an ability which is structured like this:
"All Slivers [gain ability]", or an ability which otherwise applies to all Slivers at all times. The Sliver mechanic applies to the Sliver it's on, as well as all other Slivers, even your opponent's.

The only exceptions as of the release of Dissension, are Sliver Queen, Sliver Overlord and Metallic Sliver. The Queen and Overlord have abilities which relate to Slivers but don't share this ability with all other Slivers. Metallic Sliver was simply an artifact creature which had the type Sliver and no abilities.

Because Slivers became exponentially more powerful as more entered play, they clearly rewarded the building of a "Sliver deck". Undoubtedly, there are a group of Sliver fans waiting for their return, rumoured in an article by Mark Rosewater.

[edit] Fomorii

The Fomorii were the sea gods in Irish myths, who were extremely violent and misshapen. They are described as having only one eye, one hand, or one foot. It is said that the Fomorii emerged from the waves of the ocean and challenged the rulers of Ireland, the Firbolg and the Tuatha De Danann. It was the Tuatha De Danann, who defeated them in battle.

[edit] Brooklyn, Maryland

Brooklyn is the southernmost neighborhood of Baltimore City, and is named after its counterpart in New York City because both communities are across a body of water from the city's downtown area. Brooklyn is a traditional blue-collar neighborhood and is home to 9,500 Baltimore City residents. Many residents work at the multitude of factories, import/export facilities of the Port of Baltimore, or other industrial plants in the surrounding area. Brooklyn has a mix of single-family homes, duplexes, and rowhomes.

[edit] Brooklyn, Maryland

Brooklyn is the southernmost neighborhood of Baltimore City. It is named after its counterpart in New York City because both communities are across a body of water from the city's downtown area. Brooklyn is a traditional blue-collar neighborhood and is home to 9,500 Baltimore City residents, many of whom work at the multitude of factories, import/export facilities of the Port of Baltimore, or other industrial plants in the surrounding area. Brooklyn has a mix of single-family homes, duplexes, and rowhomes, and is home to two prominent parks with panoramic views the Baltimore Harbor: Garrett Park and the much larger Farring-Baybrook Park. Brooklyn is located minutes from Baltimore's Inner Harbor, Baltimore-Washington Thurgood Marshall International Airport, and Maryland State captial Annapolis.

[edit] Jackson Whites

In the Northern part of New Jersey, in the Ramapo Mountains, right near the New York State line, live people who used to be called the Jackson Whites. Good luck trying to trace their origins, too: their surnames would indicate they're Dutch, but come from a mixed grouping of people that include African-Americans, Native Americans, and Europeans, possibly of both Dutch and Hessian descent. The name comes from the old way of referring to hill people/freed slaves as "Jacks," and was likely a combination of "Jacks" and "Whites." These days, they prefer to be referred to as "Ramapo Mountain People."

Concentrated around the Mahwah area, historical articles about the group suggest they'd developed their own dialect mixing English and Dutch; other legends suggest they're a mix of prostitutes who wandered off to an area that was thought sympathetic to outsiders. As is typical of secluded types, most of what has been written about them-at least some decades ago -- is of the fantastical variety rather than based in any sort of reality, suggesting that they're something less than human beings.

By most accounts, however, they were indeed quite private, guarding their mountainous territory vigilantly. America is full of clannish types, but the idea of such a group existing, even all the way through to the 1970s, in an area just thirty miles from teeming, overrun New York City, in some ways, is indeed a bit strange.

www.blacktable.com

  • Article already exists as Ramapough Mountain Indians, and Jackson Whites redirects to it. Tearlach 10:23, 19 May 2006 (UTC)

The Tryptamine Experience (or T.E. for short) is a one man electronic music project who mastered his own style entitled "Deathtronica". Blending Ambience, horror themes, drum and base, and experimental styles John Richard Putignano Jr. is the driving force.

The project began in 2001, under the name "The Rabbi Hitler" in Seekonk MA while he was in foster care. His first release was entitled "Get up and Sit down". A bizzare 100 song demo of weird electronic/techno mix. Early on,T.E. recieved much criticism about musical content. Horror movie and Third Reich samples were rampant and the name "Deathtronica" was first coined by John during an experience on the designer drug "Foxy".

T.E. has gone through many musical changes, releasing almost two dozen releases. Currently in the works is "Endogenous" and John describes the cd as "More atmospheric, and much more serious. I decided to take a more mature route for the Tryptamine Experience is a forever evolving project"

[edit] Takamaka Bay Rum

Takamaka Bay Rum is the first privatly owned distillery in Seychelles to export their product, started by Richard and Bernard d'Offay in 2002, Takamaka Bay has become the most popular Rum in Seychelles and achieved almost cult like status amoung tourists and regional countries!

Takamaka Bay exports it's three products, Takamaka Bay Dark Rum, Takamaka Bay White Rum and Takamaka Bay Coco to South Africa as well as Europe.

Richard and Bernard d'Offay are originally from the Seychelles but went to school in South Africa, their family was one of the first six family's to settle in Seychelles in the late 1700s! They continued to holiday in Seychelles as children and always felt a strong bond with the island.

“Distilling has always been in our family.” As children the brothers would watch their grandfather distil small amounts of rum to sell to friends in Seychelles.

“I was always blown away by what you could create from nothing.”

After completing school – Richard at Victoria Park and Bernard d'Offay at Woodridge – Richard and Bernard both studied marketing at P.E Technikon, Richard then left P.E and was working in London when Bernard phoned him with the idea of opening a distillery in the Seychelles.

“I thought: What did we know about rum? But I went to the Seychelles to investigate the possibility and started applying for licences and lobbying government ministries for support.”

“In the meanwhile Bernard was working on getting the rum blend right. He is the distiller and trained in Sweden and England.” The first bottle was produced in March 2002 with the distillery a success right from the start.

From distilling, bottling and labelling their products themselves, the D’Offay brothers now have an automatic bottling line and bigger stills and can produce up to 20 000 bottles a month.

The rum’s unique flavour epitomises its origin. “It reflects what the Seychelles is about. Everywhere you go there are palm trees, fruit and vanilla trees with a smell of cinnamon in the air.”

To take your rum like a true Seychellois, drink it on ice with freshly squeezed lemon and sugar.

“It’s the spirit of the Seychelles.”

[edit] Shlomo Avineri - Bielsko-Biala

Israeli political scientist. Born in Bielsko, 1933, immigrated to Israel in 1939. Studied at the Hebrew University of Jerusalem and the London School of Economics. Professor of Political Science at the Hebrew University, where he served as Dean of the Social Science Faculty. He held numerous visiting appointments abraod (Yale, Cornell, Oxford, Budapest) and in 1975-77 served as Director-General of Israel's Ministry of Foreign Affairs. In 1996 his was awarded the Israel Prize, the country's highest civilian decoration. Among his books: "The Social and Political Thought of Karl Marx", "Hegel's Theory of the Modern State", "Israel and the Palestinians", "The Making of Modern Zionism", "Moses Hess: Prophet of Communism and ZIonism".

[edit] Price Quotation System

Retail and consumer foreign exchange transactions in most countries use a price quotation system. This means that a foreign currency is quoted in terms of the local currency of the dealer. For example, if an individual asks a bank in Canada for a rate on dollars, the dealer tells the customer how many Canadian Dollars equal one US dollar. That is, the dealer quotes US dollars against Canadian dollars. The US dollar is the foreign currency and the Canadian dollar is the local currency of the dealer for the Canadian bank. USD 1.00 = CAD 1.48

[edit] Reubensfrau Effect

The Reubensfrau Effect is a philosophical phenomenon which states that the probable subjective utility of possibles outcomes for a game theory two player game will be dramatically increased if the total value of the game, in either outcome, will be negative.

[edit] Organic versus Conventional

When was the last occasion you ate a fatal poison? It was probably the last meal you just ate packed with harmful pesticides. If you just ate some conventional peaches, apples, strawberries, nectarines, pears, cherries, red raspberries, imported grapes, spinach, bell peppers, celery, potatoes, or hot peppers, those are the most contaminated. (www.downtoearth.org) Did you know that 63% of Americans eat conventional foods loaded with harmful pesticides? (www.ota.com) The remaining 37% eat organic food at least most of their day. Though I’m thinking that it’d be better to be in the 37 percentile.

If you recently ate a conventional apple, that apple had 20 to 30 artificial poisons on its skin, even after rinsing. (www.organicfood.co.uk) The UK Soil Association reported that 50 to 93 percent of pesticides remained on potatoes, apples and broccoli after washing. (www.organicfood.co.uk) To add to that if you had a salad with conventional lettuce that lettuce was sprayed with pesticides 25 times before harvest and before the time it reached your mouth. (www.organicfood.co.uk)

Why is this so alarming? Because food is very important in the American lifestyle and most don’t pay attention to these facts (www.organicfood.co.uk)! Unfortunately the food some Americans (www.organicfood.co.uk) choose is not the best for them. Some don’t choose foods with adequate nutritional value, don’t eat correct, or they eat a high number of foods sprayed with harmful chemicals, also known as conventional foods. (www.organicfood.co.uk) Did you know that currently about 500 additives are used in the conventional farming process? Some of which have been linked to allergic reactions (www.organicfood.co.uk), headaches, asthma, hyper ness in children, heart disease and osteoporosis to name a few. Examples of these additives include aspartame, colorings, and monosodium glutamate, or MSG (www.downtoearth.org). Aspartame can be found in sugar free gum (www.organicfood.co.uk) and no calorie sweeteners. MSG can be found in some potato chips, Asian foods, beef jerky, and other foods. (Janae Mcvean, 2006) Organic food is defined as food produced without the use of artificial pesticides, herbicides, and in many definitions genetically modified organisms or GMO’s. (www.organicfood.co.uk) GMO’s are foods that have been genetically changed, which means that their genetic makeup (www.organicfood.co.uk) has been altered by technology. (www.wikipedia.org) Two examples of that would be now they are making salmon that are genetically engineered to make their mouths bigger so they can eat more to make them fatter. Also they are making rice with higher content of Beta Carotene. (Interview Tim Cunningham 2006) Beta Carotene is a form of carotene which the body converts into vitamin A. (www.dictionary.com) Too much of anything can be harmful to your body which is why this could be a problem. So now your asking, “Well why does that matter?” because conventional foods just don’t harm your body (www.organicfood.co.uk), but the people who harvest them. Did you know that intensive farming could seriously damage a conventional farm workers health? It’s true! There is a higher instance of cancer, respiratory problems and other major diseases in farm workers on non-organic farms. (www.organicfood.co.uk) Animals and the environment are also harmed through conventional farming. Did you know non-organic pigs are routinely taken from their mothers after birth and given antibiotics? Also non-organic chickens are kept in crammed and tight conditions and are pumped full of hormones and antibodies! (www.organicfood.co.uk) However organic cows are a different story. On my milk carton, yes my milk carton, it lists four different steps on how to raise an organic cow so I’ll list the most important one. “Keep her healthy the old fashioned way, with a clean environment and attentive natural and homeopathic care – NO antibiotic drugs.” (My Horizon Organic milk carton). Moreover on that subject these are the words of the author of the web page www.organic(www.organicfood.co.uk)food.co.uk, Ysanne Spevack, “…if you simply like the idea of your children and grandchildren being able to visit the countryside and play in the forests and fields just like we did when we were young, go organic for the sake of all of our futures!” (www.organicfood.co.uk). Did you know that if only ¾% of conventional cropland went organic, it would be equal to taking 1,174,400 cars off the road, and that’s only three fourths! (Food to Live By, Earthbound Organic Brochure, 2004) Also the fertilizers and pesticides used in the soils of conventional farming have been identified as major sources of pollution of natural springs and aquifers. ( (www.organicfood.co.uk) Taste Life, The Organic Choice, David Richard) Organic and conventional foods both have their good things and their bad things. For example a bad thing about organic food is the cost. However there is evidence that if all indirect costs of conventional foods were factored into the price of the food, organic food would cost the same maybe even cheaper than conventional food. Also the prices of organic products reflect the actual cost of productions because organic growers don’t receive the same amo(www.organicfood.co.uk)unt of government support that conventional farms do. So really your paying extra for the intensive labor put into farming organic foods. (www.downtoearth.org) Also the availability of organic foods is another bad thing. I know this for a fact because there are only two certified organic grocery stores in Amarillo! (www.organicfood.co.uk) Which means that all produce is organic and there is no conventional produce. Tim Cunningham who is the nutritional guide at Eat Rite Heath Food Store said, “ Yes, I think that we should (www.organicfood.co.uk) have a wider variety of organic food choices.” (Interview Tim Cunningham 2006) As I’ve been mentioning, organic food has many more positives than negatives. For example, better taste was found (Interview Tim Cunningham 2006) and higher nutritional value. (Interview Tim Cunningham 2006) Actually, organically grown potatoes, oranges, and leafy vegetables have more vitamin C than conventionally grown products. (www.wikipedia.org) Also it’s mentioned that organic food contains on average 50% more vitamins, minerals, enzymes, and other nutrients than conventionally farmed produce. (www.organicfood.co.uk) (www.organicfood.co.uk) Contrary to what I have been mentioning, conventional foods also have their good things as well. (www.organicfood.co.uk) They are available in any non-organic super markets, they are cheaper, and there is more variety. Nevertheless my opinion stays the same, I personally choose organic. (www.organicfood.co.uk)

Before I end my paper, I would like to state one thing. By reading this paper you have probably learned a lot of things about what people put into their bodies. Now I’m not saying that you should drop the grapes and strawberries and run to Eat Rite, I’m saying that maybe we should all consider about what we are putting into our bodies and the quantities of conventional food we are consuming. American’s (www.organicfood.co.uk) can take action in a healthier eating lifestyle through eating right and eating foods not sprayed with harmful chemicals also known as organic. Eating a variety of organic foods can be a simple way to just be safer and healthier! (www.organicfood.co.uk)

[edit] Neal Jandreau

Born in 1979, Neal Jandreau and his two brothers grew up as "Air Force Brats" moving from place to place, including Germany and the U.S. Midwest. Finally landing in Fort Kent, Maine, Neal became a noted soccer player in both high school and college. In fact, he was kicking a soccer ball before he could properly walk.

It was in this small town at the top of Maine that he discovered a passion for music. Inspired by singer/songwriter Darius Rucker of Hootie and the Blowfish, in 1995 at the age of 16, he tried his hand at playing guitar. Joining a local band was next. He credits this experience with taking his life in a distinctly musical direction. "I met 4 amazing individuals and 1 kindred spirit. I am convinced that music is a stronger connection than love. We played where and when we could and grew up together and out of High School. What an experience."[1]

After playing with other bands during college, he started singing and writing original songs. He recorded and copyrighted "Ashamed", his first song in 2005. Along with the guitar player on "Ashamed", C.J.Theriault, he formed Still Frame. This acoustic duo played around northern Maine for several months, and lead several enthusiastic open mic sessions that involved other local musicians and college students.

Neal currently lives in the Portland, Maine area and works with his long time friend and musical conspirator, Jack Murray at Jack's production company Odds Are Productions.

"My passion for love and life is evident through my music and vocals and is what drives me to write and perform."[2]

[edit] [Great Cockrow Railway]

After the death of Sir John Samuel, who had founded the Greywood Central Railway in 1946 at a private address in Walton-on-Thames, the publisher Ian Allan purchased everything and in 1968 created the Great Cockrow Railway in Lyne near Chertsey. Since then, the GCR has grown to 5 miles in length and demonstrates 1950s prototypical British signalling methods.
