[edit] Lorna Tolentino

If there are images in this attachment, they will not be displayed. Download the original attachment

Lorna Tolentino

If she were a Hollywood actress, she’ll be Jodie Foster no less. While children her age were playing wantonly in the backyard, Lorna Tolentino, like the precocious Jodie, was already tugging at moviegoers’ hearts.

The future Grandslam Queen of Philippine Cinema (where grand slam means successive wins in all award-giving bodies for a single performance in a movie) started her career at seven, and with great flourish at that. Lorna, still in pigtails and bobby socks, and with an aunt hovering beside her, bested more than 500 candidates in the search for someone to play the young Susan Roces, Queen of Philippine Cinema in Divina Gracia (Divine Grace). She emerged the top choice in a hotly-contested public voting where the young finalists were all adjudged talented and promising.

It was an auspicious start for Lorna, who found herself being directed by no less than the late King of Philippine Cinema Fernando Poe Jr. (a.k.a. FPJ).

Da King, as FPJ is fondly called, also produced the film. The man many believed could have given Philippine President Gloria Macapagal-Arroyo a stiff fight for the highest office in the land, lived long enough to see his discovery bloom from an untested talent to one of the country’s most respected actresses.

Lorna’s dramatic acting in Divina Gracia created such an impact, Lea Productions, one of the biggest movie outfits in the `70s, signed her up to a contract. The film company believed in her so much, it didn’t have second thoughts about casting her in a big dramatic outing with internationally-renowned director Lino Brocka. The 1971 film, Lumuha Pati nga Anghel (Even the Angels Cried) gave Lorna her first award – that of Best Child Actress from the oldest award-giving body in the Philippines, the FAMAS (Filipino Academy of Movie Arts and Sciences). One moving portrayal deserves another. Not long after, Lorna again made moviegoers cry in FPJ Productions’ Mga Anghel na Walang Langit (Angels Without a Heaven).

Drama may be where she started. But Lorna is versatile enough to swing from tears to laughter with ease. This she proved in such comedies as My Little One, Pag-ibig Mo Buhay Ko (Your Love is My Life), Batya at Palo-Palo(Basin and Laundry Beater,, with Fernando Poe Jr.) and Mediavillo (with future husband, multi-awarded actor Rudy Fernandez).

Lorna also shared the screen with Dolphy, the Philippine King of Comedy no less, in Biyenan Ko ang Aking Anak (My Mother-in-Law is My Child).

At the tender age of 14, when other actors were in the so-called awkward stage and wanting for roles, Lorna was getting juicy assignments.

She graduated from child performer to lead actress roles, the first of which was Cubao Cinema Films’ Sariwang Damo, Matandang Kabayo (Fresh Grass, Old Horse), which was retitled as Langit Ko ang Pag-Ibig Mo (Your Love is My Heaven).

Lorna then pitted acting prowess with multi-awarded actor-director Eddie Garcia in a semi-comedy love drama story, Subok na Matatag (Tried and Tested as Stable). The movie saw local movie outfit and Hongkong Cinema Films joining forces for better results.

One film after another came in quick succession in a span of just one year. Lorna starred with Chiquito, an

established actor-comedian in Boss, Basta Ikaw Wa Na Ko Say (Boss, As Long as It’s You, I Have Nothing More to Say), written by the award-winning Efren Abueg. Leap Year Ngayon, Lagot Ka, Pipikutin Kita (You’re Done In; It’s Leap Year, I Will Force You to Marry Me), was with FAMAS awardee Christopher de Leon. More movies with veteran actors followed: Isang Dalagita (One Young Maiden) with the award-winning Tirso Cruz III, Tutol ang Lupa (The Earth Refuses) with Fred Galang and Apoy sa Ibabaw (Fire from Above) with Romeo Vasquez.

By then, Lorna’s name was already sparkling like a priceless diamond. The year 1978 saw her getting as much as 13 movie offers from various film outfits. Those she accepted proved all the more that she’s an actress to reckon with.

The comedy-drama Gorgonia, based on a well-acclaimed comics serial, cast her as an effeminate’s adopted daughter.

Dulce Amor … Ina (Dulce Amor … Mother), where she played the title role of a young mother exposed to and harassed by the world’s evils, won critical and box-office acclaim. By earning the nod, not only of the general public but hard-nosed film critics as well, Lorna joined the league of big stars in Philippine cinema.

Box-office success came fast and furious. Lorna’s next films, Sapagkat Kami’y Tao Lamang (Because We’re Only Human) with Christopher de Leon and Alma Moreno and Caught in the Act (with award-winning actresses Amy Austria and Gina Alajar) spelled magic at the tills.

Lorna rubbed elbows with legends of Philippine cinema: Asia’s Best Actress Charito Solis, former Miss Philippines Pilar Pilapil (Mga Huwad na Mananayaw /Fake Dancers), Rosemarie Gil and Gloria Sevilla (Baby Doll), Robert Arevalo and the late Vic Silayan (Katawang Alabok/Body of Dust), George Estregan (Paano ang Gabi Kung Wala Ka?/How Will the Night Be Without You?), Rudy Fernandez (Sa Init ng Apoy/In the Heat of Fire), Eddie Rodriguez (Magkano ang Kalayaan Mo?/How Much is Your Freedom?), Philippine superstar Nora Aunor and Johnny Delgado (Mga Uod at Rosas/Worms and Roses) and Vilma Santos (Sinasamba Kita/I Worship You).

By 1982, Lorna has tucked 55 major films under her belt. The projects were no mean feats. They delved on moral and social issues and trends, touching the lives of millions of Filipinos with such depth and magnitude.

These films, crafted under the meticulous hands of the masters themselves – respected, award-winning directors like Lino Brocka, Ishmael Bernal, Chito Rono, Romy Suzara, Jose Javier Reyes, Maryo J. delos Reyes, Emmanuel Borlaza, Marilou Diaz-Abaya, Laurice Guillen, Joel Lamangan, among others – will forever remain classics in Philippine cinema.

The best was yet to come. Year 1982 saw Lorna earning Best Actress nominations in all the award-winning bodies of Philippine Cinema for Moral (with Laurice Guillen and Gina Alajar and directed by Marilou Abaya).

The years 1973 up to the present saw Lorna harvesting a bumper crop of 49 Best Actress nominations. These promptly turned into every actor’s dream – awards – starting 1987. Lorna’s first Best Actress trophy came from three award-giving bodies – the Film Academy of the Philippines (an award given by peers, the Philippines’ equivalent of the Oscars) and the Philippine Movie Press Club’s Star Awards.

Lorna earned raves as a woman obsessed in getting a man’s love by hook or by crook in Lino Brocka’s Maging Akin Ka Lamang (Just So You Can Be Mine).

Her acting chops thus honed to perfection, Lorna reached the apex of her achievements in 1992 . That’s when her role as a mother seeking revenge for her child’s death won her all the Best Actress awards the Philippines can offer. Lorna was declared the best – bar none – by the Film Academy of the Philippines, the FAMAS, the Urian (from the Manunuri ng Pelikulang Pilipino, an exclusive circle made up of the country’s top film critics) and the Philippine Movie Press Club (an organization made up of the country’s entertainment journalists).

Lorna’s victory is called a grand slam – a rarity and an honor reserved only for the best of the best in local cinema.

Still, the public ain’t seen nothin’ yet. Lorna refused to rest on her laurels and tackled each role with the sensitivity and brilliance each of her portrayals has become noted for.

Her winning streak was simply unstoppable. She won Best Actress again, this time from the Manila Film Festival awards for Luksong Tinik (Jumping Over Thorns) where she juggled hero and anti-hero roles simultaneously. Lorna’s complex character required acting nuances that, in the hands of a lesser performer, will lose steam in no time at all. For playing a good single mother who works as courier of fake passports to raise her son on her own, Lorna won the nod of discriminating Manila Filmfest jurors.

Two years later, she played yet another mother role, this time, that of an illiterate woman who taught herself how to read and write for her children’s sake in Abakada … Ina. Lorna won three Best Actress trophies – from the Film Academy of the Philippines, the Philippine Movie Press Club’s Star Awards and the FAMAS for this sensitive portrayal.

Other Best Actress Awards included those for Kislap sa Dilim (A Glow in the Dark) from the Philippine Movie Press Club, Nagbabagang Luha (Smoldering Tears) from FAMAS and Kailan Mahuhugasan ang Kasalanan (When Will One’s Sin be Washed Away, directed by Lino Brocka), etc.

This brings the total number of her acting trophies to an impressive 11 in just three-and-a-half years.

Lorna’s films continue to do the rounds of international film festivals. Sigaw ng Puso (Cry of the Heart) – Emergency Call was exhibited along with Asia’s best films at the 1996 Tokyo International Filmfest. Lorna played a doctor with a heart of gold alongside Japanese actor Heroyuki Sanada.

Another film, May Nagmamahal sa Iyo (Madonna and Child), or Someone Loves You (Madonna and Child), was shown at the Fukuoka, Tokyo, New Delhi, Hawaii and San Sebastian international filmfests.

Magnifico, winner of the International Jury Grand Prix award at the Berlin International Film Festival, and the only Filipino film in history to have won over 60 awards, saw Lorna playing the sacrificing mother of a girl afflicted with a motor disease.

Today, with television dominating Philippine show business, Lorna’s shift from big to small screen has been effortless, and just as fruitful. The country’s top two networks, GMA 7 and ABS-CBN, have found her talent beyond par in drama anthologies, talk shows and a talent search.

Lorna’s soap series, Kay Tagal Kang Hinintay (I Waited So Long For You) was shown all over Asia. Her Jekyll and Hyde character required her to shift from good to bad and back in only a matter of minutes. But Lorna, as always, did justice to her role.

The GMA 7 top-rating drama anthology Magpakailanman (Forevermore), where Lorna played a Filipino worker in Hong Kong who was raped and unknowingly contracted AIDS, won critical acclaim at the Singapore TV Awards. The jurors gave the episode a Highly-Recommended rating.

GMA 7 again banked on her knack for spotting talent when she sees one when it got her to sit in the judges’ bench for the widely-popular StarStruck, the network’s yearly search for young talents nationwide.

She trades witty repartee with fellow co-hosts in the top-rating celebrity talk show Startalk, also on GMA 7. Lorna also hosted Thirty Days, a much-talked about talent search on the same network.

Her own drama anthology, dubbed as Star Drama Presents Lorna over ABS-CBN, aired for three years – already considered a long time in the fickle world of Philippine TV. Needless to say, Lorna has a string of other drama series in the two stations.

Lorna’s wholesome image and appeal among the A, B, C, D and E crowd, and among young and old have earned her TV commercials and product endorsements. She helped push various products, from instant noodles (Lucky Me Lomi), to beauty services (Flawless), mineral water (Crystal Clear), baked goods (Gals Bakery) and women’s intimate wear (Mondragon Philippines). These companies bank on her marketability and mass appeal in their TV commercials and print ads. Lorna’s face lights up giant billboards scattered all over the country – in malls, major highways, high-rise buildings, etc.

Lorna’s work doesn’t end when the klieg lights are out. It extends to other concerns, like the welfare of fellow actors and children. She is a member of the Film Academy of the Philippines, Katipunan ng mga Artista ng Pelikulang Pilipino (Actors’ Guild of the Philippines), Philippine Movie Producers of the Philippines Association (she produced the film Kislap sa Dilim or A Glow in the Dark) and Movie and Television Review and Classification Board (MTRCB). The MTRCB reviews and classifies films according to audience suitability before they are shown in the country’s theaters.

The mother in Lorna (she has two grownup sons) has found expression and fulfillment as past president and treasurer of the Action for Children Towards Success.

The actress in her thirsts for new ways of perfecting her craft. So she attends workshops that enrich her whenever she can. Those she attended tackled the rudiments of her profession: Oral Interpretation (by the late respected director Ishmael Bernal), Being, Believing (by award-winning director Mel Chionglo) and Craft and Imaging (by Eric Morris).

Still another revered director, Peque Gallaga, conducted a Teacher’s Course for actors which Lorna also completed.

Lorna’s hunger for knowledge knows no bounds. She took a special course on Motion Picture Language and Photography at the Academy of Art College in San Francisco, California.

As a businesswoman, she found the entrepreneurship course at the University of the Philippines (the country’s premiere educational institution) Open University highly useful for her various business ventures in the fields of food, mineral water and others.

Lorna Tolentino continues to evolve as an actress and, most importantly, as an individual seeking excellence in everything she does. It is by going the extra mile that she earns the admiration of peers and the love of those around her.

This is what makes her last in the Philippine movie industry, where public taste is so fickle, lesser stars just fade away, and only the talented ones stay – the way Lorna Tolentino does to this day.

[edit] Sean McCormack

Assistant Secretary of State, US

Sean McCormack was sworn in as Assistant Secretary for Public Affairs and Department Spokesman on June 2, 2005. Immediately prior to returning to the State Department, Mr. McCormack served as Special Assistant to the President, Spokesman for the National Security Council, and Deputy White House Press Secretary for Foreign Policy.

Mr. McCormack began his career in the Foreign Service in 1995. He served at the U.S. embassy in Ankara from 1996 to 1998, where he was assigned as the Farsi-speaking officer in the consular section. He was posted to the U.S. embassy in Algiers from 1998 to 1999, with responsibility for economic reporting and consular issues. Mr. McCormack served in the State Department Operations Center in 1999 before moving to the Executive Secretariat Staff ("The Line"). He was detailed to the National Security Council Staff in 2001.

Prior to joining the Foreign Service, Mr. McCormack was an analyst at the Meridian Corporation working on issues related to arms control and non-proliferation.

Mr. McCormack graduated from Colby College in 1986 with a Bachelor’s degree in economics. He received an M.A. in international relations from the University of Maryland, College Park in 1990

[edit] Sepermeru

Sepermeru was the religious capital of the 19th Nome of Upper Egypt, located on an irrigation canal near the general entrance to the Fayuum Oasis. This outpost settlement was situated roughly mid-way between Oxyrhynchos (Per Medjed) to the south and Herakleopolis to the north. According to ancient taxation records and other pertinent sources, Sepermeru was a noted settlement for active and retired military personnel and their familes, particularly during the New Kingdom reign of the Rameses pharaohs. Agriculture was also practiced here. The chief deities of the town were the god Set and the goddess Nephthys; both of these deities were highly favored by the war-like Ramessid Dynasty of kings for their ominous, agrressive attributes. As revealed by ongoing excavations in the 1980s, two provincial temples were built in Sepermeru, existing from (at least) the 19th and 20th Dynastic periods. One temple was dedicated to Set while the other temple enclosure belonged to Nephthys. Separate, hierarchical priesthoods for both deities are named, for taxation purposes, in the Wilbour Papyrus: two "prophets" of "Set of Sepermeru" and two "prophets" and a "wa'ab" priest in the service of "Nephthys of Sepermeru" (19th and 20th Dynasties). In all likelihood, the temples were either built or considerably refurbished by Rameses III. Only the foundation stones of both temples remain today and, by Ptolemaic times, it is questionable whether the temples of Set and Nephthys (along with the settlement itself) were still occupied. Indeed, a derogatory reference to "Set of Sepermeru" on the walls of the Ptolemaic temple of Horus (at Edfu) notes that the town's canals were "dried up and forgotten" by the turn of the Common Era. This may have been a mere "hieroglyphic insult" rendered to Set, enemy of Horus, for the epithet "Set of Sepermeru" was still obviously familiar to the temple theologians. The capital of the 19th Nome had long before shifted to Oxyrhynchus in any case. Thus, it is likely that the settlement had waned considerably in significance.The history of the site, however, remains notable from an ancient Egyptian perspective because of the favor lavished by the Ramessid kings upon the temples of Nephthys and Set. Set's favor declined throughout Egypt with the downfall of these kings (except in the Delta and various northern oases), while Nephthys achieved greater popularity in her role as a goddess of the Osirian cycle, especially with temples of her own at Komir and Diospolis Parva (Hiw), where the entire 7th Upper Egyptian Nome was considered to be her particular "fiefdom" in Late Period and Greco-Roman times.

Sources:

A Ptolemaic Lexikon, Penelope Wilson (1997); The Goddesses of Pharaonic Egypt, Rene LaChaud (1992); Papyrus Wilbour (Berlin)

67.49.254.4 06:05, 20 May 2006 (UTC)

[edit] Takeshi Kimeda Sensei

Tekeshi Kimeda Sensei was born in Tokyo, Japan. In 1941, Kimeda Sensei has been a professional instructor of Yoshinkai Aikido in Canada for more than 35 years.

He began his study of Aikido under both Master Shioda and Kushida Sensei at 18 years of age while he was a university student. During his senior University years he was captain of the University Aikido Club. He graduated from University with a degree in Business Administration and a third degree black belt in Yoshinkai Aikido.

In 1964 Kimeda Sensei brought Yoshinkai Aikido to North America. He initially taught in California, then moved to Michigan where he opened the first Yoshinkai Dojo in Dearborn, Michigan. From Dearborn, he decided to come to Canada, opening the first Aikido school here.

Kimeda Sensei has developed many frontiers for Aikido outside Japan. He was instrumental in bringing Kushida Sensei and Karasawa Sensei to North America, also in inspiring many other instructors to teach outside Japan.

Kimeda Sensei is the chief instructor of Aikido Yoshinkai Canada, and holds the rank of 8th degree black belt. He currently has over 500 students in 15 dojos throughout Canada, and has trained more than 200 students to black belt.

[edit] Sources

I am a former student of Kimeda Sensei. I studied under him for 4 years. Factual information about him and his life can be found on many Aikido websites including www.aikido-world.com and www.aikidojournal.com Atom Cunningham 68.144.99.119 06:27, 20 May 2006 (UTC)

[edit] Burton "Bud" Koffman

Mr. Burton "Bud" Koffman is an incredibly secretive Jewish-American financier and businessman, who resides in the city of Binghamton, New York, as well as other locations around the world. Despite the fact that he is one of the wealthiest citizens in the United States, once owned the Sands Casino in Las Vegas as well as a myriad of Caribbean resorts, an industrial empire, exclusive contracts to distribute foreign cars in the U.S., and an investment bank, there is virtually no public information or knowledge of him. Finding information about him is difficult but not impossible, and the more that is uncovered the more interesting of a figure he seems to become.

[edit] [ [Penis Theory] ]

Penis Theory Abstract Penis theory is a branch of applied masculine studies that analyzes hypothetical (yet existing) relationships in unstructured courtship. Macro penis theory is a corrolary to the Buldge/income equation, in which male desirability is a function of independent variables-- penis size and income. Beginning in April 2006, Penis theory was initially developed as a tool for understanding seemingly irrational female behavior. Derived from non-experimental reasoning, Penis theory builds from several premises resultant from an implicit hierarchy of psycho-social observations: i. Women derive sexual gratification from larger penii. ii. Wealth is an essential component of longterm male/female interaction in western society iii. The sexual revolution has limited traditional societal norms iv. The pop-culture phenomenon of Sex and the City(see Whore studies)

Penis theory has been applied to other social science disciplines including: macro/micro cockeconomics, critical feminism, whore studies, and theoretical buldgenomics. It has drawn attention.

History Penis theory was developed by disillusioned University of California undergrads Allen Gilio and Dave Markman in April 2006.

notation--in the process of being developed. All concept/theories are not currently existing and are being created.

[edit] J-Lyriq

Detroit native J-LYRIQ is a gritty, urban contemporary/neo-soul singer, songwriter and self taught producer. His influences range from Sam Cooke, Donny Hathaway, and Marvin Gaye to Jodeci, Brian Mcknight, and R. Kelly. Like other R&B artist who have emerged in the '90s and 2000s, J-Lyriq looks to different eras for inspiration. The classic soul of the '60s and '70s impact his singing and producing, but so have the urban contemporary and hip-hop of the '80s, '90s and 2000s.

At times, J-Lyriq can be flat-out retro; some of his material would have been right at home on an old Motown LP from R&B's pre-'80s, pre-urban contemporary, pre-hip-hop era. Other times he has a more modern, hip-hop-influenced outlook. In other words, he has some songs that are quite friendly to urban radio, and others that would be too old-school for urban radio.His goal is to not be able to be compared to any other artist.

Born and raised in Detroit, Michigan, where he was the last of 8 children, J-Lyriq had a very musical upbringing -- one that included a steady diet of R&B and soul. When he wasn't performing gospel, J-Lyriq listened to secular soul and funk -- and his favorites included Sam Cooke, Otis Redding, Donny Hathaway, and the Gap Band. As a lead in his choir he had big dreams of worldwide fame.

www.j-lyriq.com

[edit] Ioannis Amanatidis

Ioannis Amanatidis was born on the 3rd December, 1981 in Kozani, Greece. He is a Greek footballer, who has served as a full Greek international.

Amanatidis' early career in football was unconventional, yet promising . He began playing football in Kozani with his friends (rather than with a professional club) on the streets of the town. His first experience in organised football came at the age of nine, when he moved to Germany with his family. It was at SC Stuttgart that he first laced up his boots, demonstrating a devastating instinct for scoring goals even in his early years, and becoming the leading goalscorer during his four years with the Swabian club.

Amanatidis has, since then, played a large majority of his football in Germany, most notable are his performances with German clubs Kaiserslautern and, of course, Stuttgart. He currently plays for Eintracht Frankfurt, and serves as one of their key frontmen in the Frankfurt strikeforce. He played a vital role for Frankfurt in the 2005/2006 season, helping them stay in the German Bundesliga, and finishing the season as the clubs highest goalscorer for the year, with 12 goals. Amanatidis also led the way in the German cup, with Frankfurt just losing out to German champions Bayern Munich in the final. Amanatidis had a chance to be the hero of the night, having his 88th minute strike off a corner parried away by keeper Oliver Kahn.

Despite having such a promising career ahead of him at many periods of his blossoming career, unlike many notable Greek national players, Amanatidis was left out of the Greece squad which won the 2004 Euro Final. When asking coach Otto Rehagel why he was left out, he admitted:

"I asked Rehhagel before the European Championship why I had been left out. He explained and I accepted it".

He is no doubt, in the future, going to be in the plans for Greece, and despite Greece not making the World Cup in Germany, Amanatidis has a lot to look forward to internationally. Amanatidis was also named in the Greek squad that travels down under to meet Australia on Thursday 25th, 2006, in Melbourne.

[edit] "Sick" Nick Mondo

Born Matt Burns in Minneapolis, Minnesota. Nick Mondo quickly rose to fame in CZW (Combat Zone Wrestling) as one of its brightest stars. Making his debut in March of 1999, Nick Mondo's career, although short-lived was one of the most succesful of all those who competed in CZW. Despite giving up much in size and power to competitors such as John Zandig, Nate Hatred, The Wifebeater and Necro Butcher, Mondo was able to stand toe-to-toe with these competitors in the ring. Notable incidents from Mondo's Career include his fall of the top of the Warehouse in Delaware at Tournament of Death 2. During this 2 Out Of 3 Falls Light-Tube Log-Cabin Match. Mondo and his opponent John Zandig fell from the top of a warehouse through 4 tables and one of the Light-Tube Log-Cabins. This fall left Mondo's back badly lascerated, despite this he managed to win the match. Later that night he would also defeat Ian Rotten to win TOD2. Sadly only a few months after TOD 2 on November 10th 2003 Nick Mondo announced he was retiring due to Injury. In his four and a half year carreer Mondo had won The CZW Iron Man Title 3 times, the CZW Tag Titles with Ric Blade, the AWF championship and the NCWA Hardcore Championship, along with Tournament of Death 2. Other notable Mondo matches include Nick Mondo vs Homeless Jimmy from the original Tournament of Death, a TLC match at Cage of Death 4 between the team of Mondo and Ric Blade and The Backseat Boyz and Nick Mondo vs Nick Gage vs Nick Berk in a Tables, Ladders and Violence Match where Mondo won his 2nd CZW Iron Man belt.

[edit] Order of Prince Danilo I of Montenegro

The Order of Prince Danilo I of Montenegro was the first Montenegrin state Order and was established as a single class Order by His Royal Highness Prince Danilo Petrovic on St. George's Day April 23 (May 5), 1852, as the Order of Danilo I for the Independence of Montenegro “in order to honor the courage and the accomplishments of his subjects and of all those who dedicated themselves to defend the holy thing of the fatherland independence”. The Order became dormant upon the exile of the Royal House, though with living members and is still awarded to prominent champions of the preservation of Montenegrin independence. The conditions by which the Order is awarded are defined by Statute.

Alterations were made to the appearance of the original decoration created by Prince Danilo and during the rule of His Majesty King Nikola I Petrovic the Order underwent two restructures. During the first restructure on St. Goerge's Day April 23 (May 5), 1861, three classes were introduced, The King introducing two upper degrees, Grand Cross and Commander, with specific insignias; the old cross becoming a third class, Knight. On April 23 (May 5), 1873, the second reorganisation of the Order expands the field of rewards to civilian merits, establishes a Grand Chancellery and adds an intermediary class of Grand Officer between those of Grand Cross and Commander. In 1893, a third reform of the statutes establishes a fourth class, resulting from a reclassification of the existing class of Knight. The old cross then became a fifth class.

Throughout the history of the Order, the insignia has been produced by several famous medallists, the best-known being Arthus Bertrand, Beranger & Magdalaine (Paris, France), A. Chobillion (Paris, France), D. Cravanzola (Roma, Italy), R. Marschall (Vienna, Austria), Vincent Mayer (Vienna, Austria), C.F. Rothe & Neffe (Vienna, Austria), A. Ryabkov (St. Petersburg, Russia), G.A. Scheid (Vienna, Austria), Silberberg (Hamburg, Germany) and presently Thomas Fattorini (Birmingham, United Kingdom).

Many deserving men and women have been awarded the Order of Prince Danilo I over time including foreigners. The illustrious list includes many decorated servicemen during the World Wars and a host of other notables, including Queen Victoria and King Edward VII of Great Britain, as well as being written about by F. Scott Fitzgerald in 'The Great Gatsby'.

The Order of Prince Danilo I is the prerogative of the Head of the Royal House of Montenegro. On November 11, 2004 in Cetinje, His Majesty King Nikola II Petrovic Njegos, Hereditary Grand Master, reformed the Order, keeping the organisation of 1873 in five classes, but renaming them into Grand Cross, Knight Commander, Knight, Lieutenant and Member. The Grand Cross class is divided in four grades: Diamond Star, Gold Star, Silver Star and Grand Cross. The Hereditary Grand Master and the Grand Chancellor of the Order both wear an additional Collar of the Order.

The Order of Danilo I is registered in Montenegro as a Non-Governmental Organisation (NGO). Revised statutes of the Order were enacted on April 23 (May 5), 2005.

The present Hereditary Grand Master is His Majesty King Nikola II Petrovic Njegos of Montenegro. The Vice Grand Master is His Royal Highness Hereditary Prince Boris Petrovic Njegos of Montenegro, Grand Duke of Grahovo and Zeta. The Grand Chancellor of the Order is John Gvozdenovic, kinsman of the late General Anto Gvozdenovic (the last Grand Chancellor of the Order under King Nikola I).

The Successive Grand Masters since 1852 have been: His Majesty King Nikola II (from 24 March 1986); His Majesty King Michael (from 7 March 1921 to 24 March 1986); His Majesty King Danilo Alexander (from 1 March 1921 to 7 March 1921); His Majesty King Nikola I (from 13 August 1860 to 1 March 1921), and; Sovereign Prince Danilo I (from 23 April/5 June 1852 to 13 August 1860).

[edit] Sources

"Medals and Decorations from the Collection of Dr. Veljko Malinar" Boris Prister, 2000. "Orders, Medals and Insignia of Montenegro", Sinisa Pogacic, 2002.

Glenn Dellimore Glenn Dellimore, born 1972 in London, England, privately educated in London and holder of various England athletic records, gained entry to the London Royal College of Design and graduated from London Barons Court College in Leisure & Entertainment Business Management.

Dellimore founded a national U.K health club events company, designing membership events for the Lord Sebastian Coe health clubs brand. Thereafter, Dellimore designed and founded a renowned ‘five star’ luxury health club in London.

As Dellimore advanced in the entertainment world, he moved from London to Beverly Hills. Liaising with major Hollywood film studios, Dellimore developed two international talent entertainment businesses. Dellimore’s Celeb Entertainment is an international talent booking company for the world’s most popular international talent attending U.K appearances with CelebEvents, formerly known as Jealous Events.

Appearances booked by Jealous Events include Kelly Donovan and Stacey Scowley for a Buffy the Vampire Slayer and Angel convention. Kelly Donovan was a stunt double for the show, and Stacey Scowley was an extra in one episode.

Glenn Dellimore was featured on the U.K television BBC consumer complaints programme Watchdog in 2003 regarding the Jealous Events David Boreanaz Event. Many attendees were not satisfaid with this event due to the lack of organisation. Fans were left out of pocket, in some cases for hundreds of pounds, regarding refunds that were promised and never delivered. Glenn Dellimore's name is well known on the U.K convention circuit as an organiser who's events most do not wish to attend.

Glenn Dellimore is back on the U.K convention scene as CelebEvents. Many people believe the name change from Jealous Events to CelebEvents is to mask the 'bad reputation' he now has, so new attendees will be unaware of the hundreds of fans left out of pocket from his previous events.

[edit] Peanut Test

The peanut test can be used to see if you are (in)compatible with someone in terms of a relationship.

The test was originated in the UK and hence uses the main British flavours in nuts. It can be expanded to other nations' tipples but must be kept concise for clarity and maximum effect.

The test is as follows:

Which type of peanut do you prefer?

a) Dry Roasted b) Salted c) I don't like peanuts

The answer must be one of the above. Such comments as "well I don't really mind" are not permitted.

[edit] Order of Saint Peter of Cetinje

The Order of Saint Peter of Cetinje was the first dynastic Order of the Royal House of Montenegro and was introduced by His Majesty King Nikola I Petrovic in 1869. It is sometimes said that this order was actually introduced much earlier by Prince-Bishop (Vladica) Peter II Petrovic-Njegoš. The Order is bestowed upon prominent members of the Royal House, the Petrovic-Njegoš family, as well as to prominent foreign citizens, and is currently held by all members of the Royal House.

The name of Prince Danilo, the first Montenegrin ruler with a purely secular title, is inscribed on the Decoration. The Order was named after the Patron Saint of the Montenegrin Orthodox Church, Prince-Bishop (Vladika) Peter I Petrovic, the person who effectively obtained independence for Montenegro, and to whom is attributed the creation of the modern Montengrin State.

Tzar Alexander II of Russia was the first recipient of the Order, awarded on June 29, 1871. During his reign, King Nikola I never organised the Order and maintained it as a single class Dynastic Order, rewarding only members of the Montenegrin Royal Family and related such as Alexander I of Serbia (1888-1934), King Petar I of Serbia (1844-1921), Ljubica “Zorka” Petrovic Njegos (1864-1890), Duke Ilija Plamenac (1821-1917), Duke Bozo Petrovic Njegos (1846-1929), King Vittorio Emanuele III of Italy (1869-1947), and Jelena Petrovic Njegos (1873-1952) etc.

The present Grand Master is His Majesty King Nikola II and the Grand Chancellor is John Gvozdenovic.

The Order consists of a single class, and is normally reserved for members of the Royal Family and their kinsmen and in exceptional circumstances prominent foreign citizens.

Current living recipients include: Her Majesty Queen France, His Royal Highness Hereditary Prince Boris, Grand Duke of Grahovo and Zeta, Her Royal Highness Princess Altinai, His Most Eminent Highness Fra' Andrew Bertie, Prince and Grand Master of the Sovereign Order of Malta, His Highness Prince Nicholas of Russia, His Serence Highness Prince Dimitri of Russia, His Royal Highness Vittorio Emanuele of Savoy, Prince of Naples, Her Royal Highness Marina of Savoy, Princess of Naples, His Royal Highness Emanuele Filiberto of Savoy, Prince of Venice and John Gvozdenovic.

[edit] Sources

http://www.orderofdanilo.org/ The Official Website of the Royal House Orders of Montenegro

[edit] Feel the Darkness

Feel the Darkness is the most famous album by the punk band Poison Idea. Widely regarded as one of the best punk albums of all time, it has gained worldwide critical acclaim. Songs on the album have been covered by everyone from Pantera to Machine Head (as a bonus track on their Burn My Eyes album). It was originally released in 1990, and was reissued in 2004 by Golf records

[edit] Al Bansavage

Al Bansavage was an American college and professional football player. A linebacker, he played college football at the University of Southern California, and played professionally in the American Football League for the Los Angeles Chargers in 1960 and the Oakland Raiders in 1961.

[edit] Dj Steve Dee

DJ Steve Dee is one of the most influential DJ's of our time and the creator of the "The Funk" known to the world as "Beat Juggling" one of the greatest things to hit deejaying, since the Scratch. "Beat Juggling" is the act of manipulating individual drum beats, or vocal phrases, in order to create a unique composition using multiple turntables. Steve Dee was the founding member of the original DJ group "The X-Men" (later know as the X-Ecutioners) and fathered the movement called "Turntablism." Dj Steve Dee has worked with artist like Dougie Fresh & the Get Fresh Crew, the ever controversial Luther ‘Luke Skywalker aka Uncle Luke’ Campbell, Wreckx n Effect, Japanese superstar Toshi Kubota, Teddy Riley’s “Guy & BlackStreet”, and worked on international megastar Michael Jackson's "Dangerous" album. In 2000 DJ Steve Dee was inducted into the "DMC DJ HALL of FAME" for his immense contribution to the world of deejaying. He is also the last DJ to win the New Music Seminar Battle for World Supremacy. He can be seen in the DJ documentary "Scratch" or you can check him out at [14].

[edit] AFL Best Player

In each year of its ten-year existence (1960 - 1969), numerous sports-news services named their choice for the American Football League's best first-year player. The choices by the major services are shown below.

[edit] 1961

[edit] (UPI, TSN)

EARL FAISON, defensive end, San Diego Chargers

Despite being double and triple-teamed, Faison was chosen as the AFL Rookie of the Year in 1961. The 6-foot-5, 260-pound Earl Faison blew by opposing offensive lineman on his way to smashing American Football League quarterbacks as one of the original "Fearsome Foursome", and was chosen to the AFL All-Star team in 1961.


[edit] 1962

[edit] (UPI, TSN)

CURTIS McCLINTON, fullback, Dallas Texans

McClinton had 604 Yards on 111 carries for a 5.4 yards per carry average and two touchdowns. He added 333 yards on 29 receptions and was a member of the 1962 AFL All-Star team.


[edit] 1963

[edit] (UPI, TSN)

BILLY JOE, fullback, Denver Broncos

An eleventh-round draft choice by the Broncos, Joe had 646 yards on 154 carries for a 4.2 yards per carry average, four rushing touchdowns, and a reception for a touchdown.


[edit] 1964

[edit] (UPI, TSN)

MATT SNELL, fullback, New York Jets

Selected in the third round in the NFL draft, Matt Snell was picked in the first round as the first player drafted by the AFL's New York franchise after new owner Sonny Werblin changed the team's name from the Titans of New York. Snell rolled up 948 yards on 215 carries, for a 4.4 yards per carry average, with an additional 393 yards on 56 receptions, with four touchdowns rushing and one receiving. He was also named to the 1964 AFL All-Star team.


[edit] 1965

[edit] (UPI, TSN)

JOE NAMATH, quarterbackback, New York Jets

Choosing the American Football League's Jets (and $427,000) over the NFL, Namath was 164 of 340 for 2,220 yards and 18 touchdowns in his rookie season for the Jets, and was selected to the 1965 AFL All-Star team.


[edit] 1966

[edit] (UPI, TSN)

BOBBY BURNETT, halfback, Buffalo Bills

Arkansas' Bobby Burnett had a combined total of 1,185 yards rushing and receiving at the halfback position, with over 12 yards per catch and 4 toucdowns on 34 receptions, and 766 yards on 187 rushes, with 4 rushing touchdowns. He was also selected to the 1966 AFL All-Star team.


[edit] 1967

[edit] (UPI)

GEORGE WEBSTER, linebacker, Houston Oilers

George Webster created the "roverback" position, as a linebacker with a defensive back's moves and speed. He started as a rookie and had 15 tackles in his first game. The Oilers' defense held opponents under 200 points in 1967, helping them win the East Division title. He averaged more than ten tackles a game and was first-team All-AFL in 1967.


[edit] (TSN)

DICKIE POST, halfback, San Diego Chargers

Dickie Post rushed for 691 yards and 7 touchdowns on 161 carries in 1967, and caught 32 passes with the Chargers for 278 yards and a touchdown. He made the AFL All-Star team in 1967 and would make it again in 1969.


[edit] 1968

[edit] (UPI, TSN)

PAUL ROBINSON, halfback, Cincinnati Bengals

Paul Robinson played only one year at the University of Arizona, but in his first year as a professional, he gained 1,023 yards rushing and scored eight touchdowns. He was named to the 1968 All-AFL team and led the Western AFL All-Star team to victory over the Eastern All-Stars.


[edit] 1969

[edit] (UPI)

GREG COOK, quarterback, Cincinnati Bengals

The University of Cincinnati's 6-foot-4, 220-pound quarterback Greg Cook stayed in Cincinnati to play professional football. In his rookie year, he passed for 1,854 yards and 15 touchdowns. Injury prevented him from reaching his potential with the Bengals.


[edit] (TSN)

CARL GARRETT, halfback, Boston Patriots

Carl Garrett caught 29 passes for 267 yards and two touchdowns in 1969, and ran the ball for over five yards per carry with 137 attempts for 691 yards and five touchdowns. He was also selected to the AFL All-Star team in 1969.

[edit] George W. Bush in popular culture

George W. Bush has been satirically depicted in various media throughout the years, often in a negative context. Listed below are all the films, comics, websites, songs, tv series who've parodied or criticised him at least once:

[edit] Comics

  • In the work of cartoonist Ted Rall he is often depicted as a dictator
  • In the last Asterix album Asterix and the Falling Sky the leader of the Toon aliens is called "Hubs" an anagram of Bush.

[edit] Songs

In this list also songs about the war in Iraq are included, because they often criticize the war or war as a phenomenon in particular, however when these songs take a neutral point of view they are listed a little lower.

  • "American Idiot" (Green Day)
  • "An Open Letter To NYC" (The Beastie Boys)
  • "Bomb The World" (Spearhead)
  • "Dear Mr. President" (P!nk)
  • "Doofpot" (Osdorp Posse)
  • "Hail To The Thief" (Radiohead) (the title is a pun on the song Hail To The Chief and references the rumor that Bush stole the 2000 US presidential elections)
  • "Mosh" (Eminem)
  • "Wake Me Up When September Ends" (Green Day)
  • "Weg Met Amerika" (Raymond van het Groenewoud). The title of this Flemish album (in English: "Down with America") caused a small stream of criticism against the anti-American title.

[edit] Songs about the war in Iraq without mentioning Bush

Some of these songs happen to be about war even without specifically talking about the war in Iraq. However, it must be said that so many songs about peace and against war have appeared during Bush's presidency that all of them, even if not a real criticism against the Bush administration must of could have been inspired by the wars in Afghanistan and Iraq.

  • "The Day After Tommorow" -(Tom Waits)
  • "How To Dismantle An Atomic Bomb" - (U2)
  • "Weapon Of Mass Destruction" (Faithless)

[edit] Music Videos

  • Rage Against The Machine's music video Testify for the US presidential elections of 2000 showed Bush and Al Gore as a sort of aliens who talk and act the same. The clip also makes use of archive footage and at one point an image of two girls kissing each other is followed by film footage of Bush looking very frightened.
  • In Madonna 's video for her single American Life (2003) she was originally shown in army outfit while leading troops of female soldiers. At the end of the clip she throws a hand grenade at a lookalike of Bush who then lights it with a cigar. It received so much criticism that Madonna replaced the clip with less controversial images.
  • In George Michael's video for Shoot The Dog (2002) the animation, provided by the British animated series 2DTV, shows Bush and Tony Blair at one point firing missiles at Saddam Hussein. Blair is shown as a pet and admiring, almost homosexual assistent to a very childlike Bush.
  • Green Day's clip for Wake Me Up When Tommorow Comes (2004) shows a girl bursting in tears when she finds out her boyfriend is going to fight in Iraq. The video shows him as a soldier who is eventually shot in a desert like setting.
  • Eminem's clip for Mosh is an animation of Eminem and various people who gather together to march to a building out of protest against Bush. During the animated clip real life filmed material is shown of Bush during a presidential speech. In the end of the clip Eminem and the stream of people are shown registering to vote against Bush. After the 2004 elections however a different ending was shown: Eminem arrives at the building where Bush is seen, giving a speech. When he sees Eminem he hides behind his desk.

[edit] Tv series

  • In the British animation series 2DTV Bush is often depicted as an infantile person.
  • Trey Parker and Matt Stone of South Park fame once made a sitcom about president Bush: That's My Bush. It featured lookalikes of him, Laura Bush and his administration and was set in The White House. The series were more a satire on American sitcoms than on Bush's presidency.
  • In the British satirical series Dead Ringers Bush's dyslexia is mocked whenever he is imitated.

[edit] Errata sheet

An errata sheet is a common method of post-production editing in which the errors left in the produced copy are outlined on a sheet of paper bound into the book. This is a common method by which large works are "edited"; i.e. if the volume would cost too much and/or be too incongruous to edit, this is an acceptable method by which one might edit the work.

It should be noted that errata sheets should only outline minor errors within a work (e.g. misspellings, improper punctuation and the like). If a major error in the construction of a sentence occurs, or if the construction is such that the idea that the sentence delivers is unclear or distorted to the point of confusion or the delivery of the wrong idea, this MUST be corrected within the work.

[edit] Sources

Webster's Third International Dictionary (Unabridged)

24.153.205.144 13:28, 20 May 2006 (UTC)

[edit] Discussion

  • Article created as a part of Erratum; redirected thence. Sandstein 12:28, 21 May 2006 (UTC)

[edit] Champlin Creek

Champlin Creek is located between the hamlets of Islip and East Islip, flowing southward into the Great South Bay.The fish and wildlife habitat is an approximate three and one-half mile length of the stream, extending from Knapps Lake, just north of the Main Street, to near its headwaters north of the Southern State Parkway. Champlin Creek is a relatively clean, cold, free-flowing, freshwater stream, generally less than 6 feet wide, partially vegetated sandy substrate. The creek is bordered by limited areas of wet forest land and suburban residential development. Champlin Creek is one of only a few free-flowing, spring-fed streams on Long Island that have remained in a relatively natural state. This creek provides habitat conditions suitable for natural reproduction by brook trout, and supports one of approximately 6 known wild populations of this species on Long Island. In addition to the native fish populations in Champlin Creek, brown trout and rainbow trout are stocked in the stream by the NYSDEC, provide a recreational fishery of county-level significance. Public access for fishing the area is available along the east side of Knapps Lake and at road crossings.

[edit] Fake shamans

Fake shaman is a term used for individuals who pass themselves off as medicine men, healers, spiritual advisors, seers, or psychics, claiming a lineage to a native tradition they do not possess, yet claim to represent. The motive for this is often to claim an authority for themselves that they do not deserve, thus leveraging the mystique of these traditions for financial gain or self-aggrandisement. Generally this involves offering fictional accounts in books, workshops, or ceremonies which are for sale in a way which traditional spirituality tends to avoid. One example is the so-called "Path of Pollen", which has been promoted as a "hidden" lineage of European shamanism containing bee- and sex-related practices. The "revelation" of "hidden" or "arcane" knowledge is often a tactic of fake shamans as it makes it obviously difficult for their claims to be verified (or otherwise). Typically, the revelation of this supposedly arcane knowledge is accompanied by the demise of the person who initiated the student into it, leaving him or her free to promote themselves as the new "master" of this "wisdom". This is the case in Carlos Castaneda's work, for example, and in The Shamanic Way of the Bee, a book supposedly written (though this is disputed) by Simon Buxton of the Sacred Trust which invents the "Path of Pollen" as a European tradition, whereas, in fact, it has been demonstrated as a line pilfered from a Navajo Beauty Way song that has nothing at all to do with European shamanism, with bees, or with sexual practices of any kind. The actual (claimed) author of this book has distanced himself from it and from Buxton, claiming that he wrote it as semi-fiction, which Buxton has subsequently promoted as his own work and as fact.

http://www.psychosislane.com/bee.html

[edit] Magshimey Herut

Magshimey Herut (achievers of liberty) is a Zionist movement for young adults that was founded in 1999 by a number of Jewish activists in order to answer the need for a hagshama movement of young adults dedicated to aliyah, social justice and the territorial integrity of the land of Israel.

[edit] History

Magshimey Herut was founded in 1999 by a number of Betar activists who were disappointed with what they viewed as a lack of ideological integrity within their movement. When a Likud government led by Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu relinquished parts of Hebron to Yasser Arafat in 1998, Benny Begin led the Herut faction out of the Likud. As the youth movement most associated with the ruling party, Betar members were uncertain on how to view a Likud Prime Minister betraying their most sacred principles. While the Betar leadership officially supported Netanyahu's policies, Betar treasurer Karma Feinstein, along with a group of ideological purists and veteran activists from chapters throughout the world, left Betar in order to establish Magshimey Herut.

Discarding Betar’s militaristic flavor, Magshimey Herut focused on packaging the ideals of Zev Jabotinsky and Revisionist Zionism in a way that would be more current and appealing to young Jews. Led by a blend of secular and religious right-wing activists, Magshimey Herut made an effort to be more sympathetic than Betar to the needs and values of religious Jews. In the years that followed its establishment, a number of graduates from the Bnei Akiva religious Zionist youth movement joined Magshimey Herut, seeing it as a young adult movement most committed to the values that Bnei Akiva instilled in them as youth.

Possibly as a result of its focus on social issues in addition to right-wing Zionist ideals, Magshimey Herut attracted many Jews who, although actively left-wing on domestic issues, believed strongly in Israel’s moral right to the entire land of Israel. Magshimey Herut therefore became a unique movement in Zionist politics, combining a faithful adherence to right-wing national goals with a steadfast commitment to social justice within society.

As the youngest movement within the World Zionist Organization’s hagshama department, Magshimey Herut continues to grow both in Israel and the Diaspora.


[edit] Ideology

Magshimey Herut views itself as loyal to the basic Zionist teachings of Zev Jabotinsky. There is, however, evidence that the movement takes great liberty in interpreting Jabotinsky’s views. Some critics argue that Magshimey Herut’s ideological leanings are closer to those of Uri Zvi Greenberg and Abraham Stern’s Lehi group than to Jabotinsky and the Irgun underground (with whom Betar closely identifies). Possibly due to its more religious flavor, Magshimey Herut seems nearer to messianic strands of Revisionist Zionism than to the mainstream component represented by Betar.

Although opposed to many policies of recent Israeli governments, Magshimey Herut views the State of Israel as something sacred of great historical significance and deserving of their loyalty. The movement places unity amongst Jews of all persuasions on equal footing with the territorial integrity of the land of Israel and therefore works to build dialogue between Jews with opposing political opinions.


[edit] Objectives

All chapters of Magshimey Herut adhere to fourteen basic movement objectives:

1. Develop young leadership in Israel and abroad, working together to impart Jewish and Zionist values.

2. Initiate educational activities designed to imbue Jewish youth with a love for the nation, homeland and tradition of Israel.

3. Foster Zionist education abroad in order to promote and encourage aliyah.

4. Train young leaders dedicated to social justice and the territorial integrity of Eretz Yisrael.

5. Inculcate the importance of national solidarity and the responsibility of all Jews for one another.

6. Further cultural activities which foster Jewish nationalism.

7. Arouse the next generation to honor the memory of Holocaust victims and continue the struggle against anti-Semitism.

8. Establish absorption communities throughout Israel in order to improve the aliyah experience.

9. Inculcate the value of Hebrew settlement in all of Eretz Yisrael.

10. Train cadres of young leaders dedicated to promoting dialogue, understanding and tolerance between Orthodox and non-Orthodox Jews.

11. Promote an understanding of the necessity for preserving the Jewish character of the State of Israel.

12. Provide supplemental educational activities in Israel’s disadvantaged communities and development towns.

13. Further cultural activities to preserve the traditions of communities from around the world.

14. Educate to the importance of increasing the Hebrew birthrate.


[edit] Activities

Magshimey Herut is active in over ten countries with the primary objective of bringing young Jewish adults to Israel on aliyah. At the same time, the movement takes a leading role in numerous political causes. In addition to promoting Jewish settlement in the West Bank and fighting for the ideal of Greater Israel, Magshimey Herut has been a force in the struggle to free Jonathan Pollard. In some countries the movement has been active against globalization, claiming that it creates unjust working conditions and violates the notion of national sovereignty.

In Israel, Magshimey Herut is active in social causes and has devoted substantial effort to bridging gaps within society by creating workshops for dialogue with left-wing movements. Magshimey Herut organizes weekly programming for young immigrants to Israel and works with youth-at-risk in order to redirect their energies towards Zionist goals.

[edit] Rahul Mehrotra

Rahul Mehrotra (b.1959) studied at the School of Architecture, Ahmedabad and received a gold medal for his undergraduate dissertation. In 1987 he graduated with a Master’s Degree in Urban Design with distinction from the Graduate School of Design at Harvard.

The office of Rahul Mehrotra Associates was founded in August 1990 and has since designed and executed projects that include office interiors, boutiques, weekend houses, factories, institutes and office buildings. In addition, the practice has been involved in conservation and master planning projects in the city of Bombay, thereby being engaged with diverse issues and a number of varying scales, from Interior Design and Architecture to Urban Design, Conservation and Planning.

Rahul Mehrotra is currently an Associate Professor at the College of Architecture and Urban Planning at the University of Michigan. He was also recently a member of the Master Jury for the Aga Khan Award (2001-2004 award cycle), a member of the jury for the 2005 Berkley Prize and is a member of the Jury for the James Stirling Prize on the city (2006).

From 1992 to 1999, Mehrotra has been member of the Committee that advises the Municipal Commissioner on the conservation of historic building and artifacts in the city. In 1995 he founded, and has been a principal in The Bombay Collaborative, a conservation architecture practice, which works with historic buildings in Bombay as well as consultant to organizations such as the Bombay Environmental Action Group, INTACH, The World Monument Fund (New York), The Orient Foundation, (Portugal), Arch Foundation, (Austria) and various Neighborhood and Citizens Groups in Bombay. Since 1996, he has been on the Board of Governors of the Bombay Metropolitan Regional Development Authority’s Heritage Society and from 1994 to 2004; Rahul Mehrotra was the Executive Director of the Urban Design Research Institute (UDRI), where he is now a Trustee.

Mehrotra has written and lectured extensively on issues to do with architecture, conservation and urban planning Bombay. His writings include co-authoring the book `Bombay - The Cities Within’ which covers Bombay’s Urban History from the 1600’s to the present, `Banganga – Sacred Tank’, `Public Places Bombay’, `Fort Walks – Walking Tours of Bombay Historic City Center’, ‘Anchoring a City Line’ – A History of the Commuter Railway in Bombay and `Bombay to Mumbai – Changing Perspectives’. He has also co-authored a book titled `Conserving an Image Center – The Fort Precinct in Bombay’, based on this study and recommendation the State Government declared the Fort area a Conservation Precinct in 1995. In 2000 he edited a book for the UIA that earmarks the end of the century and is titled `The Architecture of the 20th Century in the South Asian Region’. His recent publications include a book on the historic High Court Building in Bombay, a book which evaluates the impact of Conservation Legislation in Bombay and a book which documents the Architectural Heritage of the Navy and Armed forces in Bombay. Most recently he has edited the first of the three books which document the 2004 Michigan Debates on Urbanism.

The built work of Rahul Mehrotra include the LMW Corporate Office in Coimbatore, an Orphanage for Children of the World in New Bombay, the D.J. Institute of Management in Coimbatore, an extension to the Prince of Wales Museum in Bombay and a Rural Development Institute in Tuljapur. Mehrotra has designed and built a number of houses around Bombay, in Alibag, Cochin, Indore, Ahmedabad, Baroda, Nasik, Pune and Lonavala. He has built Factory Buildings, Office Buildings, a School for hearing impaired Children, a Winery and a number of Institutional buildings in and around Bombay. Rahul Mehrotra has also designed and executed interior projects that include the Jehangir Art Gallery and Sakshi Art Gallery in Bombay, as well as office interiors – including those for the Catholic Relief Services, Virgin Records, Turner Morrison and a series of shops for the lifestyle store - Bandej. Mehrotra has worked on several Adaptive Reuse projects involving old buildings (often listed Heritage Buildings) in Bombay, Ahmedabad, Indore and Hyderabad. Currently, Mehrotra is working on a 10 acre Software Development campus for HP in Bangalore, a campus for Magic Bus - an NGO that works with street children, the restoration of the Chowmahalla Palace in Hyderabad and (with the Taj Mahal Conservation Collaborative), a Conservation Master Plan for the Taj Mahal. His current project outside India are a housing project in Beijing, a film Institute and community center in Kampala and a house in Karachi.

The projects of Rahul Mehrotra Associates have been published in various architectural journals in India and abroad. In 1995, Interiors India nominated Mehrotra `Designer of the Year’. In 1996, Architectural Design (London) selected Rahul Mehrotra Associates for their issue entitled `Architecture on the Horizon’ – which covered emerging young practices from around the World. In 2003, Phaidon selected two projects designed by Mehrotra for inclusion in their Encyclopedia on Contemporary World Architecture – (published in May 2004) Shanti, a Weekend House and a house designed for a filmmaker near Bombay. Mostly recently the firm has been extensively profiled in a book tiled new Directions in Tropical Asian Architecture (2005).

Rahul Mehrotra Associates were awarded two honorary mentions for the Kenneth F. Brown Asia Pacific Culture and Architecture Design Award 2000 for the LMW Corporate Head Office in Coimbatore and Shanti, a weekend house. In 2000, the firm received a J.K. Cements Award for the LMW Corporate Head Office. The projects of the firm have been exhibited at the RIBA in London, at the Contemporary Art Gallery in Ankara, Turkey, the Insitut Francais d’ Architecture, Paris, the Arts Biennale in Shanghai, the Aedes Gallery, Berlin, at the College of Architecture and Planning, University of Michigan, and at the Claude Batley Architectural Gallery in Bombay.

Website http://www.rma-associates.com

http://sitemaker.umich.edu/mrahul

[edit] Expected Loss

  • Expected Loss - in Actuarial Science it is defined as the Actuarial Present Value (APV) of Future Benefits minus the Actuarial Present Value of Future Premiums: E[L] = APVFB - APVFP

Many insurance mathematics problems are solved by setting E[L] = 0 and therefore setting APVFB = APVFP.

[edit] Elisabeth Karla Victoria Kalko

April 10, 1962, Berlin, Germany – is one of the 21st century's leading acoustic ecologists. She is a naturalist, community ecologist and tropical biologist with a global reputation in bats, the second largest order of mammals. Her work has contributed substantially to community ecology of tropical mammals.

[edit] Biography

Kalko was born in Berlin and completed her high school education in Berlin. She completed her Masters in 1987 at the University of Tübingen, Germany, her PhD in 1991 at the same school. A NATO post doctoral scholarship brought her in contact with the American Museum of Natural History in Washington, DC, USA, from where she started carrying out research in the Panama Canal area in Panama, Central America, in 1991. She was appointed staff scientist at the Smithsonian Tropical Research Institute (STRI) in Panama and full professor of ecology and head of department in experimental ecology at the University of Ulm in Germany. Kalko serves as in functions for several societies and advisory boards in science and for governments, in particular on global climate change.

[edit] Bibliography

[edit] Marcus Holliman

A recognized Wikipedian, Mr. Holliman has been in the commercial real estate industry since 1996 and holds the prestigious Certified Commercial Investment Member (CCIM) designation. He has been involved in numerous real estate transactions, partnerships and has participated as a principal in the purchase of numerous apartment complexes, commercial buildigns and unimproved land developments. [edit] George Bauernschmidt

Rear Admiral George William Bauernschmidt USN (SC) Ret. prepared at Calvert School, Gilman Country School, and Severn School. He attended Princeton for two years before being appointed to the Naval Academy, from which he graduated in 1922. In 1922, he married Maude Augusta Pearce. They had three children. George served in the Navy for 37 years. A line officer before transferring to the Supply Corps in 1935, he had 34 permanent assignments. He was on the London-based staff of Commander Naval Forces in Europe from 1944-45, helping to plan the invasion of Normandy. Among his awards were the Legion of Merit, the WWI Victory Medal, the American Defense Service Medal, the Korean Presidential Unit Citation Ribbon, the Marine Corps Device, and the United Nations Service Medal. In 1955 he retired and enjoyed painting, reading, and gardening. He was a member of the Military Order of World Wars, the Army-Navy Club of Washington, and the New York Paper Co. board of directors. He was predeceased by his wife in 1991 and by his daughter Mary B. Roberts in 1984. George died Apr. 18, 1998, at the Ginger Cove Health Center in Annapolis, Md. He was 99. He is survived by his children Sarah B. Murray and George Jr., 11 grandchildren, and 16 great-grandchildren.

[edit] Drink Ball

Drink ball is a highly active 2 on 2 drinking game that tests several different skills. Generally, a beer pong table is used, though it is not necessary. Each player starts with 1 can of beer, and between the group a ping pong ball is required. Each team lines up on opposite sides of the table, with the 4 cups of beer on each corner. Team 1, Player 1 starts by throwing the ping pong ball at one of team 2's beer cans. If the ball hits a can, Player 2 (of team 1) immediately begins to chug his beer until team 2 recovers the ball and hits the table with it. If the ball fails to hit the opposing team's beer can, then no chugging may occur. After the throw and subsequent recovery, team 2 gets a chance to retaliate in the same way. The next time around, Player 2 of team 1 is the thrower, and player 1 is the drinker. The game ends when one team finishes their own beer.

[edit] Audi S4 Cabriolet, One of the World's Most Beautiful Convertibles

The Audi S4 Cabriolet is a convertible Audi created to compete with the BMW M3 convertible and Mercedes-Benz CLK55 convertible. However much Audi is considered the "alternative", its designs and power continue to flourish. It has a slightly lower price than the M3, and the CLK55 is well over $80,000, pushing it out of the S4 and M3's $60,000 price barrier.

All models of the S4 are fitted with the company's acclaimed 4.2 liter V8, which in S4 form generates a more than adequate 340hp. Mated to the [six-speed manual] transmission, the car propels itself from 0-60 mph in a mere 5.7 seconds. However, the even quicker S4 sedan does this exact feat in a supercar-worthy 4.9 seconds with the manual, 5.3 with the automatic. Expect the S4 Cabriolet Automatic to accelerate in 5.9 seconds.

However, Audi did not stop the S4's beauty at the front. The convertible comes in a variety of colors, from Silver to Sprint Blue, which is by far the best complement to the aluminum trim around the beltline, mirrors and windshield. It does not have the over-designness of the BMW 7 Series or newly designed 2007 Mercedes-Benz S-Class, or the like. The S4 has simple, flowing lines, whilst retaining the dramatic elegance people expect from Audi. The interior is even more fabulous. Even in somber black, the S4's interior delights with gorgeous Birchwood trim, red-illuminated lights, simple yet graceful guages, supple leather sport seats, silver piping and leather trim all around. The design is straightforward, and yet it portrays a sense of elegance that you would find in a luxury sedan that is three times the price. This car is truly a jack-of-all-trades.

The real pleasure starts, however, when you turn the key. A low V8 grumble reaches the driver's ears, and the car roars to life. It is quite fast, and knows how to handle it when the road gets twisty, or wet-- courtesy of Audi's legendary quattro all-wheel-drive system. That is something neither of its main rivals can boast about. There is also quite a wide torque band from the award-winning V8, and you can have mid-range punch throughout your drive.

The S4 Cabriolet is the perfect complement to the S4 sedan and Avant, and this author can see nothing better for the price. The combination of eye-catching, simplistic style, luxurious interior (an Audi hallmark), and V8 power, this car is something to lust after.

[edit] Phi Tau Beta

Phi Tau Beta is a funky, experimental jam band from Alpharetta, GA, in which a mix of hard rock and punk clash with reggae acoustic jazz.

BIO: The original creators of the band, Joe Winograd (A.K.A. Ja-Lopy) and Corey Walker, begin experimenting with some bass riffs and drum fills in 2002. The original band name was "Cannibal Surplus," and thus, the band was created.

The start of 2003, Cannibal Surplus was looking for a guitarist, and they found good friend Brian O' Saben. They began to play Blink-182 covers, along with some oldies. Their first "show" was a talent show, in which the band played "Reckless Abandon" by Blink-182. In the next year, Cannibal Surplus changed their name to "Poss!" which is hebrew for 'band.' They tried a new song for the 2004 talent show. Poss! played "American Idiot" by Green Day.

During the summer of 2005, Poss! met guitarists Andrew Rose and Nate Simone, who were already experimenting with funk and metal. Also, the band changed their name to "Phi Tau Beta." The name is the greek letters that stand for FTB, or Forbid The Bacon.

As of 2006, Phi Tau Beta was recording. Their first and only two recorded originals are "Chinchilla," an up-beat jam song similar to those of the Red Hot Chili Peppers, and the other song is "Organ Donor," a hard and heavy rock song with an organ intro to begin the mood.

[edit] Take Strokes Off Your Game by Practicing Katherine Robert's Yoga for Golfers ™

Take Strokes Off Your Game by Practicing Katherine Robert's Yoga for Golfers ™

Toronto, Ontario, May 10, 2006 — Golfers in Toronto who are trying Yoga For Golfers™ classes instructed by Debbie Horovitch – Toronto’s first yoga instructor certified personally by Katherine Roberts in her Scottsdale, Arizona location – are reporting dramatic increases in flexibility & strength, more balance & power in their swing that immediately helps reduce the number strokes per round.

Mike, a Yoga For Golfers™ student at the Adelaide Club recently shared his Yoga For Golfers™ success story: "I’m currently playing to a 12 handicap, drive the ball 265-270 on average. After just one class with Yoga for Golfers, I found two major improvements in two consecutive rounds. Specifically my short to mid iron game, without even knowing it, I was able to get the club to the top of my back swing with ease and in combination with the breathing exercises (again subconsciously) recoil my body with an effortless tempo….key result was my ability to control ball flight, high-low what ever the situation required. Both rounds I scored 5 strokes better than average, but maybe the best part of all is an increased confidence level over the golf shot. For the record I’m not a gadget, watch video’s how to improve your game type guy, I just like to go out and play. What intrigued me about this was that I’ve always had an interest in Yoga (primarily for the long to term benefits) but never the courage nor the time, as a lover of the game, simply attaching the word Golf to it and concentration of the “core” (which is the golf swing), was enough for me to try it.”

The unique Yoga For Golfers™ program has been featured in Golf Magazine, GolfOnline.com, Golf For Women and The Golf Channel. The launch of Yoga For Golfers™ in Toronto was first announced in The National Post (March 11, ‘06) and has since been featured in Centre of The City Magazine (April ’06) and will be seen in upcoming issues of FAME Fitness & Lifestyle Magazine (May ‘06), Ruby Magazine (May ‘06) and on CFRB 1010 The John Donabie Show on May 14, ’06.

Golfers everywhere - of all ability levels - are using yoga to increase flexibility and enjoy improved fitness both on and off the course. Yoga, as a component of physical and mental conditioning, continues to take the PGA Tour by storm as one of the golf world's hottest fitness tools. PGA Tour pros Brad Faxon, Jonathan Kaye, Andrew Magee, Gary McCord, JL Lewis, Aaron Baddely, David Gossett, Ty Tryon, Chip Beck and the LPGA's Julie Inkster, Jill McGill, and Betsy King are leading the way in promoting the benefits that golfers can reap from incorporating yoga into their golf fitness plan.

Golfers have praised Roberts' Yoga For Golfers™ program for delivering a wide range of benefits including better performance on the course and better health off the course.

Students practising Yoga For Golfers™ experience these benefits: Improved flexibility and strength = Greater distance and accuracy off the tee Enhanced breathing awareness = Teaching rhythm and tempo in the golf swing Quieter mind = Increased concentration and visualization capabilities Improved overall fitness = Reduced risk of injury and recovery time Increased sense of balance = More effective club control/weight distribution

Yoga For Golfers™ group classes dive deeper into the wide variety of yoga postures each of which have golf-specific benefits - to help you develop the strength, flexibility & balance you'll want, to play better this year than ever before!

Students who are ready to experience the awesome benefits of yoga on their game and life can try a class in the following ways / GTA locations: • Debbie Horovitch is available to lead groups through at your corporate or private tournament, group size from 4 – 200: minimum $250/day; determined by number of students • Private on-site classes throughout the GTA, evenings & weekends: 4 classes = $300 • FAME Fitness And Model Expo 2006, Yoga For GolfersTM demonstrations and Workshops throughout the June 17 & 18 weekend at the International Centre: $25 - $45 per class www.FAMEevents.com • Group classes are open to everyone (non-members are welcomed) at downtown gyms, rates vary: $10 - $30 per class; see www.YogaForGolfers.net for schedule & locations • Complementary Class Passes & YFG Prize Packs available for tournaments: FREE

The First Tee stretch sequence utilizes the golf cart and clubs. These postures should be done before, during and after the round. Keep the muscles loose by stretching continuously throughout the round. You will be more consistent, have more speed and power in the swing and maintain the necessary endurance.

Downward Dog with Golf Cart:

This pose warms up the shoulders, low back, hamstrings and the Achilles tendons. This pose supports push-off power and a solid foundation. Facing the front of the cart, place the hands wider than shoulder width apart. Step the feet back, creating a ninety degree angle in the hips. Roll the shoulders back away from the ears and flex the quads. Hold for five breaths.

Warrior Crescent Lunge:

Working the hip flexors, psoas, quads and gluts, give more extension and power by supporting full hip extension. Bringing the left leg onto the back of the cart, come up onto the right toes. Engage the right buttocks and press the right hip towards the cart.

Seated Twist:

This is a great pose to keep the core and shoulders loose-a great pose to be done at every hole! Bring the body to the edge of the seat, sitting up as straight as possible. Bring the left hand to the right knee and the right hand behind you to increase the intensity. Hold for five breaths and switch sides.

[edit] Stevie Williams

Stevie Williams is professional skateboarder belonging to the Dirty Ghetto Kids (DGK) skateboard team. He was born on December 17th, 1979 in Philadelphia. He is known in skate circles as one of the greatest street skaters of all-time.

Williams discovered skateboarding when some kids made a bet that they could pick any stranger and teach them how to ollie. Stevie was only ten years old when the kids picked him and in forty minutes he was ollieing curbs. After taking the bet and shutting up the skate kids, young Stevie and his board became one. When a friend of his invited him to Philly's Love Park, Stevie found the place that would mold him into the skater he is today.

It was at Love Park that Stevie met future star Josh Kalis and their friendship marked a new era in street skateboarding. Kalis wanted to change the sport of skateboarding, so he packed up for San Francisco and he knew Stevie would help him do it. At the young age of thirteen, with barely any money and a desire to pursue a dream, Stevie hitchhiked to Califronia, to try and become a professional skateboarder. Arriving in San Francisco, he quickly learned how to live and survive on the streets. He lived and practiced with a number of skaters including Kalis and moved into a run-down apartment with six other kids.

Now 25 years old


[edit] THE “FIGHT FOR RIGHT” CAMPAIGN

The “Fight For Right” was the beginning of the ‘Human Rights Movement’ as we know them today. It was the first “Campaign for Human Rights” that actively used and popularized use of the term ‘Human Rights” in 1915. Before the second world war that expression was not in use. It was launched, somewhat improbably, by a noted imperialist, Colonel Sir Francis Edward Younghusband (31 May 1863 - 31 July 1942) who is, better known for his invasion of Tibet in 1904.

The Fight for Right campaign commissioned the hymn “Jerusalem” as its anthem. It was assembled from a poem by William Blake from the preface to his work “Milton: a Poem” (1804). The music was written by C. Hubert and H. Parry in 1916. The most famous version was written by Sir Edward Elgar in 1922.

This commission achieved its goal of being an inspiration to the human rights movement and has become one of England's most popular patriotic songs, often being used as an alternative anthem and is the official anthem of the British National Party and the British Women's Institute. Historically it was sung at public gatherings of the National Union of Suffrage Societies, in their “Fight for Equality and Right,” and today it is sung at the beginning of English Cricket and Rugby League matches as well as other British sporting events

The poem was inspired by the “Da Vinci Code” style legend that Jesus accompanied Joseph of Arimathea to Glastonbury. This is a legend that both Blake and Younghusband firmly believed in. There is some speculation about the line, “Among those dark Satanic mills?” as possibly referring to the Pagan origins of Britton, yet both Blake and Younghusband had sympathetic Pagan leanings. Given the purpose that the song was commissioned for, it is generally accepted as indicating any organization that suppressed human rights with the implied allegory that ‘Christ Consciousness’ will overcome human rights violations in the end. Sporting fans who sing this hymn at competitions see this line as referring to the opposing team. The title of the film “Chariots of Fire” was taken from a line in this hymn which says : "Bring me my chariot of fire"

Contemporary versions have been recorded by the British pop-novelty Fat Les, The Pet Shop Boys, Emerson Lake and Palmer, singer Bruce Dickinson from Iron Maiden, The Fall, Billy Bragg and composer Robert Steadman. In the United States, the music has been set to American patriotic lyrics which was most notably performed at Ronald Reagan's funeral.

LYRICS And did those feet in ancient time Walk upon England's mountains green? And was the holy Lamb of God On England's pleasant pastures seen? And did the Countenance Divine Shine forth upon our clouded hills? And was Jerusalem builded here Among those dark Satanic mills?

Bring me my bow of burning gold! Bring me my arrows of desire! Bring me my spear! O clouds, unfold! Bring me my chariot of fire! I will not cease from mental fight Nor shall my sword sleep in my hand Till we have built Jerusalem In England's green and pleasant land
