Additional References:- French, Patrick. 1994. “Younghusband: The Last Great Imperial Adventurer.” Harper Collins, Great Britain. 1994 Chapter 19- Reprint: 1995. Candler, Edmund “The Unveiling of Lhasa.” Thomas Nelson and Sons Ltd 1905

220.239.190.173 02:07, 22 May 2006 (UTC)© Copyright Rev. Dr. S. D’Montford. Monday, May 22, 2006 Sydney Australia220.239.190.173 02:07, 22 May 2006 (UTC)

The Escanaba & Lake Superior Railroad was founded in 1899 to serve the thriving lumber industry of the Central Upper Peninsula of Michigan.

Bold text Original mainline and Escanaba branchBold text

The railroad's original mainline was built from Wells, Michigan to Watson, Michigan; then extended from Watson to Channing, Michigan and a connection with the Milwaukee Road. Communities served along the original mainline include Cornell, Watson, and Ralph. There were also several short logging branch-lines off the mainline which have been abandoned for decades.

Besides hauling sawlogs, passengers, and general freight, the E & LS also served as host to the Milwaukee Road's ore trains. The Milwaukee Road operated an isolated ore-dock facility in Escanaba, Michigan until the 1930's, and ran over the E & LS to get to it from the mines of the Menominee Iron Range.

After the Milwaukee Road abandoned their ore-docks, the E & LS remained a profitable line serving local customers. A branch-line was built from Flat Rock Jct. near Escanaba River dam #1, to downtown Escanaba. This served dozens of customers in the Escanaba area, and would be the backbone of the E & LS for years to come. The P & H crane factory in Escanaba would become the major customer along this branch. The Escanaba Paper Company, adjacent to Groos Yard in Escanaba, would also be a major E & LS customer for years to come.

In the late 1950's, the E & LS dropped passenger service from their railroad. Due to highway construction and lack of revenue, it was no longer profitable to operate mixed trains.

In the 1970's, after a strike at the Escanaba Paper Company, the E & LS lost it's contract to provide service to the mill. The spur into the mill was removed, and the E & LS faced hard times for the near future. The closing of the P & H factory in Escanaba heightened the problem. The Soo Line began handling all freight for the Escanaba Paper Company (then Mead Papers, now New Page). Other customers along the mainline and Escanaba branch also ceased shipping by rail, until only a few customers were left.

The closing of the P & H factory was initially negative, but the E & LS purchased 2 builings at the former factory, and coverted one into a state of the art freight-car repair shop. They now handle repairs for a large ELS leasing fleet, as well as repairs for foreign railroads and leasing fleets. The carshop is now the primary source of traffic for the E & LS in the Escanaba area.

Other customers on the Escanaba branch and mainline have all but faded away, however. In fact, the only active customer in Escanaba as of 2006 is DeCock propane, just south of Flat Rock Jct. on the Escanaba branch. The southernmost mile of the branch, once very busy, has been removed. The last active customer along this stretch was Coplin's scrapyard in Escanaba.

Customers along the mainline have also faded, and the E & LS ran their last thru-train along the original mainline in the early 1990's. They now have trackage rights over the CN to reach the Escanaba area. The original mainline is active from Wells to Cornell, and from Ralph to Channing; but the portion in the middle has not seen a train in over a decade.

Bold textWells shopsBold text

In contrast to the modern carshops at the old P & H factory, the shops at Wells near Escanaba date to the beginning of the railroad. The complex consists of 2 roundhouses back-to-back, a 2-stall carshop, a machine-shop, and a depot/office building. The south-roundhouse, machine-shop, and offices are still active. All moderate to heavy locomotive repairs for the railroad are handled at the south-roundhouse. The roundhouse is beleived to be the last in the Upper Peninsula of Michigan.

In addition to the original buildings, the E & LS purchased a former sawmill building north of the yard in Wells, and coverted this into a sandblast and paint shop. They currently repaint their own equipment, as well as equipment for foreign railroads and leasing companies there.

A large collection of inoperable locomotives are also stored at Wells shops. These locomotives represent one of the largest collections of Baldwin diesels anywhere.

Bold text1980 aquisitionBold text

In 1980, the E & LS purchased hundreds of miles of former Milwaukee Road track in northern Wisconsin and Upper Michigan. These lines stretched from Green Bay, Wis. to Republic, Mich.; Channing, Mich. to Ontonagon, Mich.; and Crivitz, Wis. to Marinette, Wis.

In addition to these mainlines, the E & LS aquired an isolated branch-line in Menominee, Mich. and the Groveland Mine branch near Sagola, Mich.

The E & LS also purchased a branch-line for Sidnaw, Mich. to Nestoria, Mich. in the mid-1990's from the Wisconsin Central Railraod. This line saw very little use, and is now still intact but only used for car storage. The E & LS also purchased a short ex-CNW branch-line from Stiles Jct., Wis. to Oconto Falls, Wis. which sees regular use, serving several shippers in Oconto Falls.

The ex-Milwaukee Road track, however, is now the backbone of the E & LS. The primary customers providing the railroad with freight are Smurfit-Stone Container in Ontonagon, Mich. and Lousiana-Pacific in Sagola, Mich. Several customers are also served in Marinette, Wis., including Kimberley Clark Papers. In Menominee, Mich. the E & LS served the K & K Warehouse, Great Lakes Pulp & Fiber, and the Menominee Papers mill. Several other customers along these lines also generate significant traffic.

Although greatly expanded, the E & LS also regained it's traditional role as a logging railroad when these lines weree aquired. Pulpwood and sawlogs are loaded at several location along the ex-Milwaukee Road tracks, and shipped to papermills and sawmills throughout the midwest.

Bold textDepotsBold text

The E & LS has many old depots along it's tracks, some owned by the railroad and some not. Here is a list of those beleived to be standing, some still active for railroad use as noted:

Escanaba, Michigan; inactive; along abandoned portion of Escanaba branch; private business Wells, Michigan; active; adjacent to Wells yard; offices for railroad N. Escanaba, Michigan; inactive, along Escanaba branch, office of Bichler Concrete Channing, Michigan; active; adjacent to Channing Yard Randville, Michigan; inactive; private home Iron Mountain, Michigan; inactive; downtown Iron Mountain, owned by railroad (?) Pembine, Wisconsin; inactive; at diamond where ELS crosses WC Crivitz, Wisconsin; active; adjacent to Y, unknown use Stiles Jct., Wisconsin; inactive; adjacent to former diamond, very poor condition Amasa, Michigan; inactive Ontonagon, Michigan; active; adjacent to Ontonagon Yard, agent's office Marinette, Wisconsin; inactive; private business, former ELS agent's office

Bold textCar storageBold text

Besides revenue freight and car repairs, the E & LS also gains revenue by providing storage service for freight-cars. When cars are not needed by large leasing companies, the E & LS will store cars for a fee on unused tracks.

Common places to see storage cars are the mainline from Channing to Witch Lake, Michigan; the branch from Sidnaw to Watton, Michigan; the mainline from Escanaba to Cornell, Michigan; the Groveland Mine branch near Sagola, Michigan; and the mainline from Channing to Ralph, Michigan. Cars are also stored on unused sidings and yard tracks throughout the system.

Bold textLocomotivesBold text

The E & LS is famous for Baldwins, but as of 2006 only 2 of these diesels are active; RS12 #300 and DS-4-4-1000 #202. The rest are stored inactive around Escanaba. #300 is seldom used.

The core of the E & LS fleet is now EMD locomotives, but the fleet is still very unique.

FP7 #600 wears Wisconsin & Southern paint, and can be seen in regular freight service. SD9's #1220-1224 wear Reserve Mining paint, but only #1221, 1223, and 1224 are active in regular service. GP38's #400 & 401 are used; 400 in ELS paint and 401 in Conrail paint. SD40-2's #500 & 501 round-out the roster, both in EMD-leasing paint.

Another often overlooked member of the E & LS is Plymouth switcher #1, which is usually found switching the rip-track at Crivitz yard.

[edit] Escanaba & Lake Superior Railroad

The Escanaba & Lake Superior Railroad was founded in 1899 to serve the thriving lumber industry of the Central Upper Peninsula of Michigan.

Bold text Original mainline and Escanaba branchBold text

The railroad's original mainline was built from Wells, Michigan to Watson, Michigan; then extended from Watson to Channing, Michigan and a connection with the Milwaukee Road. Communities served along the original mainline include Cornell, Watson, and Ralph. There were also several short logging branch-lines off the mainline which have been abandoned for decades.

Besides hauling sawlogs, passengers, and general freight, the E & LS also served as host to the Milwaukee Road's ore trains. The Milwaukee Road operated an isolated ore-dock facility in Escanaba, Michigan until the 1930's, and ran over the E & LS to get to it from the mines of the Menominee Iron Range.

After the Milwaukee Road abandoned their ore-docks, the E & LS remained a profitable line serving local customers. A branch-line was built from Flat Rock Jct. near Escanaba River dam #1, to downtown Escanaba. This served dozens of customers in the Escanaba area, and would be the backbone of the E & LS for years to come. The P & H crane factory in Escanaba would become the major customer along this branch. The Escanaba Paper Company, adjacent to Groos Yard in Escanaba, would also be a major E & LS customer for years to come.

In the late 1950's, the E & LS dropped passenger service from their railroad. Due to highway construction and lack of revenue, it was no longer profitable to operate mixed trains.

In the 1970's, after a strike at the Escanaba Paper Company, the E & LS lost it's contract to provide service to the mill. The spur into the mill was removed, and the E & LS faced hard times for the near future. The closing of the P & H factory in Escanaba heightened the problem. The Soo Line began handling all freight for the Escanaba Paper Company (then Mead Papers, now New Page). Other customers along the mainline and Escanaba branch also ceased shipping by rail, until only a few customers were left.

The closing of the P & H factory was initially negative, but the E & LS purchased 2 builings at the former factory, and coverted one into a state of the art freight-car repair shop. They now handle repairs for a large ELS leasing fleet, as well as repairs for foreign railroads and leasing fleets. The carshop is now the primary source of traffic for the E & LS in the Escanaba area.

Other customers on the Escanaba branch and mainline have all but faded away, however. In fact, the only active customer in Escanaba as of 2006 is DeCock propane, just south of Flat Rock Jct. on the Escanaba branch. The southernmost mile of the branch, once very busy, has been removed. The last active customer along this stretch was Coplin's scrapyard in Escanaba.

Customers along the mainline have also faded, and the E & LS ran their last thru-train along the original mainline in the early 1990's. They now have trackage rights over the CN to reach the Escanaba area. The original mainline is active from Wells to Cornell, and from Ralph to Channing; but the portion in the middle has not seen a train in over a decade.

Bold textWells shopsBold text

In contrast to the modern carshops at the old P & H factory, the shops at Wells near Escanaba date to the beginning of the railroad. The complex consists of 2 roundhouses back-to-back, a 2-stall carshop, a machine-shop, and a depot/office building. The south-roundhouse, machine-shop, and offices are still active. All moderate to heavy locomotive repairs for the railroad are handled at the south-roundhouse. The roundhouse is beleived to be the last in the Upper Peninsula of Michigan.

In addition to the original buildings, the E & LS purchased a former sawmill building north of the yard in Wells, and coverted this into a sandblast and paint shop. They currently repaint their own equipment, as well as equipment for foreign railroads and leasing companies there.

A large collection of inoperable locomotives are also stored at Wells shops. These locomotives represent one of the largest collections of Baldwin diesels anywhere.

Bold text1980 aquisitionBold text

In 1980, the E & LS purchased hundreds of miles of former Milwaukee Road track in northern Wisconsin and Upper Michigan. These lines stretched from Green Bay, Wis. to Republic, Mich.; Channing, Mich. to Ontonagon, Mich.; and Crivitz, Wis. to Marinette, Wis.

In addition to these mainlines, the E & LS aquired an isolated branch-line in Menominee, Mich. and the Groveland Mine branch near Sagola, Mich.

The E & LS also purchased a branch-line for Sidnaw, Mich. to Nestoria, Mich. in the mid-1990's from the Wisconsin Central Railraod. This line saw very little use, and is now still intact but only used for car storage. The E & LS also purchased a short ex-CNW branch-line from Stiles Jct., Wis. to Oconto Falls, Wis. which sees regular use, serving several shippers in Oconto Falls.

The ex-Milwaukee Road track, however, is now the backbone of the E & LS. The primary customers providing the railroad with freight are Smurfit-Stone Container in Ontonagon, Mich. and Lousiana-Pacific in Sagola, Mich. Several customers are also served in Marinette, Wis., including Kimberley Clark Papers. In Menominee, Mich. the E & LS served the K & K Warehouse, Great Lakes Pulp & Fiber, and the Menominee Papers mill. Several other customers along these lines also generate significant traffic.

Although greatly expanded, the E & LS also regained it's traditional role as a logging railroad when these lines weree aquired. Pulpwood and sawlogs are loaded at several location along the ex-Milwaukee Road tracks, and shipped to papermills and sawmills throughout the midwest.

Bold textDepotsBold text

The E & LS has many old depots along it's tracks, some owned by the railroad and some not. Here is a list of those beleived to be standing, some still active for railroad use as noted:

Escanaba, Michigan; inactive; along abandoned portion of Escanaba branch; private business Wells, Michigan; active; adjacent to Wells yard; offices for railroad N. Escanaba, Michigan; inactive, along Escanaba branch, office of Bichler Concrete Channing, Michigan; active; adjacent to Channing Yard Randville, Michigan; inactive; private home Iron Mountain, Michigan; inactive; downtown Iron Mountain, owned by railroad (?) Pembine, Wisconsin; inactive; at diamond where ELS crosses WC Crivitz, Wisconsin; active; adjacent to Y, unknown use Stiles Jct., Wisconsin; inactive; adjacent to former diamond, very poor condition Amasa, Michigan; inactive Ontonagon, Michigan; active; adjacent to Ontonagon Yard, agent's office Marinette, Wisconsin; inactive; private business, former ELS agent's office

Bold textCar storageBold text

Besides revenue freight and car repairs, the E & LS also gains revenue by providing storage service for freight-cars. When cars are not needed by large leasing companies, the E & LS will store cars for a fee on unused tracks.

Common places to see storage cars are the mainline from Channing to Witch Lake, Michigan; the branch from Sidnaw to Watton, Michigan; the mainline from Escanaba to Cornell, Michigan; the Groveland Mine branch near Sagola, Michigan; and the mainline from Channing to Ralph, Michigan. Cars are also stored on unused sidings and yard tracks throughout the system.

Bold textLocomotivesBold text

The E & LS is famous for Baldwins, but as of 2006 only 2 of these diesels are active; RS12 #300 and DS-4-4-1000 #202. The rest are stored inactive around Escanaba. #300 is seldom used.

The core of the E & LS fleet is now EMD locomotives, but the fleet is still very unique.

FP7 #600 wears Wisconsin & Southern paint, and can be seen in regular freight service. SD9's #1220-1224 wear Reserve Mining paint, but only #1221, 1223, and 1224 are active in regular service. GP38's #400 & 401 are used; 400 in ELS paint and 401 in Conrail paint. SD40-2's #500 & 501 round-out the roster, both in EMD-leasing paint.

Another often overlooked member of the E & LS is Plymouth switcher #1, which is usually found switching the rip-track at Crivitz yard.

[edit] Nathan Summers - A Glimpse of Perfection

Nathan Alan Summers was born and raised in Rochester, New York. Growing up in suburban West Irondequoit, Nathan (now commonly known as "Nate"), made friends with other children his age in his neighborhood. Nathan and his friends passed time playing a myriad of sports; including soccer, street hockey, football, and track. Then, at nearly thirteen (13) years old, Nathan and his family moved from their home in Rochester, New York, to their current home in Kingsport, Tennessee. Since graduating high school, Nathan now attends the University of Tennessee at Knoxville, where he is majoring in Biomedical Engineering. There, he plays on the school's club ultimate frisbee team and enjoys a game of disc golf every now and then. Nathan recently acquired a new five string Schecter bass guitar, which he greatly enjoys. The future holds many promises for Nathan Summers. He is considering attending medical school after graduating from UT, but sees graduate school for engineering as a possibility as well. No one knows for sure what the future may bring, but we may rest assured that Nathan Summers will be a part of it.

[edit] Annapolis West Education Centre

Annapolis West Education Centre is a high school grades nine through twelve in Annapolis Royal, Nova Scotia. It is built on a swamp.
